<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel checks of the administration of value added tax between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic carried out in 2005</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The presented material informs about the progress and results of the parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of the administration of value added tax and the use of the information system VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System).</seg>
<seg id="4">In May 2004, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic joined the European Union, so the revenue from value added tax affects not only the state budgets of both countries, but also the budget of the European Union as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="5">The parallel control actions were aimed in particular at checking the procedure of the tax administrators when checking the amount of value added tax paid in commercial transactions carried out between individual Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="6">The introduction of the VIES system enabled the electronic exchange of information on the registration of VAT payers in individual Member States of the European Union and on commercial transactions carried out by these payers.</seg>
<seg id="7">The discrepancy between the data in the VIES system and the data in the tax return for value added tax submitted by the payer should alert the tax administrator to suspicious cases and allow the detection of tax evasion or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="8">The benefit of the parallel audits was not only in the exchange of information on the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax, but especially in the verification of the use of the VIES system when auditing the application of the right to exemption from value added tax on intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="9">The knowledge gained during the implementation of the parallel audits is beneficial for the development of mutual cooperation and will be used in the implementation of other parallel audits in cooperation with audit institutions of the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the results of the parallel audits of the Value Added Tax administration for the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Audit number: (CZ) 05/19 (SK) 22/2005</seg>
<seg id="13">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration, (SK) Audit of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of Value Added Tax and the fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States</seg>
<seg id="14">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as “SAO, CR”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as “SAO SR”) concluded on 12.9.2005 the Agreement on Cooperation in Audit Activities.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the Agreement was the cooperation in the performed parallel auditing operations “Value Added Tax Administration”, included in the audit plan of the SAO, CR for 2005 under No. 05/19 and “Audit of the procedure of tax authorities in the administration, control and enforcement of Value Added Tax and fulfilment of tasks within the VIES system on the exchange of information between EU Member Landscapes”, included in the audit plan of the SAO SR under No. 22/2005.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel auditing operations had the character of a coordinated audit.</seg>
<seg id="17">The result of the joint coordinated audit was prepared in the sense of the European Enforcement Regulation No. 31 for the INTOSAI auditing standards.</seg>
<seg id="18">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent stipulated by the concluded contract and in the preparation of a joint final report on the result of the parallel audits.</seg>
<seg id="19">The purpose of the coordinated audit was to verify selected cases of delivery and acquisition of goods in suspicious commercial transactions between value added tax payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as “the Czech Republic”) and the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as “the Slovak Republic”).</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties contractually undertook to provide each other with information from public sources, from the VIES (Value Added Tax Information Exchange System) electronic system and data on received and sent requests to verify commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="21">The audits were carried out in parallel between June and December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic, the audits were carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of Central Bohemia, North West Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the Ministry of Finance and 12 financial offices: the Financial Office in Mladá Boleslav, the Financial Office in Kolín, the Financial Office in Teplice, the Financial Office in Karlovy Vary, the Financial Office in Tábor, the Financial Office in Brno III, the Financial Office in Znojmo, the Financial Office in Zlín, the Financial Office in Šumperk, the Financial Office in Ostrava I, the Financial Office for Prague 7 and the Financial Office for Prague 9.</seg>
<seg id="24">The audits in the territory of the Slovak Republic were carried out by the Financial and Tax Section of the SAO of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the Expoziturami of the SAO of the Slovak Republic Banská Bystrica and Košice at 9 selected tax offices: the Tax Office of Bratislava I, the Tax Office of Komárno, the Tax Office of Trenčín, the Tax Office of Prievidza, the Tax Office of Zvolen, the Tax Office of Dolný Kubín, the Tax Office of Košice II, the Tax Office of Košice V and the Tax Office of Michalovce.</seg>
<seg id="25">Objective of the audits:</seg>
<seg id="26">The aim of the parallel audits was to examine the procedure of the financial and tax authorities in the administration of value added tax (hereinafter "VAT") after the integration of the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter "EU") and to examine the use of the electronic information system VIES, in particular when checking the application of the VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="27">The audited coordinated inspection period covered the period from 1.5.2004 to 30.6.2005.</seg>
<seg id="28">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel control actions An electronic VIES system is in place in EU Member States to allow tax authorities to check whether the supplier has been authorised to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and to check in the country of destination whether the purchaser has duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="29">The VIES system is not centralised within the EU, with each Member State developing its own system.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit found differences in national VIES systems in the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="31">The values of supplies of goods to other EU Member States are reported in the recapitulative statements, the values of services provided are not included in the recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="32">The data from the recapitulative statements submitted by Czech payers are processed in the Czech Republic at the level of the tax authorities, where they are compared with the data on supplies of goods to other EU Member States included in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="33">The tax authorities transmit the data from the recapitulative statements to the Ministry of Finance (CLO), which sends them to other EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="34">In the Slovak Republic, the data from the recapitulative statements submitted by Slovak payers to the tax authorities are only converted into electronic form and processed centrally at the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic (CLO).</seg>
<seg id="35">In the Czech Republic, payers report the value of supplies of goods and the value of supplies of services to other EU Member States on separate lines of the VAT returns, which allows to compare the values stated in the recapitulative statements with the values of supplies of goods according to the VAT returns and to identify their possible differences.</seg>
<seg id="36">In the SR, the values of supplies of goods and services to other EU Member States are reported summarily on a common line of VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="37">As a result, in the SR, the system does not make it possible to automatically identify the differences between the values of supplies of goods according to VAT returns and recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="38">Separate reporting of the values of supplies of goods in VAT returns makes it possible to use the results of data comparisons when checking the VAT exemption of supplies of goods to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="39">The delivered data from recapitulative statements submitted by payers in other EU Member States are processed at the Customs and compared with the value of acquisitions of goods stated by payers from the Czech Republic and the SR in VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="40">In the SR, these data are sent to the tax authorities and the tax authorities themselves decide which cases of differences to check.</seg>
<seg id="41">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance (CLO) determines which quantified differences between the values of supplies and acquisitions of goods must be checked by the tax authorities and transmits a list of these cases to the local tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="42">This ensures that for the most significant deviations, it will be checked whether the VAT was declared at the correct amount.</seg>
<seg id="43">The audit also highlighted some problems in the VAT administration system complications caused by different reporting of intra-Community transactions (i.e. supplies and acquisitions of goods effected by payers from different EU Member States):</seg>
<seg id="44">Summary reports are submitted in the EU for each calendar quarter and the maximum period for processing and sending the data to other EU Member States is set at 3 months from the end of the relevant quarter.</seg>
<seg id="45">Reducing the period for which summary reports are submitted to one month together with the shortening of the period for processing them would allow earlier access to the data in the VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="46">The tax administrators would thus be able to check more effectively whether the VAT was declared at the correct amount in intra-Community acquisitions.</seg>
<seg id="47">At the same time, the submission of VAT returns and recapitulative statements for the same tax period (month) would allow faster verification of whether the payer has declared identical values of supplies of goods to the EU in both the recapitulative statement and the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="48">The differences between the values of supplies of goods declared by EU taxpayers and the values of acquisitions of goods declared by Czech and Slovak taxpayers were due, among other things, to the different reporting of data on intra-Community supplies and acquisitions in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="49">These included, for example, the inclusion of received advances in the recapitulative statements, or the reporting of intra-Community supplies in the supplier's recapitulative statement in a different quarter than the intra-Community acquisitions in the tax return of the acquirer.</seg>
<seg id="50">The unification of the conditions for reporting these data within the EU would lead to more effective control activities of the tax administrations of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="51">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was also focused on the examination of selected intra-Community transactions carried out between the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">Together, a total of 40 cases of commercial transactions carried out between 29 Czech and 32 Slovak tax entities were examined, where there were doubts about their realisation or suspicion of VAT evasion.</seg>
<seg id="53">The SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of Slovakia found the following facts among others:</seg>
<seg id="54">tax entities reported in their VAT returns the realisation of intra-Community transactions, which did not actually take place, in order to obtain an excessive VAT deduction;</seg>
<seg id="55">tax entities reported intra-Community supplies within carousel shops, where there was a deliberate multiple reduction of the value of supplies in order to draw excessive VAT deductions;</seg>
<seg id="56">suppliers reported in their VAT returns and recapitulative reports the intra-Community supplies of goods exempt from VAT to the acquirers, who were so-called "lost companies" and did not declare the tax on the acquired goods;</seg>
<seg id="57">Suppliers made the intra-Community supply of goods exempt from VAT to tax subjects who were not registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="58">In these cases, the supply should not have been exempt from VAT and should have been subject to tax in the supplier's country;</seg>
<seg id="59">Suppliers declared in their VAT returns the intra-Community supply at a higher value than the intra-Community acquisition declared by the acquirers, while in some cases the VAT was declared at an incorrect amount.</seg>
<seg id="60">From the lessons learned in the audit operation, it emerged that the VIES system provides tax administrators with the information necessary to check the correct application of VAT in intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="61">Tax administrators should pay particular attention to rigorous verification of differences between the data reported by VAT payers and the data in the VIES system and the use of all information in tax proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="62">Value added tax issues after the accession of the Czech Republic and Slovakia to the EU</seg>
<seg id="63">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="64">On 1 May 2004, the Czech Republic and Slovakia became members of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="65">After the accession to the EU, internal borders and border controls on the movement of goods within the territory of the EU were abolished.</seg>
<seg id="66">The VAT administrator was the competent financial or tax office until 30 April 2004, with the exception of the importation of goods and occasional bus transport in the Czech Republic, where the tax administrator was the customs office.</seg>
<seg id="67">In connection with the adoption of the new Act No. 235/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 235/2004 Coll.”), or Act No. 222/2004 Coll., on Value Added Tax (hereinafter referred to as “Act No. 222/2004 Coll.”), the administration of VAT on the acquisition of goods and services (formerly imports) from other EU member countries passed from the customs offices to the financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="68">The supply of goods in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of § 13 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. means the transfer of the right to dispose of goods as owner.</seg>
<seg id="69">The supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another EU member state is the supply of goods that have actually been dispatched or transported to another EU member state.</seg>
<seg id="70">According to the provisions of § 64 of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. it is an exempt taxable transaction with the right to deduct VAT if the goods are supplied to a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="71">The supply of goods in the Slovak Republic according to the provisions of § 8 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll. means the supply of tangible property in which the ownership right is changed.</seg>
<seg id="72">The transfer of goods that are owned by a taxable person from the Czech Republic to another Member State is also considered as a supply of goods if these goods are dispatched or transported by that person or on his behalf to another Member State for the purposes of his business.</seg>
<seg id="73">According to the provisions of § 43 of Act No. 222/2004 Coll. the supply of goods from the Czech Republic to another Member State is exempt from VAT if the acquirer is a person identified for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="74">Acquisition of goods from another EU Member State in the Czech Republic according to the provisions of § 16 of Act No 235/2004 Coll. means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of goods that are sent or transported to the acquirer by a person registered for VAT in another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="75">A Czech taxpayer purchases goods at a price without VAT and his obligation in the Czech Republic is to declare VAT according to the provisions of § 25 of Act No 235/2004 Coll., if he fulfils the conditions set out in § 73 of this Act he becomes entitled to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="76">Acquisition of goods in the territory of the country from another EU Member State in the Slovak Republic according to the provisions of § 11 of Act No 222/2004 Z. means the acquisition of the right to dispose as owner of movable tangible property sent or transported to the acquirer by the supplier or the acquirer or on their behalf to the territory of the country from another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="77">Tax liability in the Slovak Republic arises for the taxpayer when acquiring goods in the territory of the country from another Member State according to the provisions of § 20 of Act No 222/2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="78">The payer can deduct VAT according to the provisions of § 49 of the Act No 222/2004 Z. z. if the tax is applied by him when acquiring goods in the Czech Republic from another Member State according to the provisions of §§ 11 and 11a of this Act.</seg>
<seg id="79">Trilateral trade means according to the provisions of § 17 of the Act No 235/2004 Coll. or § 45 of the Act No 222/2004 Z. trade concluded between three persons registered for VAT in three different EU Member States, where the object of the trade is the supply of the same goods between these three persons.</seg>
<seg id="80">Intracommunitary transactions means the supply and acquisition of goods effected between VAT payers from different EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="81">The total volumes of intracommunal transactions effected between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic are shown in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="82">VIES system</seg>
<seg id="83">In order to control the application of the right to exemption from VAT in intracommunal supplies of goods, a system of exchange of information in the field of VAT has been created within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="84">It includes the VIES electronic system, which allows tax authorities of the EU Member States to check whether the supplier was entitled to exempt the taxable transaction from VAT and vice versa, whether the acquirer duly declared and taxed the acquired goods.</seg>
<seg id="85">The VIES information system is not centralised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="86">Each Member State develops its own VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="87">The national systems work on a common principle and are interconnected through a common EU communication network, the so-called CCN (Common Communication Network; see diagram below).</seg>
<seg id="88">In the Czech Republic, the VIES system was interconnected with an automated tax information system (ADIS), in the Slovak Republic with the application software of the tax information system (APV DIS).</seg>
<seg id="89">These systems are used by the financial and tax authorities as technical support for executive and management activities in the administration of taxes and fees.</seg>
<seg id="90">International administrative cooperation</seg>
<seg id="91">Through international administrative cooperation, the tax administration of each EU member country obtains information about tax entities that it would not be able to obtain on its own without this cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="92">The main objective of international administrative cooperation is the fight against tax evasion and tax losses.</seg>
<seg id="93">According to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003, each Member State establishes within the internal organisational structure a central unit in the field of administrative cooperation between EU member states in the administration of VAT, the CLO (Central Liaison Office).</seg>
<seg id="94">In the Czech Republic, the Ministry of Finance – Central Financial and Tax Directorate, where the Department of International Cooperation in the Administration of VAT (hereinafter referred to as "MF CLO") has been established, performs the duties of the CLO in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="95">The function of the CLO in the Slovak Republic is performed by the Tax Directorate of the Slovak Republic, the Department of International Administrative Cooperation (hereinafter referred to as "DR CLO").</seg>
<seg id="96">These departments, among other things, communicate with foreign EU administrations, especially in the area of information exchange within the framework of the VIES system, spontaneous information exchange and information exchange upon request of EU tax administrations, coordination of multilateral (simultaneous) tax inspections, verification of tax identification numbers (hereinafter referred to as the “DIČ”) of persons registered for VAT in other EU Member States and communicate with the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to verify a certain intra-community transaction or to obtain further information related to a particular tax entity, the financial and tax authorities send requests for information to the EU via the MF CLO or the DR CLO.</seg>
<seg id="98">Through these requests, they obtain information from the requested Member States that they can use for the correct determination of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="99">Requests for information are sent between the CLOs of EU Member States mostly in electronic form, using the SCAC standardized form.</seg>
<seg id="100">Selected audit findings during verification of commercial transactions</seg>
<seg id="101">The cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO SR was focused mainly on the verification of selected intra-community transactions carried out between the two states and on the level of use of information obtained through international cooperation by financial or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="102">The SAO, the Czech Republic, requested the SAO SR to verify in 30 cases commercial transactions carried out between 19 Czech and 25 Slovak tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="103">The SAO SR requested the SAO, the Czech Republic to verify in 10 cases commercial transactions carried out between 7 Slovak and 10 Czech tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="104">The verification of intra-community transactions revealed, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="105">o</seg>
<seg id="106">The SAO, the Czech Republic asked the SAO SR to verify the procedure of the tax administrator, to whom a reply to the request for information was sent.</seg>
<seg id="107">The Slovak tax office requested through the form SCAC to verify the delivery of goods (footwear) in the 3rd quarter of 2004 from a Slovak payer in the value of 2 847 thousand CZK.</seg>
<seg id="108">The tax office in the Czech Republic replied that the Czech payer stated the acquisition of goods in this amount only in the additional VAT return and delivered the same goods back to Slovak tax entities in the amount of 2 550 thousand CZK by the end of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="109">Based on the international cooperation of the SAO, the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic, it was found that the locally competent tax office recognized the Slovak supplier in its entirety as entitled to an excessive VAT deduction incurred, among other things, on the basis of this supply.</seg>
<seg id="110">The tax office did not provide information about the suspicion of re-export to the tax authorities of locally competent customers of goods imported back from the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="111">These facts will be an incentive for further verification of commercial activities in connection with possible carousel fraud.</seg>
<seg id="112">o</seg>
<seg id="113">The Czech tax administrator asked through the SCAC form for verification of the supply of a technological line to the Slovak Republic in the amount of 4 850 thousand CZK in the 2nd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="114">The tax proceedings conducted in the Slovak Republic revealed that only a part of the technological line was delivered, the components worth CZK 3,395,000 were not delivered.</seg>
<seg id="115">The SAO of the Slovak Republic, when examining this case, found that the VAT on the effected taxable transaction was declared by the Slovak tax entity on the amount of CZK 4,850,000 in the VAT return (hereinafter referred to as "DAP") for the tax period 7/2004.</seg>
<seg id="116">The SAO of the Czech Republic also found that the Czech tax payer declared an excess VAT deduction of CZK 655,000 in its DAP for the aforementioned quarter, which arose from the application of the VAT deduction on the purchase of this technological line from another domestic payer.</seg>
<seg id="117">The Czech Tax Office concluded on the basis of the results of the investigation that the Czech and Slovak tax entities had established a business relationship for the purpose of obtaining an excess VAT deduction, questioned the realisation of the taxable transaction and did not recognise the Czech payer's part of the right to deduct the tax amounting to CZK 647,000.</seg>
<seg id="118">o</seg>
<seg id="119">In 2004, the Slovak Tax Administration applied through the SCAC form for verification of the supply of goods (copying machines) to the Czech payer amounting to SKK 24,246,000 effected in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="120">The Slovak payer purchased these goods in November 2002 in Slovakia from another tax entity amounting to SKK 29,667,000 and subsequently sold them to the Czech payer.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Slovak tax entity claimed an excess VAT deduction for the relevant tax period.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the tax investigation carried out in the Czech Republic, it was found that the Czech tax entity did not cooperate with the Tax Administration and did not submit a DAP for the 4th quarter of 2002 or for the following period.</seg>
<seg id="123">The SAO found that the Slovak Tax Administration did not recognise the right to an excess deduction amounting to SKK 5,541,000 effected in the DAP for the month of 11/2002 and determined the tax liability amounting to SKK 1,750,000.</seg>
<seg id="124">At the same time, the tax entity was not granted an exemption from VAT in respect of the export of goods in December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="125">o</seg>
<seg id="126">The Czech tax administrator received an order from the MF CLO to verify the value of the acquired goods for the 3rd quarter of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="127">According to VIES data, the Czech payer was supposed to acquire goods (diluent) from the SR in the value of 3,767 thousand Sk.</seg>
<seg id="128">This tax entity did not cooperate with the tax administrator, it did not submit the DAP and the VAT for the months of 7 to 12/2004 was charged to it ex officio in the amount of 0 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="129">The Czech tax administrator asked through the SCAC form to verify whether deliveries of goods from the SR to the Czech Republic took place, in what amount and price (according to invoices).</seg>
<seg id="130">The Slovak tax office with local jurisdiction sent a copy of the invoice, waybills and an invitation to pay the invoice.</seg>
<seg id="131">The SAO SR found that the Slovak payer was granted an exemption with the right to deduct VAT on this delivery.</seg>
<seg id="132">The SAO, Czech Republic found that the Czech tax administrator evaluated the reply to the request for information received from the SR as evidence that the company had acquired goods from another EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="133">Based on further investigation, the tax office in the Czech Republic will ask the superior authority to review the tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="134">o</seg>
<seg id="135">The Slovak company supplied goods (particle board products) to, among others, an American company that deposited these goods in the Czech Republic in a free customs zone.</seg>
<seg id="136">The operator of this free customs zone was listed on the invoices as the recipient of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="137">In 2004, the American company, for example, purchased from the Slovak payer particle board tiles worth 57 600 USD (at a unit price of 100 USD/piece), which it placed in a free customs zone.</seg>
<seg id="138">Subsequently, the company transferred ownership rights to the goods to the Swiss company in the amount of 14 400 USD (a unit price of 25 USD/piece) and the goods were exported back to the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="139">The goods were not unloaded in the Czech Republic, but left the area of the free customs zone on the same means of transport.</seg>
<seg id="140">The Slovak tax administrator initiated tax inspections of the individual tax periods of 2004 and 2005 at the supplier of the goods on suspicion of carousel transactions.</seg>
<seg id="141">The verification of the underlying transactions was requested from the Czech locally competent tax administrators through several SCAC forms.</seg>
<seg id="142">Individual answers gradually created a picture of the transactions and confirmed the involvement of Slovak and Czech stakeholders in carousel transactions.</seg>
<seg id="143">The SAO, the Czech Republic in cooperation with the SAO of the Slovak Republic found that in these commercial relations the value of the goods was deliberately gradually reduced several times.</seg>
<seg id="144">The tax directorate of the Slovak Republic concluded on the basis of the information obtained that in this case of carousel trade it is free price formation (i.e. the import of undervalued goods and their overvaluation by domestic companies located in the chain between the importer and the exporter), which is not a violation of the VAT Act in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="145">Under the current legislation it is not possible to prevent the payment of excessive VAT deduction to export companies, as they meet all the conditions of the Act to exempt supplies from VAT.</seg>
<seg id="146">o</seg>
<seg id="147">On 12 July 2005, the Czech payer's VAT registration was cancelled.</seg>
<seg id="148">On 27 October 2005, on the basis of a voluntarily submitted application for VAT registration, this entity became a tax payer again.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Czech tax entity entered into the DAP for the month 8/2005 (i.e. the period when it was not a VAT payer) the value of the acquisition of goods (polygraphic printing press) from Slovakia in the amount of CZK 1,174,000 and claimed the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="150">This value corresponded to the delivery of goods from the Slovak payer in the amount of SKK 1,530,000, which the Slovak payer stated in the DAP as a delivery of goods to another EU Member State with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="151">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify the said delivery using the SCAC form, as the Slovak supplier did not prove how he acquired the goods delivered to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO, CR found that the Czech payer did not cooperate with the tax administrator and did not reside at the address specified in the Commercial Register.</seg>
<seg id="153">As part of the international exchange of information, a local investigation will be carried out in the CR by the locally competent tax administrator in order to verify the data.</seg>
<seg id="154">o</seg>
<seg id="155">The Slovak payer stated in the summary report for the 3rd quarter 2004 the delivery of goods in the amount of SKK 956,000 to the tax entity from the CR.</seg>
<seg id="156">The VAT number of the Czech entity was marked as erroneous by the VIES system.</seg>
<seg id="157">A verification in the database of payers revealed that such VAT identification number was never assigned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="158">According to invoices issued by the Slovak payer, it was the execution of electrical assembly works on real estate in the Czech Republic, it was not the delivery of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="159">The services were invoiced without VAT, as the Czech entity informed the Slovak entity that it was registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="160">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify the above mentioned facts by means of the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="161">The SAO, Czech Republic, inquired with the locally competent tax administrator in the Czech Republic that the tax entity stated on the invoices as a customer was never registered as a VAT payer in the Czech Republic, it did not declare the tax on received services from the Slovak entity, and it did not declare the tax on the acquisition of goods.</seg>
<seg id="162">Neither the local investigation nor the tax inspection was carried out at the Czech entity, its current whereabouts are unknown.</seg>
<seg id="163">Based on the international exchange of information, the Czech tax administrator learned that the Czech tax entity became a VAT payer by law by accepting the service.</seg>
<seg id="164">A tax inspection will be carried out at the Slovak tax entity for the first to fourth quarters of 2004.</seg>
<seg id="165">o</seg>
<seg id="166">The Slovak tax payer stated in the recapitulative statement for the third quarter of 2004 the supply of goods in the value of 1 055 thous. to the Czech tax payer.</seg>
<seg id="167">According to invoices issued by the Slovak tax payer, it was the execution of electrical assembly works on real estate in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="168">It was not the delivery of goods from Slovakia to the Czech Republic, but the provision of services.</seg>
<seg id="169">The Slovak tax administrator requested to verify the above mentioned facts by means of the SCAC form.</seg>
<seg id="170">The SAO, the Czech Republic inquired at the locally competent tax administrator in the Czech Republic that the Czech entity was a VAT payer at the time of the delivery and a local investigation was carried out at the Czech entity in order to verify the acquisition of goods from other EU member states in the third quarter of 2004.</seg>
