<seg id="345">The tax administrator carries out a tax inspection of the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="346">The difference between the acquisition data listed in the Slovak payer's DAP for the 3rd quarter of 2004 to the 1st quarter of 2005 and the delivery data reported by payers from EU member countries in each quarter was in the total amount of 4,800 thousand Sk.</seg>
<seg id="347">The tax office found that the tax entity purchased goods from suppliers from the Czech Republic and Belgium and subsequently sold these goods to Ukraine.</seg>
<seg id="348">The invoices were accompanied by export uniform customs declarations.</seg>
<seg id="349">The acquisition of goods in the DAP was not mentioned by the tax entity, according to the statement of the company's manager, the goods in transit were transported directly from the Czech Republic to Ukraine.</seg>
<seg id="350">The tax entity did not submit any VAT registration during the local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="351">A tax inspection was initiated for the payer.</seg>
<seg id="352">5.2 International exchange of information level L3</seg>
<seg id="353">The exchange of information at level L3 is initiated by the locally competent tax administrators, who send their requests for information (hereinafter referred to as "RUI") or spontaneous information (hereinafter referred to as "SPI") relating to a particular tax entity or transaction through the MF CLO, respectively.</seg>
<seg id="354">DR CLO to another EU member country. The objective of the RU is e.g. to prove the execution of a given transaction in the framework of intra-community transactions, to verify a certain TIN, etc.</seg>
<seg id="355">In the case of SPI, it is the communication of information important for the tax administrator in another EU member country.</seg>
<seg id="356">Cooperation in the field of exchange of information is regulated by Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="357">The maximum time limit for replying to the RU was set in Article 8 of this Regulation at 3 months.</seg>
<seg id="358">The conditions for admissibility of requests are regulated by the Decision of the Commission of the European Communities of 15 November 2004, which stipulates that, unless the participating states agree otherwise, the STI must relate to commercial transactions with a value of at least EUR 1 500 excluding VAT.</seg>
<seg id="359">If a STI relates to a commercial transaction with a value of less than EUR 15 000 excluding VAT, the requested authority may, in view of its workload, refuse to reply.</seg>
<seg id="360">The procedure for processing received STIs by the tax administration of the Czech Republic, including an indication of the internal time limits set for processing at each organizational level, is illustrated in the following diagram.</seg>
<seg id="361">In the SR, the time limit for processing STIs by the tax authorities was set internally at 2 months, so that the three-month deadline under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 could be met.</seg>
<seg id="362">The MF CLO received a total of 29 STIs and 3 STIs from the SR between 1 May 2004 and 30 June 2005.</seg>
<seg id="363">Of the 29 received STIs, 26 (i.e. 89.7%) were discharged within the stipulated time limit of 3 months and 3 (i.e. 10.3%) were discharged after this time limit.</seg>
<seg id="364">In the same period, the DR CLO from the Czech Republic received a total of 71 STIs and 7 STIs.</seg>
<seg id="365">Of the 71 RUs received, 64 (i.e. 90.1%) were processed within the stipulated period of 3 months, 5 (i.e. 7.0%) were processed after this period (for the remaining 2 cases it was not possible to determine the period of processing from the submitted materials).</seg>
<seg id="366">More detailed data on the time of processing of RUs received by the MF CLO and DR CLO are contained in the following chart.</seg>
<seg id="367">The reasons for sending RUs, stated on the SCAC forms, are contained in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="368">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="369">On the basis of international cooperation, compliance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT was verified as well as the use of the VIES system for the exchange of information between EU Member States, especially when controlling the application of the right to VAT exemption.</seg>
<seg id="370">International cooperation made it possible to verify selected intra-community transactions carried out between VAT payers from the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="371">The examination of selected transactions revealed that on the basis of international information exchange, tax administrations of both countries detected cases of companies that carried out fictitious intra-community business transactions in order to obtain excessive VAT deductions, as well as cases where the acquirers did not declare VAT on the received supplies of goods in the correct amount.</seg>
<seg id="372">The audit also found differences in the processing and use of VIES data by tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="373">The audit also pointed to problems caused by different reporting of data on intra-community supplies and acquisitions of goods in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="374">The unification of the conditions for reporting these data within the EU would lead to more effective control activities of tax administrations of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="375">The examination of the procedure of financial or tax authorities in the administration of VAT and the use of the VIES system revealed that the financial or tax authorities did not make sufficient use of all VIES possibilities and the relevant legal authorizations.</seg>
<seg id="376">It was also found that the VIES system did not provide up-to-date information on deliveries of goods and on the validity of the VAT registration of tax entities in all cases.</seg>
<seg id="377">The SAO SR compared the data on occurrence of erroneous data in the SH, processed before the start of the audit, with the data processed after the completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="378">From the comparison of these data it was clear that the SAO SR's audit had an impact not only on the reduction of the number of SH with erroneously stated VAT numbers, but also on the reduction of the number of uncorrected errors in the SH.</seg>
<seg id="379">In case of discrepancies in the reported data, the SAO SR asked the tax authorities to carry out local investigations, or to carry out tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="380">The SAO, the Czech Republic, did not have such an option within the framework of the applicable legislation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="381">From the findings of the audit operation it was found that the VIES system provided the tax administrators with basic information necessary for the control of the correct application of VAT in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="382">As there is still room for tax evasion in this area, it is necessary to pay increased attention to intra-community transactions in the administration of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="383">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="384">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak languages and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Chairman of the Najvyššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
