<p>
<seg id="1">Parallel Control of Value Added Tax and Excise Tax Administration between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">This information material gives an overview of the progress and results of parallel control actions carried out by the Supreme Audit Office and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, which were focused on the area of value added tax and excise tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation between the supreme audit offices of both countries was realized on the basis of a contract on cooperation in control activities concluded in February 2004.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of parallel control actions was chosen in view of the fact that indirect taxes significantly contribute to the revenues of the state budgets of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="6">The design of the value added tax, allowing the refund of the excess deduction, provides a space for tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="7">High rates of excise taxes, especially on tobacco and tobacco products, alcohol and mineral oils, mean a high profit for those who escape taxation by illegally selling these goods.</seg>
<seg id="8">Tax fraud is a problem not only in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, but also in other countries of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="9">Due to the need to address this issue comprehensively within the whole European Union, a working group of the VAT Working Group has been created by the supreme audit institutions of the European Union Member States, in whose activities the supreme audit offices of both countries are actively involved.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefit of the audits carried out can be seen not only in the exchange of experience, but especially in the joint effort to identify problem areas of indirect tax administration with the aim of limiting the scope for tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="11">The gained experience and knowledge will be used in the framework of the planned audits of indirect taxes, focused mainly on the involvement of the tax administrators of both states in the VIES system, which allows to control the movement of goods between the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="12">Report on the results of the audits of the administration of value added tax and excise taxes for the years 2002 and 2003</seg>
<seg id="13">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="14">Audit number: (CZ) 04/07 (SK) 18/2004</seg>
<seg id="15">Audit subject:</seg>
<seg id="16">(CZ) Value added tax and excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="17">(SK) Audit of the tax administrator's procedure for administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="18">On February 11, 2004, the Agreement on cooperation in the audit activities between the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (SAO SR) was concluded. The subject of the Agreement was cooperation in the parallel auditing operations "Value added tax and excise taxes", included in the SAO Audit Plan for 2004 under No. 04/07 and "Audit of the procedure of the tax administration, control and enforcement of value added tax and excise taxes", included in the SAO Audit Plan under No. 18/2004.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information to the extent stipulated by the concluded Agreement and in the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the audits.</seg>
<seg id="20">Both parties undertook in the contract to provide each other with information from public sources, from the database of the customs administration and from the files of tax entities maintained by the tax authorities in the Czech Republic and the tax authorities in the Slovak Republic, which the contracting parties could not obtain during the audit of the application of value added tax and excise taxes on imports and exports from sources in the territory of the respective state.</seg>
<seg id="21">The audits were carried out in parallel in the period from January to August 2004.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the territory of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "CR"), the audit was carried out by the State Budget Department and the territorial departments of South Bohemia, North East Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited bodies were the General Directorate of Customs and 12 selected financial offices: the Financial Office for Prague 1, the Financial Office for Prague 3, the Financial Office in České Budějovice, the Financial Office in Frýdek-Místek, the Financial Office in Hodonín, the Financial Office in Jihlava, the Financial Office in Kostelec nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Kroměříž, the Financial Office in Písek, the Financial Office in Rožnov pod Radhoštěm, the Financial Office in Ústí nad Orlicí, the Financial Office in Velký Meziříčí.</seg>
<seg id="24">The auditing operation on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Slovak Republic") was carried out by the Tax and Customs Administration Section of the SAO of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the Expoziturami of the SAO of the Slovak Republic Banská Bystrica and Košice at 10 selected tax offices:</seg>
<seg id="25">The Tax Office Bratislava for selected tax entities, the Tax Office of Bratislava III, the Tax Office of Trnava, the Tax Office of Pu-chov, the Tax Office of Banská Bystrica I, the Tax Office of Liptovský Mikuláš, the Tax Office of Žilina I, the Tax Office of Žilina II, the Tax Office of Košice I and the Tax Office of Košice IV.</seg>
<seg id="26">Objective of the auditing operation</seg>
<seg id="27">The aim of the audit was to verify the fulfilment of obligations of financial and tax authorities and customs offices in the administration of value added tax and excise taxes with a focus on the collection of these taxes on imports and exports of goods and services.</seg>
<seg id="28">The aim of the international cooperation was to verify imports and exports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic and their subsequent verification in tax returns at the respective financial and tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="30">2. Recapitulation of the audit results</seg>
<seg id="31">2.1. General evaluation of the audit activity</seg>
<seg id="32">Within the framework of the international cooperation of the SAO, the SAO SR transmitted 22 206 items of uniform customs declarations (hereinafter referred to as "JCD") from the customs database of the Czech Republic on imports and exports of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and vice versa, the SAO SR transmitted 30 221 items of JCD to the SAO from the customs database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">A comparison of the selected JCD items from the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic was performed.</seg>
<seg id="34">Of the 5 883 selected items of the JCD from the customs database of the Czech Republic, a total of 43% of the related items of the JCD were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="35">Of the 12 343 selected items of the JCD from the customs database of the Slovak Republic, a total of 26% of the related items of the JCD were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="36">Based on the unassigned items of the JCD, a selection of the files of tax entities was carried out at the financial or tax offices, where the declared imports and exports were further verified in cooperation with the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="37">Based on the exchange of information from the customs administrations of the Czech Republic and Slovakia and the financial or tax authorities, the realisation of the declared imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia was verified on the territory of the second state.</seg>
<seg id="38">The SAO and the SAO carried out a joint pilot audit at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov - Drietoma, during which both parties closely cooperated in verifying the accuracy of data on the movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="39">The audit did not find any deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods carried out in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="40">International cooperation enabled the verification of commercial transactions carried out between business partners from both countries and pointed out deficiencies in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="41">2.2. Summary of the audit results</seg>
<seg id="42">In the area of international cooperation, the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic focused on imports and exports of alcohol and spirits, tobacco and tobacco products, computers and computer components, mobile phones and their parts, as well as other types of goods.</seg>
<seg id="43">On the basis of the audit of files of tax subjects at selected financial and tax offices, the SAO requested verification of the realisation of exports of goods declared on 40 JCD with a total statistical value of CZK 15,301,093 and the SAO of the Slovak Republic requested verification of exports with a statistical value of CZK 56,989.</seg>
<seg id="44">The SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic found the following facts among others:</seg>
<seg id="45">- commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides, which made it difficult to identify the corresponding imports and exports in the customs database of the Czech Republic and the customs database of the Slovak Republic;</seg>
<seg id="46">- errors in entering data into customs databases made it impossible to identify certain imports or exports,</seg>
<seg id="47">- for some exports from the Czech Republic, corresponding imports into the Slovak Republic were not proved.</seg>
<seg id="48">In these cases, there is a reasonable suspicion of fictitious exports of goods for the purpose of improper application of value added tax deductions,</seg>
<seg id="49">- tax subjects did not fulfil certain statutory obligations when reporting imports and exports in value added tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="50">- deficiencies were found in the activities of financial or tax authorities in the administration of value added tax and excise taxes and in their cooperation with customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="51">In the area of value added tax and excise taxes, attention will continue to be paid to international trade with the aim of effectively minimising tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="52">In particular, it is important to improve the work of tax authorities in the performance of the administration of value added tax.</seg>
<seg id="53">Effective control of excise duties is based on control of document circulation, systematic physical control of goods and mutual exchange of information on import and export of goods.</seg>
<seg id="54">3. Description of the situation regarding value added tax and excise duties</seg>
<seg id="55">Value added tax</seg>
<seg id="56">Value added tax (hereinafter referred to as "VAT") was levied by the tax or tax authorities on taxable transactions carried out within the territory of the country and by the customs authorities on importation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="57">The tax revenue was determined by the tax authorities by the difference between the collected own tax liability and the refunded excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="58">VAT revenue at customs offices was determined by the amount of tax collected by them.</seg>
<seg id="59">In accordance with the basic principles of the VAT mechanism, the tax collected by the customs authorities was reflected in the tax deductions applied at the tax or tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="60">For most tax and tax authorities, excess VAT deductions exceeded tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="61">VAT is one of the key taxes in terms of state budget revenues, as it accounted for about 31% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Czech Republic in 2003 and for about 42% of the tax revenues of the state budget of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="62">The total VAT collection in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 162.9 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="63">The financial and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 394.3 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions returned amounted to a total of CZK 231.4 billion.</seg>
<seg id="64">The total VAT collection in the Slovak Republic amounted to CZK 83.8 billion in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="65">The tax and customs authorities collected a total of CZK 187.0 billion in VAT in 2003 and the excess VAT deductions returned amounted to a total of CZK 103.2 billion.</seg>
<seg id="66">Excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="67">The collection of excise taxes (hereinafter referred to as the "CND") was carried out by the respective financial or tax authorities and the customs authorities when importing products subject to the CND.</seg>
<seg id="68">The share of the CND in the tax revenues of the state budget in the Czech Republic amounted to about 16% in 2003 and about 19% in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="69">The total CND collection collected by the financial and customs authorities in the Czech Republic amounted to CZK 85.6 billion in 2003 and CZK 38.0 billion in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="70">4. Progress of the audit operation</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation between the SAO and the SAO took place in two stages.</seg>
<seg id="72">In the first stage, the comparison of imports and exports of selected commodities from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia was carried out, in the second stage, the results of this comparison were used for mutual verification of the implementation of selected commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and Slovakia and for audits carried out on the territory of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="73">4.1.</seg>
<seg id="74">Preparation of the audit operation</seg>
<seg id="75">The first proposal for cooperation in parallel audits of VAT and DTC was presented at a working meeting of representatives of the SAO and the SAO of the Slovak Republic in April 2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">In November 2003, a coordination meeting was held at which, among other things, the selection of commodities - types of goods that represented a significant risk in compliance with customs and tax regulations was agreed on: - alcohol and spirits, tariff headings No 2207 and 2208, - tobacco and tobacco products, tariff headings No 2401, 2402 and 2403, - computers and computer components, tariff headings No 8471 and 8473 30, - mobile phones and their accessories, tariff headings No 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8529 90 40.</seg>
<seg id="77">Both parties agreed that the selection of tax subjects to be checked would be carried out: (a) from unassigned items determined by comparison of exports and imports of selected commodities between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, (b) from entities carrying out imports and exports regularly or in one-off large volumes, (c) on the basis of findings from inspections carried out by selected financial and tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.2. Comparison of the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="79">In the first stage, the mechanism for the cross-referencing of JCD items registered in customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was tested on a sample of imports and exports of selected commodities for the month of October 2002.</seg>
<seg id="80">Subsequently, part of exports from the Czech Republic was compared with imports into the Slovak Republic for the year 2002 and vice versa for selected commodities according to the customs tariff:</seg>
<seg id="81">- 2207 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of 80% vol or more; ethyl alcohol and other spirits denatured, of any strength,</seg>
<seg id="82">- 2208 Undenatured ethyl alcohol of an alcoholic strength by volume of less than 80% vol; spirits, liqueurs and other spirituous beverages,</seg>
<seg id="83">- 2401 Unmanufactured tobacco; tobacco refuse,</seg>
<seg id="84">- 2402 Cigars (with or without ends cut off), cigarillos and cigarettes, of tobacco or of tobacco substitutes,</seg>
<seg id="85">- 2403 Other tobacco products and tobacco substitutes; homogenised or reconstituted tobacco; tobacco extracts and essences;</seg>
<seg id="86">- 8525 20 91 Transmission apparatus incorporating reception apparatus: For cellular networks (mobile phones),</seg>
<seg id="87">- 8525 20 99 Transmission apparatus incorporating reception apparatus: Other;</seg>
<seg id="88">- 8529 90 40 Parts suitable for use solely or principally with apparatus of headings 8525 to 8528.</seg>
<seg id="89">Other: Parts of apparatus falling in subheadings 8525 10 50, 8525 20 91, 8525 20 99, 8525 40 11 and 8527 90 92.</seg>
<seg id="90">JCD items from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia were cross-referenced on the basis of the agreement of individual paragraphs of the JCD (e.g. invoiced price, quantity, weight, registration number of the vehicle transporting the load, date of crossing the national border, tariff heading, etc.).</seg>
<seg id="91">The results of the comparison are given in the following tables and graphs.</seg>
<seg id="92">The cross-referencing of individual imports and exports was made more difficult by the fact, among other things, that commercial transactions were not declared in the same way on both sides.</seg>
<seg id="93">For example, exports from the Czech Republic declared on one export JCD were declared on more import JCDs in the territory of the Slovak Republic, or the export JCD had a different number of items from the import JCD.</seg>
<seg id="94">Other factors that influenced the success of the attribution were the different composition of data in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, as well as the time shift between the registration of exports in the customs database of one country and the registration of corresponding imports in the customs database of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="95">The results of the comparison were used in the selection of control samples at the audited financial or tax offices.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority was given to certain tax entities that carried out imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, which could not be identified in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="97">Furthermore, some tax entities were selected for the verification of commercial transactions reported in the VAT returns, for which data on imports or exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were found in both databases.</seg>
<seg id="98">4.3. Pilot control at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma</seg>
<seg id="99">The border customs crossing point for the execution of the pilot control was selected on the basis of a joint analysis of unassigned JCD items in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="100">Based on a bilateral agreement between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia, the use of control sheets was introduced at the border customs crossings between the Czech Republic and Slovakia from 1.6.1998.</seg>
<seg id="101">The aim of this measure was to eliminate customs and tax evasion as much as possible, to ensure an overview of the movement of means of transport transporting commercial goods in the customs area and to create conditions for mutual comparison of customs records.</seg>
<seg id="102">The joint pilot control was carried out from 8.3.2004 to 26.3.2004 and was aimed at examining this system of customs control.</seg>
<seg id="103">Procedure for the use of control sheets at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma:</seg>
<seg id="104">1) Weighing the vehicle, issuing the control sheet and handing it over to the driver.</seg>
<seg id="105">2) Unloading the vehicle in the designated sector in the parking area.</seg>
<seg id="106">Customs processing in the clearance hall of the Police of the Czech Republic, Police of the Slovak Republic, Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="107">The individual components confirmed the execution of the clearance by stamping in the control sheet.</seg>
<seg id="108">3) Bringing the vehicle to the physical inspection area.</seg>
<seg id="109">Presentation of the control sheet, JCD, or other documents to the customs administration employee - check the execution of all prescribed operations and documents.</seg>
<seg id="110">Performance of the physical inspection by the respective components.</seg>
<seg id="111">Release of the vehicle from the customs area.</seg>
<seg id="112">Note: When importing goods into the Czech Republic, the weighing of the vehicle was carried out directly by the employees of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="113">When importing goods into the Slovak Republic, the weighing of the vehicle was carried out by the employees of an authorized legal entity.</seg>
<seg id="114">The vehicles were recorded in the computer register after weighing.</seg>
<seg id="115">4.3.1 Inspection sample</seg>
<seg id="116">Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="117">The inspection sample was selected on the basis of the analysis of records from the Customs database of exports of the Czech Republic in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="118">The composition of the inspection sample for exports is shown in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="119">4.3.2. Inspection sheets and their registration Exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="120">When exporting from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic, the Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic issued and registered the inspection sheets.</seg>
<seg id="121">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic recorded the registration numbers of these inspection sheets in the electronic database of exports.</seg>
<seg id="122">From the number of 453 JCD items, the SAO found 256 cases of imports into the Slovak Republic according to data from the customs database of the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The remaining 197 JCD items were identified by the SAO SR in cooperation with the staff of the Drietoma border crossing point.</seg>
<seg id="123">Exports from Slovakia to the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="124">When exporting from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic, the control sheets were issued and registered by the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="125">From the total number of 339 JCD items of the selected control sample, the SAO in cooperation with border customs crossing staff assigned the corresponding registration numbers of the control sheets to the 295 JCD items.</seg>
<seg id="126">The remaining 44 cases were identified in the register by the employees of the border customs crossing Drietoma and the export of goods from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic was confirmed.</seg>
<seg id="127">The SAO and SAO audit did not find any deficiencies in the registration of selected cases of imports and exports of goods in 2002 at the border customs crossing Starý Hrozenkov-Drietoma.</seg>
<seg id="128">4.4. Selected audit findings when verifying commercial transactions</seg>
<seg id="129">Within the framework of international cooperation, the implementation of imports and exports between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic was verified from documents of customs administrations and tax authorities in the territory of the other country.</seg>
<seg id="130">The selected tax subjects were verified:</seg>
<seg id="131">- whether the submitted JCD were registered in the customs databases of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic,</seg>
<seg id="132">- fulfilment of legal conditions for application of VAT deduction on import, refund of excess VAT deduction and application of VAT exemption on export.</seg>
<seg id="133">The verification of commercial transactions revealed:</seg>
<seg id="134">1. The SAO of the Slovak Republic requested verification of the realization of export of alcohol in the statistical value of 56 989 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="135">The SAO identified in the customs database of the Czech Republic the corresponding import in the statistical value of 42 624 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="136">2. The company dealing with import and export of photographic devices and accessories applied an excess VAT deduction in the amount of 3 740 664 CZK in the VAT declaration for the month of December 2002.</seg>
<seg id="137">In order to check the reported exports from the Czech Republic, the SAO selected 3 JCD (16 items) in the statistical value of 1 274 822 CZK.</seg>
<seg id="138">The SAO identified 3 corresponding import JCD (17 items) at a statistical value of CZK 1,724,321.</seg>
<seg id="139">The VAT was paid to the competent customs office in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="140">3. The company, whose business was mainly trading with optical devices, applied a total excess VAT deduction of CZK 4,1,36,000 higher than the tax liability in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="141">In order to verify the reported trade activity, the SAO selected the export JCD (32 items) at a statistical value of CZK 7,154,124.</seg>
<seg id="142">The SAO found that the import JCD (12 items) corresponded to this JCD with a statistical value of CZK 9,653,827.</seg>
<seg id="143">The VAT was paid to the competent customs office in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="144">4. The company dealing with, among other things, the purchase of goods for resale and sales, did not report any export of goods in the submitted VAT returns in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="145">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the statistical value of the export of goods in 2002 amounted to CZK 3,439,888.</seg>
<seg id="146">Based on these facts, the SAO selected for verification 5 export JCDs (5 items) at a total statistical value of CZK 669,839.</seg>
<seg id="147">The SAO SR identified 5 corresponding import JCDs (5 items) with a statistical value of CZK 1,012,656.</seg>
<seg id="148">The SAO SR audit at the relevant tax office proved the realisation of the declared imports and payment of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="149">5. The company, whose business included the purchase of goods for resale and sale, production, installation and repair of electrical machinery and devices, reported in the tax returns of VAT in the year 2002 the export of goods with a value of CZK 12,966,706.</seg>
<seg id="150">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the total value of exports in the year 2002 was CZK 14,474,381.</seg>
<seg id="151">The SAO submitted 17 export JCDs (59 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,975,122.</seg>
<seg id="152">The SAO SR identified 13 JCDs (50 items) with a statistical value of CZK 3,621,370 in the customs database of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="153">The Slovak customs database failed to identify the corresponding import JCDs to 4 export JCDs (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 399,776.</seg>
<seg id="154">The relevant tax office in the Slovak Republic verified these imports with the tax entity.</seg>
<seg id="155">The tax entity listed on the JCD as an importer to the SR expressed in the minutes of the local investigation that the imports declared on the Czech export JCDs had not been realized.</seg>
<seg id="156">The SAO SR therefore asked the local tax office to carry out a tax audit of VAT and corporate income tax for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="157">6. The company engaged in the import and sale of cigarettes exported tobacco stickers with a statistical value of CZK 7,338,199 in 2002 and CZK 12,228,545 in 2003, according to the Czech customs database.</seg>
<seg id="158">The company did not report any exports in the tax returns for VAT in 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="159">The SAO selected for verification 5 export JCDs (5 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 2,471,598.</seg>
<seg id="160">The SAO SR identified 7 JCDs (7 items) with a statistical value of CZK 2,919,514 in the Slovak customs database.</seg>
<seg id="161">The corresponding imports could not be assigned to the export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 224,738 in the Slovak customs database.</seg>
<seg id="162">7. The software company did not report exports of goods in the VAT returns for 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="163">According to the Czech customs database, the statistical value of exports of goods in 2002 and 2003 amounted to CZK 1,630,198 in total.</seg>
<seg id="164">The SAO selected for verification in the SR 9 JCDs (9 items) with a total statistical value of CZK 755,588.</seg>
<seg id="165">For the Slovak customs database, the SAO SR identified 8 JCDs (8 items) with a statistical value of CZK 915,601.</seg>
<seg id="166">For the export JCD (1 item) with a statistical value of CZK 68,286, the corresponding import could not be assigned in the SR customs database.</seg>
<seg id="167">In the above cases, the corresponding imports could not be identified in the SR customs database for 6 JCDs with a statistical value of CZK 692,800.</seg>
<seg id="168">Of which:</seg>
<seg id="169">- for 2 export JCDs from the Czech customs database with a statistical value of CZK 293,024, the corresponding import JCDs could not be identified in the SR customs database (see points 6 and 7).</seg>
<seg id="170">Due to a certain error rate in entering data in the customs database, it was not possible to identify certain registered imports, e.g. in cases where the importer's name was missing or there was an error in the tax identification number (TIN).</seg>
<seg id="171">Therefore, it cannot be concluded with certainty that these exports did not take place.</seg>
<seg id="172">- to 4 export JCDs from the customs database of the Czech Republic, imports corresponding to exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic in the statistical value of CZK 399,776 were not proven (see point 5).</seg>
<seg id="173">In such cases, there are reasonable grounds for suspecting that goods have been fictitiously exported for the purpose of wrongfully claiming a VAT deduction.</seg>
<seg id="174">5. Control of imports and exports of goods and services within the scope of control of selected financial and tax authorities</seg>
<seg id="175">5.1. Control sample</seg>
<seg id="176">In order to verify the fulfilment of the obligations of tax entities in the import and export of goods and services and to evaluate the level of cooperation between the tax and customs authorities, the files of tax entities were selected at the audited financial and tax offices according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="177">1. tax subjects were selected from the customs databases of the Czech Republic and Slovakia: (a) with the highest volume of imports, (b) with the highest amount of VAT charged, (c) with the highest volume of exports,</seg>
<seg id="178">2. tax entities were selected from the register of the tax or tax authorities according to the amount of: (a) VAT deductions applied on importation, (b) excess VAT deductions applied, (c) VAT refund entitlement, (d) VAT exemption applied on exportation,</seg>
<seg id="179">3. tax entities that have been subject to a tax audit.</seg>
<seg id="180">The sampling was carried out irrespective of the country of destination, with a focus on risky commodities.</seg>
<seg id="181">5.2. Inspection findings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="182">An overview of imports into the Czech Republic and exports from the Czech Republic for risky commodities in 2002 and 2003 is given in the following table:</seg>
<seg id="183">5.2.1. Inspection of selected sample at financial offices</seg>
<seg id="184">The SAO focused on:</seg>
<seg id="185">- the procedure of the tax authorities in verifying the correctness of reported VAT,</seg>
<seg id="186">- cooperation between the tax authorities and the customs administration,</seg>
<seg id="187">- comparison of data from the customs database with the JCD database at financial offices with a focus on comparison of declared value, application of the correct VAT rate in connection with the customs classification of goods or services, or comparison of data on the JCD and attached invoices with data in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="188">- comparison of data from VAT tax returns on performed and received transactions from abroad with data in the JCD database at financial offices or in the customs database,</seg>
<seg id="189">- method of verification of the right to exemption from VAT when exporting goods or providing services abroad,</seg>
<seg id="190">- comparison of the volume of exports of goods or services declared in VAT tax returns with data from the customs database.</seg>
<seg id="191">The JCD database at financial offices contained only records of those imports and exports where tax subjects were obliged to include imports or exports in their tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="192">At the audited financial offices, the files of tax subjects were examined, which declared imports totalling CZK 60 396 379 thousand in the VAT returns in 2002 and 2003 and the corresponding VAT totalling CZK 12 644 052 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="193">Furthermore, the files of tax subjects were checked, which reported exports totalling CZK 47 323 111 thousand in the tax returns for 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="194">According to the customs database of the Czech Republic, the tax subjects for which the imports and exports between the Czech Republic and Slovakia were examined carried out imports into the Czech Republic from the Slovak Republic in 2002 and 2003 with a total VAT base of CZK 3 759 352 thousand, VAT of CZK 767 607 thousand and exports from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic with a total statistical value of CZK 1 989 090 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="195">The detected differences between the records in the database of JCD at the financial offices and in the customs database of the Czech Republic were examined as follows:</seg>
<seg id="196">- the items of JCD that were missing in the customs database of the Czech Republic were requested directly at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic,</seg>
<seg id="197">- the JCD items that were missing in the database of the tax offices were verified as canceled documents,</seg>
<seg id="198">- the JCD items that were found to have different values between the customs database of the Czech Republic and the database of the tax offices were requested at the General Directorate of Customs of the Czech Republic in written form, including the attached invoices.</seg>
<seg id="199">The verification revealed that the JCD database at the tax offices did not contain, for example, records on import JCDs with a total value of VAT of CZK 3,622,000 and records on export JCDs with a total statistical value of CZK 9,359,000.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1.1. Detected differences</seg>
<seg id="201">Comparing the JCD database at the tax offices and the cumulative tax obligations for 2002 and 2003 in the VAT returns for a selected sample of tax subjects, the following differences were found:</seg>
<seg id="202">The differences in values were mainly due to:</seg>
<seg id="203">- The time shift between the realisation of the imports and the exercise of the right to deduct the VAT charged on the importation of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">The tax subject was able to exercise the right to deduct on the importation of goods within 3 years from the end of the tax period in which the goods were placed under the relevant scheme or, in the case of the temporary importation scheme, within 3 years from the end of the tax period in which the scheme was terminated.</seg>
<seg id="205">- The time shift between the realisation of the exports and the moment when the tax subject received the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="206">The tax subject was obliged to include data on realised exports exempt from the obligation to apply output tax in the VAT return at the earliest for the tax period in which the goods left the country if he also had a tax document, which was the JCD.</seg>
<seg id="207">- The failure of tax subjects to fulfil their obligations when reporting imports and exports in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="208">In some cases, tax subjects did not include correct data on imports and exports in the VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="209">As tax subjects did not have to attach JCD lists to the VAT returns submitted, the control of the right to deduct or exemption from VAT by the tax authorities was made more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="210">5.2.2. Cooperation of the financial and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="211">During the audited period, the customs authorities decided to refund or remit import or export duties and VAT.</seg>
<seg id="212">Tax subjects were obliged by law to reduce the previously exercised right to deduct VAT by the amount of tax returned by the customs office in the tax return for the period in which the tax was refunded.</seg>
<seg id="213">No legal regulation provided for the sending of information about changes in the amount of duties and VAT from the customs authorities to the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="214">Some audited tax authorities received this information, but irregularly or with a considerable time delay and only from some customs authorities.</seg>
<seg id="215">One audited tax office did not receive this information at all.</seg>
<seg id="216">If the tax office did not receive information about changes in the amount of customs duties and VAT directly from the customs office, it did not have the necessary data for checking the fulfilment of the legal obligation of tax subjects.</seg>
<seg id="217">In 2002, the customs offices returned VAT in the amount of more than CZK 319 million and in 2003 in the amount of more than CZK 398 million.</seg>
<seg id="218">The results of the audit pointed to persistent deficiencies in the activities of tax administrators, some systemic errors in the cooperation of the tax authorities with the customs administration authorities and the non-fulfilment of certain obligations of tax payers filing VAT returns and the Income Tax Act.</seg>
<seg id="219">During the administration of VAT and Income Tax Act, deficiencies were found in the following areas in particular:</seg>
<seg id="220">a) at the cancellation of VAT registrations, the fulfilment of the obligation of tax payers to pay VAT on commercial assets registered or which should have been registered at the date of the cancellation of the registration, where the payer claimed a tax deduction, was verified only rarely,</seg>
<seg id="221">b) the tax authorities did not consistently use the possibility to carry out a tax inspection or a local investigation.</seg>
<seg id="222">This resulted in insufficient verification of the validity of the right to a VAT deduction in some cases,</seg>
<seg id="223">c) the official records and minutes of oral proceedings did not contain all the necessary data proving the validity of claimed excess VAT deductions,</seg>
<seg id="224">d) the tax authorities did not sufficiently verify imports and exports declared in VAT tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="225">5.3. Inspection findings in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="226">5.3.1. Inspection of the selected sample at tax offices</seg>
<seg id="227">In the selected sample, the SAO audited or the tax office carried out a tax inspection for the tax years 2002 and 2003.</seg>
<seg id="228">After analysing the submitted tax returns and requests for tax refunds at selected tax subjects, the SAO asked the tax office to secure the relevant JCDs documenting imports and exports, invoices and proof of payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="229">Subsequently, the SAO SR audited whether the submitted JCDs were registered in the customs database of imports and exports and whether the decisive facts and legal conditions were fulfilled in the application of the input tax deduction for imports, in the refund of excess VAT deduction, in the application of the tax exemption for exports and in the refund of the CAS.</seg>
<seg id="230">At 10 audited tax offices, the SAO SR audited selected cases of imports and exports of goods between the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the structure according to the number of JCD items and the sum of statistical values given in the following table.</seg>
<seg id="231">In total, imports were audited at a statistical value of 856.2 mil. Sk, which represents 5.11% of the total value of imports of selected commodities from the Czech Republic into the CAS.</seg>
<seg id="232">Exports of selected commodities were audited at a total statistical value of 176 mil. Sk, which represents 6.87% of the total value of exports of selected commodities from the Slovak Republic to the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="233">Furthermore, 618 cases of imports of other goods and services (mainly white goods, packaging technology and software) from the EU countries to the Slovak Republic were audited in the statistical value of SKK 532.8 million.</seg>
<seg id="234">5.3.2. Cooperation of tax and customs authorities</seg>
<seg id="235">The SAO scrutinized tax authorities and found discrepancies between data recorded in the Slovak Republic customs database and data recorded in specific VAT returns, e.g.:</seg>
<seg id="236">- 2 tax subjects (natural persons) declared in their tax returns imports of goods in the total value of SKK 1 589 261, on the basis of which they claimed a claim for refund of excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="237">In local investigations carried out at the instigation of the SAO of the Slovak Republic, tax subjects failed to prove to the tax office the legitimacy of applying the input tax with relevant documents on realisation of imports and payment of VAT,</seg>
<seg id="238">- the tax subject (s. r. o.) declared in the tax return for the tax period January 2003 the received taxable performance in the value of 77 167 576 Sk, the export of goods in the value of 18 006 041 Sk and claimed the excess VAT deduction in the amount of 17 157 101 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="239">The tax returns filed for the year 2003 show that the difference between the volume of purchase and export in the value of 59 161 535 Sk, which arose in January 2003, was not equalized during the whole year 2003.</seg>
<seg id="240">In the above cases, the SAO SR asked the relevant tax authorities to carry out a tax inspection of the applied excess VAT deductions.</seg>
<seg id="241">- in another case, the tax subject (s. r. o.) declared in the tax returns for the tax period January to June 2002 the export of goods in the total value of 87 199 Sk.</seg>
<seg id="242">A verification in the customs database of the SR revealed that the tax subject made exports in the statistical value of 296 747 Sk in the indicated period.</seg>
<seg id="243">The tax office carried out several local investigations at the registered office of the company, which found that the company's manager (a citizen of Great Britain) had travelled and the company had left the leased premises without terminating the lease agreement in August 2002.</seg>
<seg id="244">At the time of the audit, the SAO SR filed a report with the law enforcement authorities on the suspicion of committing a crime of non-payment of tax.</seg>
<seg id="245">Based on the results of the audit at selected tax authorities, the SAO SR finds that the biggest problems in the performance of the administration and control of VAT and VAT were found mainly in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="246">- failure to use the possibility to carry out the tax audit of VAT on problematic tax entities, especially in cases of application of a high value of excessive VAT deductions,</seg>
<seg id="247">- the tax audit reports did not contain an inventory of audited documents</seg>
<seg id="248">- JCD on import and export of goods,</seg>
<seg id="249">- insufficient verification of declared import and export of goods in the tax returns,</seg>
<seg id="250">- lengthy proceedings of tax administrators when issuing decisions, especially in the context of the assessment procedure, with the consequence of the extinction of the right to assess sanctions,</seg>
<seg id="251">- failure to comply with legal conditions when granting deferments of payment of taxes,</seg>
<seg id="252">- failure to compensate VAT arrears within the deadline for the refund of excessive VAT deductions,</seg>
<seg id="253">- insufficient use of all forms of security and recovery of tax arrears.</seg>
<seg id="254">Based on the audited shortcomings, the SAO asked the relevant tax authorities to perform VAT tax audits focusing on the justification of applied excessive VAT deductions for 14 tax subjects.</seg>
<seg id="255">At all audited tax offices, measures were taken to eliminate the audited shortcomings, whose compliance will be monitored and audited by the SAO.</seg>
<seg id="256">6. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="257">International cooperation enabled the verification of commercial transactions carried out between business partners from both countries and pointed out shortcomings in the registration of imports and exports.</seg>
<seg id="258">The inspections also revealed persistent deficiencies in the fulfilment of the obligations of VAT and VAT payers, in the activities of the financial and tax authorities, in the system of cooperation and exchange of information between tax and customs administrations, which ultimately reduced the effectiveness and efficiency of tax inspections.</seg>
<seg id="259">The findings also showed that the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have at their disposal within the tax information system basic data on imports and exports from the customs database of the Czech Republic. In SR, there is no similar system for transmitting information on imports and exports of goods between customs and tax administrations.</seg>
<seg id="260">The procedure for verifying the performance of the VAT and VAT administration was not the same due to the different legislation and conditions in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="261">The SAO verified the necessary data from information obtained at the Czech Customs Administration and from documents available at audited financial offices. The SAO verified the execution of commercial transactions from documents of tax entities requested through tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="262">In case of detection of irregularities, it asked tax authorities to perform tax audits.</seg>
<seg id="263">The performed parallel audits in the area of VAT and the VAT administration evaluated the state of administration of these taxes in the period before the accession to the European Union and pointed out the necessity of further cooperation in this area.</seg>
<seg id="264">Mutual cooperation will be further deepened in the auditing of the activities of financial and tax authorities in connection with the adoption of the new VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="265">One of the new obligations related to the delivery of goods to other Member States of the European Union is the submission of the so-called summary report.</seg>
<seg id="266">This report must be submitted by all VAT payers who carried out the delivery of goods to another Member State to a person registered for VAT in another Member State.</seg>
<seg id="267">Tax administrators are obliged to enter the data from the summary reports into the VIES (VAT Information Exchange System) system, which is accessible to tax administrators from the Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="268">The financial or tax authorities then have the possibility to compare these data with the data provided in the submitted VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="269">This system is further used to verify the validity of the VAT numbers of persons registered for VAT, to verify the validity of the applied VAT exemption in the case of a supply of goods to another Member State and to check the proper taxation of goods.</seg>
<seg id="270">The implementation of parallel audits showed the possibilities of cooperation between the SAO and the SAO of Slovakia.</seg>
<seg id="271">The results of these audits will be confronted with the outcomes of the upcoming audits, which will focus, among other things, on the verification of the VIES system, which is supposed to prevent tax evasion in so-called "intra-community supplies".</seg>
<seg id="272">Due to the importance of VAT and the Internal Revenue Act for budgetary revenues, it is necessary to focus the auditing activities mainly on monitoring and identification of risk areas in order to limit the scope for tax evasion in indirect taxes.</seg>
<seg id="273">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="274">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak and signed by the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office and the Chairman of the Najvyššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic.</seg>
</p>
