<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_04_23" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="CUNI-DocTransformer2020">
<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the Results of the Control in Asylum Facilities in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">State Property and Funds Intended for Securing the Activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior</seg>
<seg id="3">Control Action No. 04/23 "State Property and Funds Intended for Securing the Activities of the Refugee Facilities Administration of the Ministry of the Interior"</seg>
<seg id="4">Control Action No. 15/2004 "Control of hospodárenia with state property and financial prostriedkami Intended for Providanie of Asylum and Temporary Refugee Cudzincom in the Slovak Republic"</seg>
<seg id="5">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="6">Population migration is one of the phenomena of a global nature and has become an inseparable part of the current development phase of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="7">Its cause is mainly the flight of citizens from their country of origin or last permanent residence from persecution, especially for reasons of race, religion, nationality, politics, as well as the consequences of military conflicts and ethnic cleansing.</seg>
<seg id="8">Their aim is to obtain asylum and integration into society, especially in one of the advanced democratic countries of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="9">A large group also consists of foreigners whose reason for migration is unfavourable economic and living conditions.</seg>
<seg id="10">Migration is not a new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="11">The adoption of the Geneva Agreement of 1951 and the New York Protocol of 1967 on the legal status of refugees, by accepting them, the governments of the signatory countries undertook to apply them in their foreign-policy orientation, already brought about the establishment of specific principles of assistance to refugees.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Czech and Slovak Federative Republics ratified the New York Protocol in 1991 and the Geneva Agreement in 1992.</seg>
<seg id="13">After the split in 1993, both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic declared their position on the refugee issue by continuing to comply with the adopted international documents and confirmed their binding force within the framework of national legislation by a legal act.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both Republics also enshrined the granting of asylum in their constitutional laws.</seg>
<seg id="15">Parallel checks carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic focused on the asylum process and related issues, the results of which are contained in a joint final report.</seg>
<seg id="16">The cooperation between the supreme audit offices of both countries was implemented on the basis of the "Agreement on Cooperation in Control Activities" (hereinafter referred to as "the Agreement") concluded in April 2004.</seg>
<seg id="17">In the Agreement, both parties undertook to provide each other with information on the legislation governing the asylum procedure in the other Contracting Party's State, selected statistical data concerning the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process, as well as information on asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="18">The parallel control action sought to identify the same problem areas and to point out the consequences arising from this for the area of population migration.</seg>
<seg id="19">The cooperation consisted in the unification of the programme of control actions, in the exchange of information within the scope of the Treaty and in the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the controls.</seg>
<seg id="20">At the first joint meeting, which took place from 5.4. to 7.4.2004, the same audit areas and control procedures were established in the preparation of the control actions.</seg>
<seg id="21">At the second meeting, which took place from 28.6. to 30.6. 2004, the common points for the programme of the control action were specified.</seg>
<seg id="22">At the third joint meeting, which took place during the control action from 8.11. to 10.11.2004, the experience of the ongoing controls was exchanged.</seg>
<seg id="23">The forms of the outcomes of the controls were specified and the structure and content of the joint final report, which was prepared from 14.2. to 17.2. 2005 at the last joint meeting, were provisionally established.</seg>
<seg id="24">The controls were carried out in parallel between September 2004 and January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Czech Republic, the control was carried out by the inspectors of the Department of Defence and Security and selected territorial departments.</seg>
<seg id="26">The auditees were the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as the "MoI") and the Administration of Refugee Facilities of the Ministry of the Interior (hereinafter referred to as the "SUZ").</seg>
<seg id="27">In the Slovak Republic, the audits were carried out by the Section of Defence, vnútra and štátnych úradov.</seg>
<seg id="28">The auditee was the Migračný úrad of the Ministry of the Interior of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as the "MoI").</seg>
<seg id="29">The audited period covered the years 2001, 2002 and 2003 (hereinafter referred to as the audited period).</seg>
<seg id="30">In some cases, statistical data for a longer period are also used in the joint report.</seg>
<seg id="31">2. Recapitulation of the results of the audits</seg>
<seg id="32">2.1. Evaluation of the auditing activities</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of the audits carried out in parallel were: - the asylum process, - asylum facilities, - the management of state funds and property, - the internal control system.</seg>
<seg id="34">The mutual exchange of gained experience between the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic took place at the stage of preparation and implementation of the auditing operations.</seg>
<seg id="35">This exchange made it possible to evaluate the submitted documents more thoroughly, to analyse the causes of the detected differences in the security of the asylum process.</seg>
<seg id="36">In this way, it was possible to concentrate on the decisive problems affecting the activity of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="37">In the end, this had a positive effect on the quality of the implementation of control activities.</seg>
<seg id="38">2.2 Summary of control results</seg>
<seg id="39">The harmonisation of the asylum law of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic with European Union (EU) documents has been the subject of evaluation reports by the European Commission on the readiness of both countries to join the EU.</seg>
<seg id="40">The adoption of legislation regulating this area continues after the accession of both countries to the EU, with the aim of further harmonisation with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="41">The number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic increased significantly in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="42">In the Slovak Republic, the number of applicants has been steadily increasing, with a significant increase in applicants occurring in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="43">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic provide financial and material security for asylum seekers in the sense of international agreements.</seg>
<seg id="44">The state budget of both countries allocates the necessary financial resources for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="45">The amount of expenditure drawn from the state budget of both countries is influenced in particular by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until asylum is granted or not granted, as well as by the state of health of the applicants.</seg>
<seg id="46">The amount of some of the benefits collected is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="47">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic have established asylum facilities in which they have gradually created suitable conditions for the stay of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="48">The asylum facilities provide accommodation, meals, health care and basic material equipment and sanitary needs for the duration of the stay of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="49">At the same time, leisure courses are organised and the conditions for cultural and sporting activities are created for applicants.</seg>
<seg id="50">The asylum facilities include reception centres and residential centres, and in the Czech Republic, integration centres.</seg>
<seg id="51">The costs per stay day depend on the occupancy and equipment of the centre and are comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="52">In the Czech Republic, the capacity of asylum facilities is basically stabilised.</seg>
<seg id="53">In the Slovak Republic, it is expected to increase by almost 1 000 places in the next two years.</seg>
<seg id="54">The aim is to create the conditions for applicants, whose increasing number is expected to continue in the following years in connection with the application of the Dublin Convention.</seg>
<seg id="55">In the Czech Republic, the largest part of the approved budget expenditure was spent on the provision of services. The decisive expenditure of this item was expenditure on accommodation and catering for applicants in asylum facilities operated on the basis of a contract, expenditure on health care provided to asylum seekers and the cost of a permanent security service providing protection of asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="56">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work carried out and insurance premiums also contributed significantly to the total expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="57">In the Slovak Republic, the budgetary management of the security of the migration policy and asylum process was marked by many budgetary measures that addressed the legitimate requirements related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="58">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance premiums, expenditure on materials and services and expenditure on security services contributed to a decisive extent to the drawdown of current expenses.</seg>
<seg id="59">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic drew attention to some similar deficiencies that did not have a major impact on the financial management and management of state property.</seg>
<seg id="60">These were deficiencies in particular in the area of the use of state budget funds contrary to the purpose for which they were determined by the Act on the State Budget, when ordinary expenses paid for actions having the character of technical evaluation of long-term tangible property.</seg>
<seg id="61">The Act on Accounting in the area of inventory was also violated and in the failure to comply with the chart of accounts.</seg>
<seg id="62">In the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were also found in the management of State property when it was handed over to another person without a contract.</seg>
<seg id="63">The Act on the Land Register was violated by failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes in the Land Register data and the Act on Waste was violated by handing over waste for disposal to a person who was not a person authorised for waste management.</seg>
<seg id="64">In the Slovak Republic, deficiencies were also found in the provision of unreasonably high advances for electricity and natural gas consumption, deficiencies in public procurement and in the management of State property when its registration was not sufficiently ensured and the method of disposing of unneeded assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="65">The internal control system was ensured in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in the sense of the generally binding legal regulations that govern the way financial control is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="66">The submitted written documentation did not reveal any deficiencies.</seg>
<seg id="67">The Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, despite some deficiencies found, evaluate positively the procedure of SUZ and MU in providing services for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="68">Based on the findings gained during the audit, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší Audit Office of the Slovak Republic note that despite a significant increase in the number of asylum seekers in recent years, the respective organisational units of both countries have managed the tasks related to the care of asylum seekers to an adequate level.</seg>
<seg id="69">The evaluation shows that the system is functional and stable.</seg>
<seg id="70">The results of the audit were discussed with interested statutory representatives of the respective organisational units of the state on both the Czech and Slovak sides.</seg>
<seg id="71">Based on the results of the audit, we recommend that positive methodological experience from the audit be used in other joint control actions within the framework of international cooperation of supreme audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="72">3. Legislative framework</seg>
<seg id="73">In both the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic, asylum law is based on the 1951 Geneva Convention (the Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees and the subsequent New York Protocol of 1967).</seg>
<seg id="74">The first legislation was implemented by Act No. 498/1990 Coll., on Refugees.</seg>
<seg id="75">In the Czech Republic, Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum and on the Amendment of Act No. 83/1991 Coll., on the Police of the Czech Republic, has been effective since 1 January 2000.</seg>
<seg id="76">This Act has been amended five times (Act No. 2/2002 Coll., Act No. 217/2002 Coll., Act No. 320/2002 Coll., Act No. 519/2002 Coll. and Act No. 222/2003 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="77">Two other amendments to Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, are currently in the legislative process and the adoption of further amendments will be linked to European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">At the time of the creation of Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, the field of asylum was part of the 3rd pillar of the EU and asylum documents were political documents in terms of binding force.</seg>
<seg id="79">Already within the framework of the adoption of this Act, efforts were made to make it as compatible as possible with EU law.</seg>
<seg id="80">A significant change for asylum policy within the EU was the transfer of the issue of asylum from the 3rd to the 1st pillar, when the right of asylum became part of Community law from 1.5.1999 on the basis of the Treaty of Amsterdam.</seg>
<seg id="81">This shift triggered the need to create appropriate legislation, i.e. to create legal instruments in appropriate legal binding force.</seg>
<seg id="82">The compatibility of Czech asylum law with EU documents was the subject of regular evaluation reports by the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="83">Key Community regulations in the area of asylum were adopted shortly before or after the Czech Republic's accession to the EU and their transposition deadline had not yet expired at the time of the Supreme Audit Office's audit, the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="84">After their implementation into the Czech legal order, the Czech Republic will be obliged to notify the European Commission of how it has implemented the transposition.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Slovak Republic, the procedure of the state authorities in the procedure for granting refugee status and determining the obligations of foreigners who have applied for refugee status or who have been granted temporary refuge in the territory of the Slovak Republic was established with effect from 1.1.1996 by the Act of the National Council of the Slovak Republic No.283/1995 Z. z., o utečencoch.</seg>
<seg id="86">Since 2003, the Act on Refugees has been replaced by the Act No.480/2002 Z. z. on Asylum and on Amendments to Certain Acts, in which the harmonisation of the legislation of the Slovak Republic with the Council of Europe Directive 2001/55/EC of 20.7.2001 on minimum standards for providing temporary protection in the event of a mass influx of displaced persons and on measures to promote the balance of efforts between member countries in receiving such persons and bearing the resulting consequences has been incorporated.</seg>
<seg id="87">After two amendments to Act No. 480/2002 Coll., on Asylum, in 2003 and 2004, a third amendment was approved at the beginning of 2005, which entails further harmonisation of the Slovak Republic's law with the EU legislation in the area of migration and asylum.</seg>
<seg id="88">Its important elements are, for example, the establishment of an obligation for asylum seekers to attend a course on the basics of the Slovak language during their stay in an integration centre, the designation of a guardian by the courts for foreign minors if they reside in the territory of the Slovak Republic without a legal representative, the possibility for applicants to enter into an employment relationship under certain circumstances specified in the amendment to the Act.</seg>
<seg id="89">The harmonisation of the Slovak Republic's law with the EU law in the area of migration and the asylum process was evaluated in the regular reports of the European Commission on the preparedness for the Slovak Republic's accession to the EU.</seg>
<seg id="90">In 2002, the report drew attention to the lack of staffing capacity of the Ministry of Interior, which did not correspond to the increased number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="91">4. Asylum process</seg>
<seg id="92">In the Czech Republic, since 1990, refugee matters have been the responsibility of the Ministry.</seg>
<seg id="93">With effect from 1 January 1996, the Ministry established the organisational component of the State of SUZ. This was due to the separation of the performance of the state administration in the field of asylum procedure, which is carried out through the Department of Asylum and Migration Policy of the Ministry, from the provision of services to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="94">The task of the SUZ is to provide accommodation, catering, health and other services for the Ministry of Interior to participants in asylum procedures and asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Slovak Republic, the Ministry of Interior performs crucial tasks in the field of the asylum process, especially in terms of the financial and material-technical provision of the asylum process, to the extent defined by special regulations.</seg>
<seg id="96">Priority tasks are issues related to the decision-making of asylum applications by foreigners at the first stage of the administrative procedure and the complex operation of asylum facilities in the field of accommodation, catering, health, financial and material provision of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="97">In addition, it prepares concepts on the migration policy of the state.</seg>
<seg id="98">The results achieved in the field of asylum system development in the Slovak Republic in recent years were significantly influenced by the cooperation and support of the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).</seg>
<seg id="99">A particular benefit was its financial contribution to the reconstruction of the housing stock for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="100">The UNHCR also co-financed social, cultural and sports activities for asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="101">4.1 Development of the number of asylum seekers and the results of the asylum process</seg>
<seg id="102">The development of the number of asylum seekers in the Czech Republic is shown in the chart.</seg>
<seg id="103">A significant increase occurred in 2001 due to the Kosovo crisis and an increase in the number of refugees from Chechnya manifested itself in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="104">An overview of the results of the asylum procedure in the Czech Republic is given in Table 1.</seg>
<seg id="105">In the audited period, asylum was granted in a total of 394 cases, of which 83 in 2001, 103 in 2002 and 208 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="106">In the audited period, asylum was not granted in total in 22 731 cases and in 22 636 cases the asylum procedure was stopped.</seg>
<seg id="107">The number of participants in the procedure as of 1.1. includes both persons who have not yet been issued with a decision and those who have not been handed a decision.</seg>
<seg id="108">Also included here are persons who have been forgiven for missing the deadline for lodging an appeal, or who have had a previous decision revoked and have not yet been issued with a new one.</seg>
<seg id="109">In the Slovak Republic, the number of asylum seekers is on a steadily increasing trend.</seg>
<seg id="110">While 96 applicants were registered in 1993, in 2003 it was already 10 358 persons.</seg>
<seg id="111">There was a significant increase in the number of applicants in 2001, when 8 131 applicants were registered, which represented an increase of 423% compared to 2000, in which 1 556 persons applied for asylum.</seg>
