<seg id="113">In the audited period, a total of 49 asylum seekers were granted and their number did not exceed 0.22% of the registered number of applicants in individual years.</seg>
<seg id="114">Asylum was not granted in 860 cases.</seg>
<seg id="115">The asylum procedure was stopped in a total of 23 088 cases.</seg>
<seg id="116">The majority of applicants voluntarily left the asylum procedure before its completion by staying away from the asylum facility without permission.</seg>
<seg id="117">In 2002 it was more than 82% of the total number of registered applicants and in 2003 it was already more than 94% of persons.</seg>
<seg id="118">The length of stay of one applicant in one of the asylum facilities, converted to an average number of days, was 13 days in 2001, 18 days in 2002 and 19 days in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="119">The findings of the Ministry also show that for most applicants entering the asylum process in the Slovak Republic it is a search for better living conditions, i.e. so-called economic migration, which is not supported by documents adopted by the international community, to which the Slovak Republic has also signed up.</seg>
<seg id="120">In these cases the asylum system is used by applicants for a purpose.</seg>
<seg id="121">An application for asylum based on economic reasons, such as seeking employment or better living conditions, is not a reason for granting asylum.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an application should be assessed as manifestly unfounded under the provisions of § 12(1)(a) of Act No 480/2002 Coll., on Asylum, and should be decided within 30 days.</seg>
<seg id="123">Internationally recognized principles for identification of economic migrants, which would distinguish them from applicants persecuted in the country of origin and which would make it possible to speed up the asylum process, have not yet been established.</seg>
<seg id="124">In view of the above, it can be concluded that the Slovak Republic is a transit country from the point of view of international migration, and the destination countries of migration have been and remain Western European states.</seg>
<seg id="125">Upon accession to the EU, the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic acceded to the Agreement determining the state responsible for examining asylum applications lodged in one of the Member States of the European Communities (Dublin Convention).</seg>
<seg id="126">The Convention prevents the submission of multiple targeted asylum applications in more than one EU country.</seg>
<seg id="127">After positive identification in the EURODAC system, applicants return to the country of first registration.</seg>
<seg id="128">The Slovak Republic is part of the external borders of the EU countries, therefore the application of the Dublin Convention may result in an increase in the number of applicants in the following period, who will need to create conditions for their stay in the Slovak Republic until a decision is taken on whether or not to grant asylum.</seg>
<seg id="129">4.2 Drawing on funds</seg>
<seg id="130">The Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic are obliged to provide financial and material security for asylum seekers in accordance with international agreements and the national legislative regulations based on them.</seg>
<seg id="131">The state budget of both countries allocates the necessary funds for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="132">The amount of expenditure drawn from the state budget is mainly influenced by the number of applicants, the duration of the asylum procedure until the final decision on granting asylum, as well as their state of health.</seg>
<seg id="133">The increasing number of people entering the asylum process has a direct impact on the higher uptake of statutory benefits for applicants, such as food expenses, pocket money, expenses for basic material equipment, other material equipment and other social contributions.</seg>
<seg id="134">The amount of some selected benefits is comparable in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="135">In the Czech Republic, during the audited period, meals were CZK 58 per person per day, pocket money was CZK 12 per person per day and CZK 6 per child up to 15 years of age.</seg>
<seg id="136">The costs per asylum seeker per stay day were on average CZK 351 in 2001, CZK 383 in 2002 and CZK 345 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="137">In addition to pocket money, asylum seekers accommodated in residential centres with independent cooking and applicants accommodated privately outside asylum facilities can be granted a contribution up to the minimum subsistence level.</seg>
<seg id="138">Act No. 325/1999 Coll., on Asylum, as amended, among other things grants municipalities the right to a contribution to reimburse costs incurred in connection with asylum facilities on their territory in Section 84.</seg>
<seg id="139">The amount of the allowance was set annually by government resolutions and in the audited period was CZK 7 per person per day of stay.</seg>
<seg id="140">At the same time, municipalities are granted a contribution to reimburse the non-investment costs of primary schools attended by asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="141">The amount of the allowance was CZK 120 per pupil per month in the audited period, provided that in the given month the person attended school for a minimum of 10 days.</seg>
<seg id="142">In the Slovak Republic, in the audited period, the meal allowance was SKK 70 per person per day, pocket money was SKK 12 per person per day and SKK 8 per child up to 15 years of age.</seg>
<seg id="143">The cost per asylum seeker per day of stay was on average SKK 442 in 2001, SKK 447 in 2002 and SKK 445 in 2003.</seg>
<seg id="144">Municipalities on whose territory an asylum facility is located are granted a contribution to partially reimburse the expenses incurred by the municipality in connection with the establishment and activities of the asylum facility, in accordance with Act No 480/2002 Coll., on Asylum.</seg>
<seg id="145">Municipalities have so far only partially used the possibility to apply for the contribution, which is set at 1 500 Sk per bed per calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="146">National legislation in both countries provides for a 90-day period from the start of the asylum procedure for issuing an asylum decision, while allowing for an extension of this period in justified cases.</seg>
<seg id="147">The most common reason for extending the asylum procedure, which affects the level of state budget expenditure, is the lodging of appeals against the decision not to grant asylum.</seg>
