<seg id="183">Expenditure per applicant per stay day was lower in these years.</seg>
<seg id="184">However, long-term maintenance of high filling capacity of these facilities is not possible.</seg>
<seg id="185">The risks of an unexpected influx of refugees and the associated demand for higher accommodation capacity must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="186">At the same time, it is not possible to carry out some repairs, maintenance and investments when the accommodation capacity is fully occupied.</seg>
<seg id="187">The form of asylum facilities operated under contract allows the adoption of operational solutions in the area of asylum facilities capacities if necessary.</seg>
<seg id="188">5.2 Asylum facilities in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="189">Asylum facilities are reception centres and residential centres.</seg>
<seg id="190">The Ministry has in its administration the reception centres Adamov-Gbely, Rohovce, Opatovská Nová Ves and the Brezová pod Bradlom residential centre.</seg>
<seg id="191">The total capacity of reception centres is 470 places and the residential centre 100 places.</seg>
<seg id="192">The increasing number of asylum seekers was solved by the Ministry by setting up a residential centre in Gabčíkov in the rented premises of the Slovak Technical University of Bratislava with a flexible available capacity of 250 to 940 places.</seg>
<seg id="193">According to the concluded contract, the renter also provides services related to the operation of the centre.</seg>
<seg id="194">In this form, the Ministry solved the lack of its own staff.</seg>
<seg id="195">The residential centre was also temporarily set up in 2002 and 2003 in the rented premises in Jazierciach with a capacity of 160 places.</seg>
<seg id="196">The reception centres had an average occupancy rate of 57% to 62% during the audited period, while the residential centres had an average occupancy rate of 33% to 50%.</seg>
<seg id="197">The occupancy rate varied according to the time of year and was highest in the last months of the year when a much larger number of asylum seekers applied for asylum compared to other months of the year.</seg>
<seg id="198">A further increase in accommodation capacities of about 450 places will be possible after the reconstruction of the centres in Opatovskej Novej Vsi and Vlachoch.</seg>
<seg id="199">After the completion of the centre in Humennom in 2006, the number of places will increase by another 550 persons.</seg>
<seg id="200">5.2.1 Costs of asylum facilities</seg>
<seg id="201">Data on the costs of running asylum facilities are given in Table 4.</seg>
<seg id="202">Their analysis shows that the operation of an asylum facility by another entity, which will provide premises and ensure the running of the facility, including related activities, is one of the options to ensure the tasks arising from the stay of asylum seekers in the Slovak Republic at a reasonable cost.</seg>
<seg id="203">6. Management of State Funds and Property</seg>
<seg id="204">6.1 Analysis of Management</seg>
<seg id="205">In the Czech Republic, in 2001, the approved budgetary expenditure of SUZ was increased by thirteen budgetary measures by CZK 103 077 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="206">Of this, CZK 89,979 thousand (87.29%) were earmarked funds. The bulk was intended to deal with the consequences of the Kosovo crisis (CZK 44,538 thousand) and to provide health care provided to asylum seekers (CZK 38,870 thousand).</seg>
<seg id="207">In 2002, the expenditures of SUZ were increased by 20 budgetary measures by CZK 88,362 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="208">Of this, CZK 62,282 thousand (70.48%) were earmarked funds, of which the bulk (CZK 53,200 thousand) was intended for health care provided to asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="209">In 2003, the expenditures of SUZ were increased by 14 budgetary measures by a total of CZK 88,078 thousand.</seg>
<seg id="210">Of this, CZK 82,000 thousand (93.09%) were earmarked funds released from the General Treasury Administration.</seg>
<seg id="211">The amount of CZK 51,000 thousand was intended for health care provided to asylum seekers, CZK 24,000 thousand for dealing with the influx of Chechen refugees and CZK 7,000 thousand for the humanitarian evacuation program of disabled residents of the Republic of Iraq.</seg>
<seg id="212">An overview of the use of selected expenditures of SUZ in the audited period is given in Table 5.</seg>
<seg id="213">From the above overview it is clear that the largest part of the expenses was spent on providing services.</seg>
<seg id="214">The amount of expenses incurred on the purchase of services ranged from 37.07% to 38.23% of the total expenses.</seg>
<seg id="215">The outrageous expenses in this item were expenses for accommodation and meals of asylum seekers in asylum facilities operated on the basis of a contract, expenses for medical care provided to asylum seekers and costs of permanent security service providing security in individual asylum facilities.</seg>
<seg id="216">Expenditure on salaries, payments for work done and insurance premiums (23.99% - 24.97%) accounted for a significant share of the total SUZ expenses.</seg>
<seg id="217">Last but not least, purchases of materials (approximately 14%) accounted for a significant share of the total SUZ expenses, with the largest share of these expenses having been the purchase of food (7.61% ? 9.83% of the total expenses).</seg>
<seg id="218">In the Slovak Republic, the budget management of the Ministry of Interior for securing migration policy and the asylum process was marked by more budgetary measures that addressed legitimate requirements related to the increase in the number of asylum seekers.</seg>
<seg id="219">The draft and breakdown of the budget in the expenditure part was characterised, especially in 2001 and 2002, by an imbalance between the requirements of the Ministry of Interior, which were based on the increase in the number of asylum seekers and on the need to finance their legal entitlements, and the resources provided, especially in the main category of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="220">The administrator of the budget chapter addressed the disproportion during the year with several budgetary measures, increasing the limit of current expenditure by 41.8% in 2001 and by as much as 71.7% in 2002.</seg>
<seg id="221">An overview of the execution of selected expenses of the Ministry of Interior in the audited period is given in Table 6.</seg>
<seg id="222">Expenditure on wages, salaries and insurance premiums in the range of 24.47% to 30.51% and expenditure on materials and services in the range of 21.04% to 38.82% of total expenditure accounted for a significant share of current expenditure.</seg>
<seg id="223">More than 10% were expenditures on security services and from 3.92% to 7.20% were expenditures on food purchases.</seg>
<seg id="224">Another significant part was expenditures on accommodation and catering services ranging from 10.82% to 26.96%.</seg>
<seg id="225">A relatively low share in the range from 1.03% to 6.25% were capital expenditures.</seg>
<seg id="226">6.2 Detected deficiencies</seg>
<seg id="227">The results of the audit in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic pointed to some similar deficiencies that did not have a major impact on the management of state funds and property.</seg>
<seg id="228">These were deficiencies in particular in the following areas: (a) the use of state budget funds contrary to the purpose for which they were determined by the Act on the State Budget, when current expenditures were paid for actions having the character of technical evaluation of long-term tangible assets; (b) violations of the Act on Accounting in the area of inventories and in non-compliance with the indicative chart of accounts.</seg>
<seg id="229">Furthermore, in the Czech Republic, minor deficiencies were found in the management of State property, when it was left for use by another person without a proper contract; failure to comply with the deadline for reporting changes to the Land Register data violated the Act on the Land Register; failure to leave waste for disposal to a person who was not a person authorised to handle waste violated the Act on Waste.</seg>
<seg id="230">Furthermore, in the Slovak Republic, deficiencies were found in the provision of unreasonably high advances for the collection of electricity and natural gas, deficiencies in public procurement and in the management of State property, when its records were not sufficiently secured and a method of liquidation of unneeded assets was not demonstrated.</seg>
<seg id="231">7. Internal control system</seg>
<seg id="232">In the Czech Republic, an internal control system within the meaning of the provisions of Act No 320/2001 Coll., on financial control, determining the competences of individual employees responsible for carrying out preliminary, continuous and subsequent control, was introduced at SUZ on 1 July 2002.</seg>
<seg id="233">At the same time, an internal audit system was introduced and an internal auditor of SUZ was appointed.</seg>
<seg id="234">Every year, SUZ is issued a plan of financial, social and operational technical controls aimed at comprehensive verification of the management of state funds and property in individual asylum facilities managed by SUZ.</seg>
<seg id="235">In 2002, 42 management controls were carried out and in 2003, 54 were carried out.</seg>
<seg id="236">In the Slovak Republic, the direct performance of control activities in the departments and organisations of the Ministry of Interior of the Slovak Republic with regard to compliance with generally binding legal regulations and internal regulations is ensured by the Office of Control of the Minister.</seg>
<seg id="237">During the audited period, the performance of tasks in the field of asylum policy was not audited.</seg>
<seg id="238">The internal control system of the Ministry of Interior is focused mainly on carrying out preliminary and interim financial control according to Act No 502/2001 Coll., on financial control and internal audit.</seg>
<seg id="239">The performance of financial control is also regulated by the internal regulations of the Director of the Ministry of Interior.</seg>
<seg id="240">The substantive focus of the control activities as part of the management of individual departments was determined in the framework of the annual plan of the Ministry of Interior.</seg>
<seg id="241">The directors of departments were designated as responsible for the performance of the control in this area.</seg>
<seg id="242">According to the submitted written documentation, no deficiencies were found.</seg>
<seg id="243">Since the date of the Regulation of the Ministry of Interior of the Slovak Republic No. 28 of April 23, 2004, the Ministry of Interior is obliged to handle and investigate complaints under the Complaints Act.</seg>
<seg id="244">The organisational security of this task will need to be solved in the near future.</seg>
