<p>
<seg id="1">Joint Report on Parallel Controls of Expenditure on the Prague – Dresden Motorway Construction</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory statement</seg>
<seg id="3">Without the existence of trans-European transport networks, it would be difficult to imagine a modern, dynamic and, above all, united Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">High-quality transport networks are a prerequisite for maintaining and increasing the standard of living of Europeans.</seg>
<seg id="5">Creating the conditions for fast, safe, reliable and cheap transport of people and goods is an important task for the state administration.</seg>
<seg id="6">It is a very demanding task, both organisationally and technically, as well as financially.</seg>
<seg id="7">European efforts at sustainable mobility often find it difficult to compromise with Europe's interest in maintaining a healthy and human-friendly environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Transport infrastructure construction, thanks to the necessary measures for the benefit of the environment, is financially demanding.</seg>
<seg id="9">Considerate procedures and decisions by the state administration in preparing and acquiring transport constructions can bring significant savings of public financial resources, which can be used in other ways for the benefit of citizens.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of audit institutions is to actively search for deficiencies that led to lower-than-achievable economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditures on transport infrastructure constructions.</seg>
<seg id="11">Audit institutions should not only alert the state administration to the detected deficiencies, but recommend measures that will lead to improvement of the situation, for the benefit of citizens, for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Short summary</seg>
<seg id="13">The two supreme audit institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic) the Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as the BRH) and the Supreme Audit Office (hereinafter referred to as the Supreme Audit Office (SAO) carried out parallel audits of expenditures on the construction of the Prague – Dresden motorway (the D8 motorway in the Czech Republic and the A17 motorway in the Federal Republic of Germany) in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="14">The motorways are connected by a border bridge, which is co-financed by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">Thanks to cooperation with the SAO, the BRH was able to carry out a thorough audit of the effectiveness of the funds spent on the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">Based on the close cooperation with the SAO, the SAO obtained the necessary data on the level of German costs of bridges and tunnels for comparative purposes.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany concluded a contract for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the construction process, the deadline for completion was finally scheduled for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the award procedure, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made errors, which led to an extension of the competition period and a shorter construction period.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was thus signed later than expected.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time and ensure its completion in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">As a result, the RMD had to accept a significant increase in the price of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the framework of the joint audits, the prices of bridges on the D8 and A17 motorways were compared, based on the calculation of the square metre area of the bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="24">Statistical analysis of the prices allowed to identify bridges with high costs per square metre of area.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis revealed that the border bridge was the most expensive bridge in the group of large bridges with a length of over 100 meters.</seg>
<seg id="26">The price increase could also be attributed to the delay that occurred during the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="27">In the analysis of the tunnel construction costs, the auditors found that the tunnel prices on the D8 motorway were significantly higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and the SAO now have a database of the prices of bridges and tunnels on which they will be able to rely in future checks of the efficiency of the means used for transport infrastructure purposes.</seg>
<seg id="29">For the construction of bridges, the two auditing institutions recommend: standardization of the bridge construction and the use of combined steel-concrete and special structures only in cases where prestressed reinforced concrete bridges are not adequate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The main features of the cooperation included its team spirit and informality.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel inspection, the auditors shared their specific knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report reports on the progress and results of the parallel audits of funds spent on the construction of the motorway connecting Dresden and Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The audits focused on the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenses incurred.</seg>
<seg id="35">Parallel audits were carried out by BRH in Germany and by the SAO in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="36">Parallel audits were carried out in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The SAO audited the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditures amounting to approximately CZK 20 billion including VAT (approximately EUR 690 million) on the border section of the D 8 motorway, which is numbered 0807.</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, EUR 64 million from European funds (ISPA) were planned to be used.</seg>
<seg id="39">In addition to the parallel audits carried out jointly with the SAO, BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The funds spent on the construction of all three sections of the A 17 motorway amounted to approximately EUR 670 million, of which EUR 277 million will be co-financed by European funds (EFRE).</seg>
<seg id="41">The motorway from Prague to Dresden is part of the Trans-European Transport Corridor IV. Dresden – Central and Southern parts of Eastern Europe – Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 motorway runs from Prague through Ústí nad Labem to the state border.</seg>
<seg id="43">The A 17 motorway runs from the state border of the Czech Republic/Germany to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the audits, the border sections of the two motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">These sections were put into operation on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">On the German side, the motorway is completed as far as Dresden, while on the Czech side of the D 8 motorway it is not completed because the section No 0805, which is 16.4 km long across the Bohemian Central Mountains between Řehlovice and Lovosice, is still in the preparatory phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">According to the plan, the section No 0805 between Prague and Ústí nad Labem is to pass through the protected landscape area of the Bohemian Central Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to forecasts carried out in the Czech Republic in 2001, the traffic intensity on the border section No 0807 of the D 8 motorway should be 22,940 vehicles per day in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="49">According to German forecasts, the traffic intensity on the Czech border will total about 25,000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, Germany and the Czech Republic concluded the Contract between the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic for the interconnection of the German A 17 motorway and the Czech D 8 motorway on the common state border by the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Both states are involved in the construction of the bridge, therefore the control of the construction of this bridge was an important aspect of the parallel controls carried out by the two audit institutions.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and the SAO</seg>
<seg id="53">Since mid-2005, the two supreme audit institutions have been discussing close cooperation in the control of the construction of the motorway connecting Prague and Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had serious reasons for such cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">The SRN is financially involved in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Its planning and construction is based on the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="58">Therefore, BRH itself did not have the opportunity to carry out the control of this construction project.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The SAO did not have the comparative database needed to assess whether the funds were used in a cost-effective manner with regard to the overall level of the costs of bridges and tunnels on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO needed to make sure that the expenditures were effective with regard to the main technical parameters of the motorway, especially the arrangement of bridges and tunnels, which should allow for the same quality of travel on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">After the preparatory negotiations, the Agreement on the Coordinated Inspection of the D 8/A motorway 17 was signed by the presidents of both supreme audit institutions on 4 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">The joint working meetings of the auditors of BRH and the SAO took place at an interval of approximately six to eight weeks throughout 2006.</seg>
<seg id="65">The meetings dealt with current problems and tasks, in particular the preparation of a uniform methodology for the control of the prices of bridges and tunnels, the exchange of findings from the inspection of the construction of the border bridge and the preparation of joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">An important sign of cooperation was the continuous exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="67">While BRH carried out most of the work on the comparison of technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and the tendering procedure, the SAO prepared for the most part the methodology for the control of the prices of bridges and tunnels.</seg>
<seg id="68">The applicable legal standards for control in the state administration differ in the way the auditing operations are concluded in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="69">For these reasons, the two supreme audit institutions drew their own audit conclusions on their findings obtained during their audits.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report reflects the results achieved during the parallel audits.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation will be concluded by the signing of the final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the Border Bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">The Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed in a contract from 2000 on a date of completion of the construction of the border bridge in 2005, if possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">Both parties then agreed to postpone this date until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as an investor.</seg>
<seg id="76">The SRN contributes financially to the construction of the bridge from 42.13%.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the period up to 1999, the RMD proposed that the border bridge should have a prestressed reinforced concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, in agreement with its partners in Germany, the RMD agreed on a coupled steel-concrete structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">This decision was justified by the reduction of the number of double pillars from seven to five and the consequent environmental benefits of such a solution for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">Moreover, comparative calculations carried out by the RMD indicated that the combined steel-concrete structure should be a less costly option.</seg>
<seg id="81">However, there was an error in the calculations.</seg>
<seg id="82">It was stated that the new combined steel-concrete structure would be only 397 m long.</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it is 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award of the border bridge contract, the RMD made serious errors.</seg>
<seg id="85">It did not prepare the contract documentation adequately describing the assessment criteria and sub-criteria for comparing the bids.</seg>
<seg id="86">This error led to the evaluation committee and the general manager evaluating the bids in a subjective and problematic manner.</seg>
<seg id="87">The unsuccessful bidder challenged the results of the contract procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">A subsequent investigation by the Office for the Protection of Competition led to the contract for the construction being signed later than originally calculated.</seg>
<seg id="89">This meant that the 2004 summer construction season, after the evaluation of the bids, was wasted and the construction period shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The construction company agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time, but at the cost of a substantial increase in costs.</seg>
<seg id="91">The procedure offered included the double assembly of the bridge superstructure, a change in the structure of the pillars and the installation and fitting-out of the assembly area.</seg>
<seg id="92">Moreover, the construction company was not able to procure the type of steel originally proposed in due time.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel – at a higher price of about €4 million, which had to be fully paid by the RMD – allowed for a shortening of the time to perform corrosion protection, which in turn allowed for a shortening of the total construction period of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the net price of €18.3 million offered in the tender, the total cost of building the border bridge will increase considerably due to the accelerated procedure and other modifications in the financing.</seg>
<seg id="95">The shortened construction period led to a price increase of about €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">Currently, the net cost amount is around €25.9 million, not taking into account the automatic price increase (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of bridge and tunnel prices</seg>
<seg id="98">The two supreme audit institutions carried out an analysis of bridge prices on the D 8 and A 17 motorways in order to identify bridges whose price was too high and to compare bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The analysis was based on methods of mathematical statistics.</seg>
<seg id="100">Furthermore, the tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the motorways in Germany (A 71, A 38 and A 4).</seg>
<seg id="101">There are no similar tunnels on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="102">In preparing this part of the inspection, it was important to identify the relevant prices accurately.</seg>
<seg id="103">The two supreme audit institutions set the following principles for comparing bridge prices: to base the actual price paid for the bridge excluding value added tax (VAT rates differ in the Czech Republic and the SNR and are subject to changes); not to take into account the prices for the special foundations of the bridge; to convert the prices in CZK into € according to the European Central Bank rate in force on 30.12.2005 (CZK 29 = € 1).</seg>
<seg id="104">On both D 8 and A 17 there are bridges of different constructions (steel-concrete, prestressed reinforced concrete, combined steel-concrete and steel) and different sizes.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the homogeneity of the constructions examined, the bridges were divided into groups according to the type of construction.</seg>
<seg id="106">Within these groups, the size of the bridge was also taken into account in the analyses.</seg>
<seg id="107">Concrete bridges on both sides of the border were by far the most common type of construction (20 bridges on D 8, 36 bridges on A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The analysis focused mainly on this group of bridges, as the number of bridges allowed the use of mathematical-statistical methods with a high degree of reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The inspections found that the prices per m 2 of concrete bridges on both D 8 and A 17 depended on the size of the bridge (its length, area): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per m2 of the bridge structure.</seg>
<seg id="110">In the case of German bridges, the dependence of the price on the size was stronger than in the case of Czech bridges (see the graphs below).</seg>
<seg id="111">Two concrete bridges on A 17 and four on D 8 were identified, the price of which is significantly higher.</seg>
<seg id="112">In order to find these bridges, a method was used to identify atypical values in a set of numbers, on the one hand, and a regression analysis taking into account the dependence of the price of the bridge on its size (the distance from the regression curve upwards is decisive for the determination of atypically expensive bridges).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, information on the atypical high price of these bridges should be considered only as an indicator of which bridges should be targeted.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw a generally applicable conclusion, the causes of the high price in each identified case should be analysed.</seg>
<seg id="115">One such cause may be inefficient administrative measures, or also environmental protection requirements or other plausible reason.</seg>
<seg id="116">Considering that Czech concrete bridges are on average longer than German ones (see table below), the proven negative dependence of the price of the bridge on its length could lead to the assumption that Czech bridges should be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">The hypothesis of lower prices of Czech concrete bridges is also supported by lower labour costs in the construction industry in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">On the contrary, the results of the analysis show that the prices of concrete bridges on D 8 are higher than on A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During the joint negotiations, two possible causes of this state of affairs were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, most bridges are awarded as separate contracts.</seg>
<seg id="122">Such an award allows small and medium-sized regional firms to participate in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of the contract for a part of the motorway route, which is several kilometres long.</seg>
<seg id="124">Small and medium-sized firms do not participate in such a tender because the contract is too big for them.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic, there is more variability in the construction of bridges than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the SAO found that the type of bridge construction is decided long before the bridge is built.</seg>
<seg id="128">The decision is taken at the time when the SAO submits the application for a zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this time, the SAD selects types of bridges from several variants, but economy plays a smaller role in the decision.</seg>
<seg id="130">A general conclusion on the prices of bridges in the Czech Republic and Germany could be reached only on the basis of a thorough analysis of the construction works market in both countries, which would go beyond this control action.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive coupled steel concrete bridge on D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of tunnels, the prices of tunnels on D 8 were found to be twice as high as those in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the main construction-technical parameters of tunnels on D 8 with those in Germany did not show any substantial difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">Significant price differences could be attributed to the fact that there is no real competition in the tunnel construction sector in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow for generally applicable conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Effectiveness and efficiency of the Dresden-Prague motorway construction</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was established in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">The government approved the concept of the motorway network development in the same year.</seg>
<seg id="139">The D 8 motorway was to be gradually extended from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section No 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains was to be acquired before the border section No 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic acquires the D 8 motorway as part of the programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">The programme No 327 220 "Construction of the D 8 motorway Prague – Ústí nad Labem – state border of the Czech Republic/Germany" set two objectives for the construction of the D 8 motorway:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">to improve the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem – a national objective;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">to improve the connection between Prague and Berlin within the framework of the IV Trans-European Transport Corridor Berlin – Istanbul – an international objective.</seg>
<seg id="147">According to the programme, the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Highlands was to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of the border section No 0807 in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be added that the completion date is not identical to the date of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">The SAO found that the preparation of the construction of the section leading through the Czech Central Highlands is now at the stage of an official zoning decision.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental activists challenged this decision with legal actions.</seg>
<seg id="151">The legal action is not final.</seg>
<seg id="152">It cannot therefore be excluded that the section leading through the Czech Central Highlands will be completed several years later than indicated in the programme documentation.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed to postpone the completion date of the section No 0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result of the above mentioned facts, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national goal of improving the connection between Prague and Ústí nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD carried out an estimate of capital expenditures for the border section D 8 No 0807 and section No 0805 through the Czech Central Mountains in the years 1999-2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">The estimate of the capital expenditures included in these capital expenditures amounts to about 639 million € for both sections No 0805 and No 0807 together.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the economic assessment (EIRR = internal rate of profitability)</seg>
<seg id="158">All considered motorways and expressways opened, both sections D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">On the northern part of the border section traffic intensity of 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="160">All considered motorways and expressways opened, both sections D 8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">On the northern part of the border section traffic intensity of 22,000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="162">All motorways and express roads under consideration opened, both sections of D8 opened in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">On the northern part of the border section, the traffic intensity of 25 000 vehicles per day in 2010</seg>
<seg id="164">The economic analysis carried out in 2001 was based on the assumption that the border section and the section through the Bohemian Central Highlands would be completed on time.</seg>
<seg id="165">However, at the time of the inspection, it is clear that the section through the Bohemian Central Highlands will not be opened at the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This will reduce the above mentioned EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The cost of both sections, net of VAT, calculated as at 31.12.2005, was €897 million, i.e. higher by 27.4% than the cost level worked out by the economic analysis in 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">However, there is a risk that section 0805 will be run on a different, more expensive route, which would affect the above mentioned economic viability threshold.</seg>
<seg id="169">The economic analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically viable at a traffic intensity of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="170">The forecast for 2008 was 22,940 vehicles, but the study dealing with the issue of bypass routes for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains calculates traffic intensity of 12,600 to 13,750 vehicles per day, which pushes the investment below the limit of economic viability.</seg>
<seg id="171">With a higher load on bypass routes for the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains, there is a high probability of congestion and thus an increase in external costs, which were not foreseen in the original economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The above-mentioned decrease in revenues and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR that the construction of the border section D 8 should have had will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">Construction of the D 8 border section is therefore inefficient.</seg>
<seg id="174">Also during the construction of the A 17 motorway, there were similar cost overruns as in the case of these two sections on D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment of the federal road development plan for long-distance transport for 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport of Germany projected costs of about 320 million €.</seg>
<seg id="176">The resulting cost/benefit ratio was then 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, however, the cost had risen sharply to about €670 million and the cost-benefit ratio had been more than halved.</seg>
<seg id="178">In addition to the parallel inspection carried out jointly with the SAO, the BRH audited the preparation and construction of the A 17 motorway in 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="179">The BRH found that the competent state approval authority had requested an off-road tunnel for the third section of the A 17, which was not needed.</seg>
<seg id="180">During the auditing operation, the BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the German Road Construction Administration that the tunnel was not necessary.</seg>
<seg id="181">The result was savings, which amounted to about €10 million in construction costs alone and €0.15 million in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">When assessing the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction project had not been properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">This is illustrated by the following example:</seg>
<seg id="184">In the preparatory stage, the Road Construction Administration did not carry out a survey of the bedrock conditions in the Dölzschen rocks, as the site was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">This was carried out only after the tunnel digging machine had hit the rock.</seg>
<seg id="186">Tests showed that the rocks were more weathered inside than anticipated during the tender.</seg>
<seg id="187">Therefore, costly measures such as anchoring, injection and safety nets against falling rocks had to be taken, which cost about €3.3 million.</seg>
<seg id="188">The Road and Motorway Directorate had to bear the costs not only of other emergency operations such as safety measures in the Dölzschen rocks, but also of measures that would not have been necessary if the construction project had been properly prepared first.</seg>
<seg id="189">Expenditure of this kind includes costs related to interruption of construction operations (€3.2 million), additional training of drilling staff (€0.5 million) and increasing wages and expenditure on goods due to the project's exceeding duration (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">The cost overruns thus amounted to about €10.7 million, which did not correspond to any added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">Based on the lessons learned from this and other audited projects, BRH asked the Federal Ministry to apply stricter guidance in its supervision of road construction works.</seg>
<seg id="192">The Federal Ministry should give the road and motorway directorates the necessary impetus to implement quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of cooperation for BRH and the SAO The cooperation fulfilled the intention of both auditing institutions.</seg>
<seg id="194">BRH gained audit knowledge about the preparation, assignment and progress of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">Both supreme auditing institutions built a database of bridge and tunnel prices on which future audits could be based.</seg>
<seg id="196">The SAO found that the main construction and technical parameters of bridges, tunnels and the route of the D 8 motorway did not differ from the parameters of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">Auditors of both institutions involved in the cooperation gained new experience which can be used in further audits.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
