<p>
<seg id="1">Public works procurement and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report on parallel audits carried out by the Czech Supreme Audit Office (SAO) and the German Federal Court of Auditors (BRH)</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">Public procurement of goods and services by contracting authorities is very important for both the state and the private sector.</seg>
<seg id="5">The role of the state is to use public resources in the most efficient and economical way and to ensure fair and regulated free competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), public procurement is a key factor for the success of the single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">The EU has set limits in its regulations above which the contracting authority must comply with certain requirements designed to guarantee a wide and unlimited competitive environment throughout the EU.</seg>
<seg id="8">EU Member States must therefore transpose European procurement law into their national legislation and put it into practice.</seg>
<seg id="9">Both the Czech Republic and Germany have already done so.</seg>
<seg id="10">For public contracts below the EU thresholds, the regulation of their awarding remains the responsibility of individual countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In addition, public procurement is prone to corruption with a consequent high potential for damage.</seg>
<seg id="12">Therefore, contracting authorities are obliged to take reasonable measures in their procurement procedures to prevent corruption and unfair favouritism (prevention of corruption).</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Czech SAI – SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors of Germany (German SAI – BRH) agreed to perform parallel audits in the area of procurement procedures and prevention of corruption in land and transport constructions.</seg>
<seg id="14">The cooperation was also focused on the area of European procurement law as transposed into national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="15">The audits also included awarding contracts below the European thresholds in order to sanction the area of prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit findings of the two supreme audit institutions are summarised in a joint report, which is among others addressed to international organizations such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="17">Audit areas and audited institutions</seg>
<seg id="18">The evaluation of the BRH is based on general audits of the aforementioned areas, which were carried out at the German building administrations responsible for federal transport and land constructions between 2011 and 2012.</seg>
<seg id="19">For example, motorway constructions and large-scale construction projects were evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="20">The BRH also included findings from past audits in the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="21">The evaluation of the SAO is based on audits carried out during the years 2008 to 2012, which focused on the construction of roads, railway lines, water projects, large buildings (hospitals, cultural facilities, universities) and some other constructions in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, federal public procurement is mostly carried out by the regional building administrations.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, public procurement in the area of transport infrastructure is the responsibility of state institutions for road and railway construction.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the area of building construction, public procurement is carried out by entities that receive budgetary funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, the services of external experts are also used in the individual stages of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="26">The evaluation must take into account differences in public procurement legislation and the specificities of the construction market in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of the Public Procurement Act in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the course of European procurement procedures is governed by laws and sub-statutory standards.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to Germany are governed by budgetary law and relevant administrative acts .</seg>
<seg id="30">Internal administrative rules contain numerous additional provisions for both European and national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="31">Further details regarding the requirements of European procurement law and the prevention of corruption are enshrined in the so-called procurement manuals of the federal government, in which the requirements are elaborated or formulated in greater detail with regard to legal precedents in the field of procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, public procurement is governed by the Public Procurement Act and other legislation that relates to contracts with a value above and below European thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">Procurement law underwent substantial changes in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules reinforced the transparency of procurement procedures, opened up space for more competition and limited opportunities for corruption in the course of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic aspects of procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">As regards European procurement procedures, open and restricted procedures in particular must be applied in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, contracts below the European threshold are awarded in accordance with national rules (public call for competition, restricted call for competition, negotiated procedures), however, these are practically identical to the above-mentioned conditions for European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement in Germany is characterised by the principle of preference for open procedures (where candidates are invited on a European scale) and public calls for participation (only in the case of national procedures).</seg>
<seg id="39">In open procedures and in calls for competition, any candidate can submit a bid.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another important feature of German procurement law is the support of small and medium-sized firms.</seg>
<seg id="41">This is achieved mainly by dividing the total public contract into business-specific parts and by dividing it into sub-contracts.</seg>
<seg id="42">By awarding contracts divided into these parts, the chances of participating in the procedure are given to the largest possible number of candidates.</seg>
<seg id="43">The two characteristics of German procurement law are time-tested tools for obtaining good value for money.</seg>
<seg id="44">There are more than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees registered in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, the conditions of European procedures must be applied also in cases of public procurement with a value below the EU limit.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception is the simplified below-threshold procedure, where the contracting authority may use less demanding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with European law, Czech procurement law includes the conditions under which the contract must be awarded in order to ensure competition and achieve a favourable price.</seg>
<seg id="48">Current Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to choose between an open procedure and a restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are 85,000 construction companies registered in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 have 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Total volume of contracting authorities' public works contracts and proportion of individual procedures in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In 2011, the total volume of construction works in Germany amounted to EUR 7 675 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">CZK 1,138 billion (15 %) of which was accounted for by the share of public contracts which, in addition to those awarded by the federal government, included contracts awarded by individual Länder and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The total volume of projects of federal road and land constructions (without the construction of railways and water constructions) amounted to CZK 212.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the composition of federal works and transport contracts was as follows: 80,7 % open procedures and public calls; 12,7 % restricted management and calls;</seg>
<seg id="55">6.6% negotiated procedures and direct award of contracts; 33.2% is the share of European procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction contracts in the Czech Republic reached 118.6 billion CZK in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction works.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, the value reached CZK 194.0 billion, which was 37% of the total.</seg>
<seg id="58">Structure of tender types in 2011: 65,1 % open procedures; 14,3 % restricted procedures; 9.5% negotiated procedures; 8.4% simplified procedures for low-threshold contracts; 2.7% other proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="59">The figures include all public supply, service and works contracts awarded by contracting authorities in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">The figures show that: parallel controls in both countries were focused on a substantial part of public procurement procedures; prevention of corruption, which must be kept in mind during procurement procedures, has a significant financial impact; open significance. procurement procedures are of key importance.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of main results</seg>
<seg id="62">The SAO and BRH carried out parallel controls on the procurement of European works contracts with an emphasis on prevention of corruption in their respective countries.</seg>
<seg id="63">The audits were focused on comparing the legislation in both countries and the EU and on the implementation of public contracts in the field of land and transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">The following are the key findings:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU Public Procurement Directive has been transposed into the national laws of both countries (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">Prevention of corruption is not only the aim of the EU Directive, but also the national procurement rules of both countries, which differ partly in terms of focus and details.</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, the basic requirement to be met by the procurement documents is the inclusion of all information needed for the preparation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The specifications must be neutral and must not contain any requirements restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">The procurement documents in Germany generally meet these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, the problem is an insufficient definition of the subject matter of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, the division of contracts into parts where possible is required in order to promote a competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the BRH's findings, this requirement is respected in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The SAO's audits showed that in the Czech Republic very large public works in the field of road construction are awarded without being divided into parts or only into very significant parts in volume. This method can distort competition and lead to restrictions on only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">These limitations on market potential can result in significant cost increases and risk of unserious price negotiations and inadmissible agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">The legislation in both countries allows contracting authorities, under certain conditions, to award additional works retrospectively if the need arises after the conclusion of the contract (point 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">In both countries, the requirements for correctly determining the type of procurement procedure are met.</seg>
<seg id="77">In the Czech Republic, under the applicable rules, contracting authorities are free to determine one of the open procurement procedures, namely the open procedure or the restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="78">The German rules in procurement and budget law enshrine the preference for open procedures for both European tenders and national tenders, known as public calls for competition.</seg>
<seg id="79">The open procurement procedures in both countries allow a larger range of candidates to submit a tender and also reduce the risk of corruption as they make it more difficult to negotiate prices illegally between candidates.</seg>
<seg id="80">At the same time, the best value for money results are achieved.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of large contracts where the estimated total price reaches or exceeds the EU thresholds, the audited contracting entities have always issued a European tender.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct estimation of the estimated value of the contract plays a very important role in determining the type of tender.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, databases are used for objective pricing of public works, in which values are based on completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="84">This is a sufficiently objective tool.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, databases are used only in the field of road construction, but they are not yet an effective tool (point 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">When awarding a public works contract under European tendering procedures, it is necessary to publish prior information and a contract notice in order to strengthen competition by allowing candidates to prepare in time for the submission of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the construction audited impad with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In isolated cases, errors in the information released, incorrect application of provisions and/or a lack of controls may have impaired competition (item 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">When selecting candidates to participate in a restricted procurement procedure, there is a greater risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of candidates invited must be high enough to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">Selection criteria must be objective, non-discriminatory and published well in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">Beyond the EU requirements, contracting entities in both countries should rotate as often as possible candidates invited to participate in the procedure when selecting suppliers.</seg>
<seg id="93">In Germany, there are partly very detailed requirements to prevent risks of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="94">In some cases, the audited contracting entities did not follow these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, selection decisions were not always credible (section 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, contracting entities must ensure during the procurement procedure that all candidates who wish to submit a tender receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Any agreements between these candidates and between them and third parties involved in the preparation of the specifications must be prevented as far as possible in order to avoid restricting competition in the form of illegal agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">In Germany, the relevant measures are more thorough than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, the audited German contracting entities did not comply with this requirement in several cases (point 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">In both countries, the principle of cross-checking and transparency must be applied when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements on the marking, documentation, protection and confidentiality of tenders are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and in Germany they are particularly detailed.</seg>
<seg id="102">Checks in both countries found only a few cases of irregularities (point 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">The evaluation and evaluation of tenders is regulated procedurally in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">The relevant German measures are more comprehensive, but they were not always respected by the audited contracting entities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting authorities passed their tenders to third parties for consultation without prior assessment, without properly documenting any suspicious circumstances.</seg>
<seg id="106">Thus, tenders were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (point 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">For reasons of legal protection, bidders must be informed about the intended award of the contract before the contract is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection award is designed to prevent corruptive procedures before the contract is finalised.</seg>
<seg id="109">The law of the Czech Republic provides for judicial review of the contracts for national contractors.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in few cases, the due review of the enterprises was not ensured (item 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The tender documentation was not always complete or fully credible for the audited contracting authorities in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In the case of several procurement procedures, the transparency requirements applied at European level were not always adequately respected in the tender minutes.</seg>
<seg id="113">In addition, some deficiencies identified reduced the preventive anti-corruption function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">Contracting entities in both countries mostly fulfilled their reporting obligations (point 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Summary of the main principles of European procurement law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">European procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure free competition in the EU, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, a Directive on the coordination of procedures for the award of public works contracts, public supply contracts and public service contracts to ensure the free movement of goods and services and a Directive on the coordination of laws, regulations and administrative provisions relating to the application of review procedures to the award of public supply contracts and public works contracts (the Remedies Directive), both of which were to be transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The EU's general procurement principles include in particular: a requirement for a competitive environment; a requirement for equal treatment or non-discrimination; a requirement for transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">EU procurement principles include In addition, the Directive on the coordination of public procurement procedures includes provisions concerning construction projects with a total estimated value of €5 million or more.</seg>
