<seg id="358">The prevention of corruption is significantly reinforced as the pool of candidates is not limited by decisions taken in advance by the contracting authority, which thus gives room for manipulation and fixing of prices between bidders.</seg>
<seg id="359">Studies have confirmed the advantages of the German provision on the preference of open procedures or public calls for participation.</seg>
<seg id="360">Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to award contracts in open or narrower procedures.</seg>
<seg id="361">However, the latest legislation of the Public Procurement Act introduces a prohibition for contracting authorities to limit the number of bidders in narrower procedures.</seg>
<seg id="362">The narrower procedure has now come very close to the open procedure.</seg>
<seg id="363">In Germany, contracting authorities are largely fulfilling the requirement of preference for open procedures or public calls for competition, while in the Czech Republic some projects were divided in violation of the law, in order to circumvent the requirement to choose the appropriate type of procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="364">However, in the case of some projects implemented in Germany, European limits have not been respected, resulting in a lack of a minimum share in pan-European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="365">In the Czech Republic, a satisfactory system has not yet been put in place to facilitate the correct calculation of the expected costs of works and projects.</seg>
<seg id="366">Where appropriate, contracting entities should ensure, through more extensive controls, that the requirements to choose the type of procurement procedure and the volume of contracts awarded in European procedures are fulfilled, or they should create such conditions as are necessary to enable the correct calculation of the expected costs.</seg>
<seg id="367">Preliminary information and notice of initiation</seg>
<seg id="368">In cases where contracts are awarded in the framework of the European procedure, the contracting entity must publish a tender report.</seg>
<seg id="369">Preliminary information and contract notice are an important basis for European competition.</seg>
<seg id="370">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="371">By means of prior notices, the contracting authority must indicate the basic specifications of the intended projects.</seg>
<seg id="372">Preliminary notices are required for projects where the estimated total cost is equal to or greater than the European limit and when the contracting authority wishes to shorten the deadline for submitting tenders in individual procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="373">The contracting authority is obliged to publish a contract award notice with detailed information for all public contracts requiring the European procedure.</seg>
<seg id="374">The information is binding on the contracting authority after publication.</seg>
<seg id="375">Among other things, the notice must contain the specifications, the time limits for the procedure and for completion of the contract, the specific requirements and selection criteria and their weightings.</seg>
<seg id="376">A common procurement dictionary must be used to describe the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="377">Preliminary information and contract notices are published in the EU in the Official Journal of the EU and on the profile of the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="378">In order to avoid discrimination against foreign candidates, notices at national level should not contain any additional information and should not be published before the text of the notice is sent to the Publications Office of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="379">Incomplete or inaccurate information in a pre-notification may distort competition or even facilitate manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="380">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="381">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="382">Both countries have fully implemented the EU provisions on pre-information and contract award notices in their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="383">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="384">In the Czech Republic, pre-information and notices must be published even in the case of contracts for which a European procedure is not required.</seg>
<seg id="385">The procurement procedure may not start until one month after the pre-notification has been sent.</seg>
<seg id="386">The publication of the pre-information may be waived only in exceptional cases.</seg>
<seg id="387">In Germany, pre-information is not required in cases where a European procedure is not required.</seg>
<seg id="388">In the case of national procedures, the public call must be published on the federal government website and, where appropriate, in the press.</seg>
<seg id="389">In the case of restricted procedures without competition from participants, the notice must be published when the estimated contract price is equal to or higher than €25,000 ($625,000).</seg>
<seg id="390">The prior information notices must explain all the planned parts of the project.</seg>
<seg id="391">This is an important requirement given the number of small contracts in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="392">The splitting of projects into smaller parts is not as common in the Czech Republic and this measure is considered to be less important.</seg>
<seg id="393">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="394">BRH</seg>
<seg id="395">Preliminary notice</seg>
<seg id="396">Contracting authorities published a prior information notice for projects which included works to be awarded in the European procedure.</seg>
<seg id="397">In some open procedures, they shortened the time limit, although the number of days between the prior information notice being sent and the contract notice being sent was less than 52 days.</seg>
<seg id="398">In other abridged procedures, the annual time limits applicable to the prior information had expired and were to be renewed.</seg>
<seg id="399">In many cases, the advance notice did not indicate the anticipated division of the works into several parts.</seg>
<seg id="400">Procurement notice</seg>
<seg id="401">Some notices contained codes from the common dictionary that deviated from the content of the advance notice or did not specify precisely the works to be carried out.</seg>
<seg id="402">In rare cases, the notice at national level included more information, e.g. concerning performance deadlines, or was published before the notice was published in the Official Journal of the EU.</seg>
<seg id="403">Ex-ante transparency</seg>
<seg id="404">One contracting authority hired an external company to publish the national notice.</seg>
<seg id="405">The company published the notice on its platform, the use of which was subject to a fee.</seg>
<seg id="406">However, the contracting authority did not check whether the company had to comply with the requirement to send further notices to a free internet government portal.</seg>
<seg id="407">On a sample, it was found that only one third of the notices were actually published on the government portal.</seg>
<seg id="408">SAO</seg>
<seg id="409">Procurement notice</seg>
<seg id="410">In the construction of the wastewater treatment plant, the contracting authority did not set criteria in the notice of the tender procedure for the construction contractor, according to which it would reduce the large number of bids for the evaluation procedure.</seg>
<seg id="411">The contracting authority was not able to demonstrate the method of selection (reduction) of the bids for the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="412">The reduction of the number of bids was allowed by previous legislation.</seg>
<seg id="413">In the construction of the road circuit, the contracting authority did not define in the notice of the tender procedure or in the qualification documentation the values by which it would assess the degree of fulfilment of the qualification criteria or the number of bidders to be invited.</seg>
<seg id="414">The contracting authority evaluated the fulfilment of the qualification so that all six candidates in the tender procedure fulfilled it, but excluded one of them as having fulfilled it only in the last sixth place.</seg>
<seg id="415">The procedure of the contracting authority was not transparent as it did not publish in advance information on what of the qualification data would be evaluated and how.</seg>
<seg id="416">Publication of invitations</seg>
<seg id="417">For building modifications in former military installations, the contracting authority did not publish a written call for tenders in violation of the law.</seg>
<seg id="418">Conclusions and recommendations / Summary</seg>
<seg id="419">The two-stage information process with prior information and publication of a notice of initiation is an important tool for meeting the requirements for transparency and strengthening the competitive environment applied in European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="420">By extending the obligation to publish prior information in the Czech Republic also for national procurement procedures and by strengthening this obligation in Germany for restricted procedures, both countries have increased the transparency of procurement procedures and improved the competitive environment.</seg>
<seg id="421">Selection of candidates in restricted procurement procedures</seg>
<seg id="422">Compared to open procedures, restricted procurement procedures do not allow participation of all potential bidders who would be interested.</seg>
<seg id="423">In restricted procedures, the contracting authority first selects potential suppliers who will be asked to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="424">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="425">EU provisions allow to limit the number of bidders in European restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="426">However, the restricted procedure requires at least five bidders to be invited to submit a tender, and in the case of a negotiated procedure with publication, at least three potential bidders must be invited.</seg>
<seg id="427">In any case, the number of bidders invited must be sufficiently broad to guarantee genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="428">The selection criteria must be objective and non-discriminatory and must be published in advance.</seg>
<seg id="429">The selection of potential bidders who will be invited is very susceptible to manipulation, e.g. the preferences of some of them.</seg>
<seg id="430">Reducing competition to a few bidders can facilitate their collusion.</seg>
<seg id="431">This has a negative impact on the outcome of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="432">Therefore, the contracting authority must take measures to prevent manipulation and ensure that it has effective control in order to make the procedure transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="433">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="434">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="435">The provisions for the selection of bidders are similar in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="436">In addition to the requirements of the European directive, contracting authorities should rotate the tenderers they invite to submit a tender.</seg>
<seg id="437">It is also not permissible to restrict competition from a regional point of view.</seg>
<seg id="438">Contracting authorities must document and justify the selection of tenderers and the selection process.</seg>
<seg id="439">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="440">In Germany, at least three tenderers are required to be invited in the case of a restricted procedure and several suitable tenderers in the case of a negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="441">Except in two cases, the new Czech regulations do not allow limiting the number of tenderers approached in the case of a restricted and negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="442">In Germany, the "four eyes principle" must be respected in the selection of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="443">While one worker proposes their list, another must substantially modify the proposal, e.g. by removing the proposed tenderer or appointing another.</seg>
<seg id="444">This is to avoid a situation where an individual can definitively determine the range of tenderers who will take part in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="445">If such a provision is not in place, a far-reaching illegal agreement between the participants is allowed.</seg>
<seg id="446">The list of tenderers who will be invited to submit a tender must be confidential and must not be divulged.</seg>
<seg id="447">Authorised independent experts are also obliged to do so.</seg>
<seg id="448">There is no similar measure in the Czech Republic, nor is there any measure for confidential treatment of the list of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="449">According to the German provisions, external companies may not designate candidates, but they may make proposals to the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="450">There is no similar requirement in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="451">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="452">BRH</seg>
<seg id="453">Number of candidates</seg>
<seg id="454">Except in a few cases, the requirement for reaching the minimum number of tenderers was met.</seg>
<seg id="455">An analysis of almost 7,000 works contracts with a value below the national limit showed that in the case of restricted procedures, contracting authorities invited an average of 6.6 potential tenderers and in the case of direct negotiation an average of 4.4 tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="456">Change of contractors and regional restrictions</seg>
<seg id="457">In particular in the field of building construction, contracting authorities did not change the pool of tenderers approached, as they had good experience with those with whom they had previously cooperated.</seg>
<seg id="458">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="459">The contracting authorities argued that in the case of a non-public procedure, they should guarantee that they would reach out to candidates whose suitability they had already ascertained beforehand.</seg>
<seg id="460">Although there was no evidence for illegal regional restrictions, the range of candidates in the non-public procedure included a greater proportion of regional tenderers than in the case of public procedures.</seg>
<seg id="461">The contracting authorities explained this by the low level of the contract compared to the public procedure and the high cost of travel for potential tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="462">Cross-checking principle and proposals of self-employed professionals</seg>
<seg id="463">The contracting authorities mostly ignored the obligation to change the list of candidates proposed by self-employed professionals.</seg>
<seg id="464">They mainly argued the lack of staff, time pressure or inadequate knowledge of a suitable tenderer.</seg>
<seg id="465">In many cases, the records did not show who had proposed the candidate who had been asked to participate in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="466">A check of some samples showed that the list of potential tenderers had been drawn up by self-employed professionals and had been accepted by the contracting authority without changes.</seg>
<seg id="467">The contracting authorities were thus insufficiently protected from potential manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="468">Confidentiality of the treatment of lists of potential tenderers</seg>
<seg id="469">One contracting authority kept a list of candidates for invitation to tender in a database to which all employees had access at any time.</seg>
<seg id="470">This allowed for manipulation or unauthorised disclosure of the names of prospective or admitted tenderers, who could then agree on the price.</seg>
<seg id="471">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="472">The documentation gave the reasons for the selection of tenderers in only a few cases.</seg>
<seg id="473">SAO</seg>
<seg id="474">Criteria for the selection of tenderers</seg>
<seg id="475">During the construction of the ring road, the candidates did not have information about what information about their qualifications would be evaluated and how.</seg>
<seg id="476">For the action related to the development and modernisation of waterways and ports, the tender notice for participation in the restricted procedure did not set out criteria for limiting the number of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="477">All eight tenderers met the qualification requirements, but this exceeded the number to which the contracting authority had limited participation in the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="478">The Commission then carried out the selection of candidates by random selection – by drawing lots, which was legal at the time.</seg>
<seg id="479">This procedure should have been mentioned as a criterion already in the tender notice.</seg>
<seg id="480">Summary</seg>
<seg id="481">In view of the high risk of manipulation in the selection of the winning tenderer in restricted procurement procedures, both countries have introduced special measures to prevent unlawful restrictions on competition.</seg>
<seg id="482">German rules limit such opportunities for manipulation by means of so-called cross-checking (the four-eyes principle), by maintaining the confidentiality of the list of tenderers and by prohibiting external companies from making proposals for the selection of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="483">The Czech rules aim to prevent potential restrictions with a view to manipulation mainly by an unlimited number of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="484">However, the audit found that some of the above rules were not applied to a sufficient degree and that an unlawful restriction of the number of candidates was not prevented in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="485">Contracting authorities are obliged to eliminate the aforementioned shortcomings completely.</seg>
<seg id="486">Submission of tenders</seg>
<seg id="487">The stage of the procurement procedure, at which potential tenderers can prepare tenders on the basis of the tender documents they have received, starts with the publication of the tender information and/or the invitation to tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="488">Until the date of opening the envelopes, potential tenderers can submit their tenders to the contracting entity in order to compete for the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="489">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="490">EU law does not prescribe specific requirements at this stage of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="491">The contracting entity must follow the national rules governing this stage of the procedure and prevent potential manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="492">These rules relate in particular to organisation and control.</seg>
<seg id="493">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="494">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="495">The principle is that tender documents on the basis of which potential suppliers prepare their tenders must always be sent by the contracting entity.</seg>
<seg id="496">The design offices that are involved in the procedure should not fulfil this role.</seg>
<seg id="497">The contracting authority must ensure that all candidates have received the same information during this stage of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="498">In case of ambiguity in the tender documents or when other questions arise, only the contracting authority may supply the information to the tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="499">No information may be provided by the design bureaux in charge of drawing up the tender documents.</seg>
<seg id="500">During this entire stage, any contact between the design bureau and the tenderers must be avoided.</seg>
<seg id="501">They must remain anonymous throughout, as allowing them to be contacted may adversely affect competition.</seg>
<seg id="502">Tenders sent by post or submitted directly must be submitted in a closed envelope.</seg>
<seg id="503">Tenders submitted electronically must be encrypted.</seg>
<seg id="504">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="505">In Germany, the contracting authority may entrust insured external service suppliers with the printing and distribution of the documents, and their employees must be bound to confidentiality.</seg>
<seg id="506">In Germany, tenders received must be marked with the date of receipt and transmitted directly and immediately in their original state (sealed) to the official in charge of their safekeeping.</seg>
<seg id="507">This official must have no interest in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="508">Tenders received must be locked until the opening date of the envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="509">In the Czech Republic, tenders received are marked with a serial number.</seg>
<seg id="510">The contracting authority issues a report with details of the competition, including the tender number and information on the preparation of the tender and its receipt.</seg>
<seg id="511">There are no specific provisions on the safekeeping of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="512">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="513">BRH</seg>
<seg id="514">BRH inspected the award of the administrative building.</seg>
<seg id="515">Sending the procurement documents</seg>
<seg id="516">The inspected contracting authorities sent the procurement documents either directly or entrusted its printing and distribution to an external firm.</seg>
<seg id="517">Self-employed persons did not send any documentation.</seg>
<seg id="518">Information to tenderers</seg>
<seg id="519">For the part of the tender documents related to questioning and obtaining information, the contracting authority did not follow the rule for separate planning from the tender procedure.</seg>
<seg id="520">Contrary to the relevant regulations, it often did not mention in the documentation the names of its contact staff, but rather the staff of the project management department.</seg>
<seg id="521">Some notices during the tender procedure even included the names of companies or self-employed persons who participated in the preparation of the tender documents.</seg>
<seg id="522">In rare cases, tenderers who asked questions during the tender procedure did not receive identical information.</seg>
<seg id="523">Labelling of tenders</seg>
<seg id="524">For the contracting authorities, all accepted tenders were marked with a stamp and a receipt.</seg>
<seg id="525">However, in some cases for the negotiated procedure, tenders were accepted by self-employed professionals, which violated the rule of one building preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="526">Custody of the tenders</seg>
<seg id="527">Once marked, not all tenders were passed on directly and without delay to the official assigned to keep them in custody locked the tenders in a steel cabinet.</seg>
<seg id="528">For one contracting authority, tenders were temporarily placed in an open slot in the mail room, to which all employees had access.</seg>
<seg id="529">Another contracting authority placed the box in the corridor without constant supervision, and a part of the tenders thrown into the box remained there overnight.</seg>
<seg id="530">The opening of the box was wide and unsecured, and it was accessible not only to employees.</seg>
<seg id="531">SAO</seg>
<seg id="532">The SAO did not find any shortcomings in this area.</seg>
<seg id="533">Summary</seg>
<seg id="534">In both countries, rules are laid down to prevent contacts, especially between interested companies and design offices cooperating in the procurement procedure, throughout the entire process.</seg>
<seg id="535">Equal treatment is ensured by sending the same information to all tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="536">Rules to prevent manipulation and corruption are suitable for the receipt, safekeeping and confidentiality of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="537">In Germany, the relevant requirements are somewhat more elaborated than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="538">In Germany, accumulated control records have shown breaches of the rules in some areas.</seg>
<seg id="539">These irregularities can easily be corrected.</seg>
<seg id="540">Opening of envelopes</seg>
<seg id="541">Opening of envelopes</seg>
<seg id="542">During the opening of envelopes, tenders that have so far been closed are opened, their contents read and published.</seg>
<seg id="543">The period during which a tenderer is bound by his tender begins when the deadline for submitting or opening envelopes expires and ends with a deadline specified by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="544">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="545">European legislation does not contain any specific provisions dealing with the opening of envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="546">However, national laws and regulations contain extensive requirements to protect tenders as well as competition during this sensitive phase of the entire procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="547">The principles of "more eyes", transparency and trustworthiness of the process of opening envelopes are intended to prevent manipulation and modification of tenders already submitted.</seg>
<seg id="548">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="549">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="550">Opening of envelopes must be carried out by several persons appointed by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="551">Compliance with the principle of ‘multiple eyes’ is intended to prevent individuals from covertly manipulating bids.</seg>
<seg id="552">Bidders may be present when opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="553">When opening, all envelopes must be placed before the chairman of the board and are opened one by one.</seg>
<seg id="554">Bids received late must not be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="555">To ensure transparency when opening envelopes, this stage, including the conclusions (results), must be recorded in writing. The record must include, among other things, the names of the bidders and the price offered.</seg>
<seg id="556">The record must be read and signed by the group leader.</seg>
<seg id="557">The record may also be signed by the bidders present.</seg>
<seg id="558">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="559">In the Czech Republic, a board is set up for opening envelopes.</seg>
<seg id="560">The participation of independent experts is permitted.</seg>
<seg id="561">Members of the board may also be entrusted with deliberations during the subsequent stages of the procedure, i.e. the evaluation of the bids.</seg>
<seg id="562">In Germany, the opening of envelopes takes place in the presence of the manager and the registrar.</seg>
<seg id="563">The manager must be an employee of the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="564">The manager and, in the case of building, the registrar may not participate in the preparatory stage (preparation of the tender documents), may not decide on the award of the contract and may not be a member of the subsequent processing (management) of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="565">The German regulations require that the minutes of the opening of envelopes contain not only the tender prices, but also all information on discounts and special (unusual) signs, e.g. damaged envelopes on receipt or late receipt of a tender.</seg>
<seg id="566">In the Czech Republic, the minutes drawn up must include, in addition to the tender prices, an indication of the tenderer's language and signature authorization.</seg>
<seg id="567">The German regulations require all parts of the opening envelopes to be marked so as to prevent subsequent changes.</seg>
<seg id="568">Tenders, usually marked by a form of perforation with a date, must be kept confidential (secret) after the opening of the envelopes has been completed and may only be made available to persons who further process them.</seg>
<seg id="569">There are no similar arrangements in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="570">If a single tender is received in the Czech Republic, the envelope may not be opened and the tenderer must be informed immediately.</seg>
<seg id="571">In Germany, they do not have this arrangement and if a single tender is accepted, it is opened and evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="572">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="573">BRH</seg>
<seg id="574">Cross-checking principle</seg>
<seg id="575">During the opening of the envelopes, the contracting authorities followed the four-eyes principle.</seg>
<seg id="576">The manager and the registrar, who was not assigned a different role, were always present.</seg>
<seg id="577">In rare cases, however, for small negotiated procedures, natural persons opened the tenders sent to them without the participation of the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="578">Opening process</seg>
<seg id="579">The notes from the opening of the envelopes did not always document the progress.</seg>
<seg id="580">In some cases, tenders submitted late were not marked and in some cases signatures were missing.</seg>
<seg id="581">Marking of received tenders</seg>
<seg id="582">The contracting authorities marked the tenders with a date-stamped perforation, which was in line with the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="583">Some of them had wrongly marked the tenders in the past, but changed their practice after being warned by the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="584">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="585">SAO</seg>
<seg id="586">Deadline for the delivery of tenders</seg>
<seg id="587">During road repairs, for one action, the tenderer's tender was submitted to the contracting authority with a month's delay, which nevertheless accepted it.</seg>
<seg id="588">Summary</seg>
<seg id="589">The essential parts of the provisions for opening envelopes are identical in both countries with regard to the principle of "more eyes" and the principle of transparency, thus allowing for a substantial reduction of the risk of corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="590">The German rules are more comprehensive than those of the Czech Republic, especially the requirements for accurate documentation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="591">Marking, safe keeping and respecting the confidential nature of tenders substantially limit the possibility of subsequent changes in submitted tenders.</seg>
<seg id="592">Moreover, the staff responsible for opening envelopes may not carry out any other activities related to the contract to be awarded.</seg>
<seg id="593">The findings, despite the discovery of some irregularities, confirm that the rules for opening envelopes are largely applied.</seg>
<seg id="594">Assessment and evaluation of tenders</seg>
<seg id="595">The contracting authority must examine and evaluate the tenders received within the deadline set.</seg>
<seg id="596">At the same time, it must award the contract to the tenderer who best meets the award criteria in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="597">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="598">EU law sets out the process of assessing and evaluating tenders in several steps:</seg>
<seg id="599">The first step is to check the suitability of the tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="600">They must be in a good economic and financial position and possess the required professional and technical knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="601">Bidders who have ever been finally convicted of bribery or defrauding must always be excluded from procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="602">The tenders of non-excluded tenderers must be evaluated in terms of numerical accuracy, technical suitability and value for money on the basis of previously published award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="603">The contracting authority must identify the economically most favourable tender and, in particular, examine all significantly low price tenders.</seg>
<seg id="604">Review and evaluation are particularly sensitive and prone to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, tenderers may be excluded without legitimate reason, or tenders that do not meet the requirements may be left to tender.</seg>
<seg id="606">The outcome of the evaluation may be improperly influenced by the preference of a tenderer or its disadvantage, thereby preventing the selection of the most economically advantageous tender.</seg>
<seg id="607">The contracting authority must therefore take special measures in selecting the persons involved in the process and must ensure that they meet the requirements of integrity and technical knowledge.</seg>
<seg id="608">It must also ensure that the whole process and the decisions taken are transparent and credible.</seg>
<seg id="609">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="611">In line with EU requirements, the relevant provisions in both countries require the examination and evaluation of tenders in successive stages.</seg>
<seg id="612">During the evaluation, the requirements for the proof of the suitability of tenderers, the evaluation criteria and their weightings set out in the notice or in the procurement documents may not be changed.</seg>
<seg id="613">The criteria set for evaluating the suitability of tenderers may no longer be used.</seg>
<seg id="614">Further evaluation may be carried out only on the basis of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="615">The tenders submitted must first be examined from a formal point of view, whether they are complete or do not contain any suspicious elements which might encourage manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="616">If tenderers are excluded from further examination and evaluation of the tenders submitted by them, they must be informed immediately.</seg>
<seg id="617">If the evaluation of the tenders results in the discovery of an unreasonably low tender price, the tenderer concerned must be given the opportunity to comment on the situation before his tender may be eliminated.</seg>
<seg id="618">The reasons for the decision must be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="619">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="620">In Germany, tenderers must maintain confidentiality and only authorised persons may participate in the evaluation of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="621">Only the contracting authority may examine the mathematical accuracy of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="622">Only employees who are not involved in the decision-making stage of the selection of the contractor or in the implementation of the project may be entrusted with evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="623">There are no precise provisions as to who may carry out further reviews and evaluations.</seg>
<seg id="624">If external companies are entrusted with the review and evaluation of tenders, they must be aware that the tenders are confidential and respect this honestly.</seg>
<seg id="625">They may only make proposals for decisions to the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="626">In the Czech Republic, tenders must be examined and evaluated by a committee appointed by the contracting authority, which draws up a report with a proposal for conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="627">However, in both countries, the final decision depends on the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="628">If in Germany the documents and declarations required in connection with the submission of tenders are incomplete, the tenderers concerned must subsequently submit the required documents within six days.</seg>
<seg id="629">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="630">If tenderers fail to comply with this obligation, their tenders must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="631">In the Czech Republic, the contracting authority may decide whether to give the tenderer the opportunity to complete the missing documents.</seg>
<seg id="632">If the tenderer fails to provide evidence, he must be excluded.</seg>
<seg id="633">In Germany, not only the total price but also the unit prices must be reviewed.</seg>
<seg id="634">If the price structure of the tender indicates that prices for parts of the overall project have been estimated to be unreasonably high or low, tenderers must be asked to provide explanations.</seg>
<seg id="635">If they fail to provide explanations, and if the contracting authority can demonstrate that the tender contains countervailing prices, such tenders must be eliminated.</seg>
<seg id="636">This is to prevent tenderers from submitting price calculations on the assumption that substantial quantitative changes will be made to individual parts of the overall project, which may lead to a significant increase in project costs.</seg>
<seg id="637">In the Czech Republic, the total price of a work is evaluated and the prices of individual parts are not examined in detail.</seg>
<seg id="638">Valuation compensations do not justify the exclusion of a tender.</seg>
<seg id="639">In Germany, a contract cannot be awarded to a tenderer who offers a price that is unreasonably high or low.</seg>
<seg id="640">If one or more tenders differ in price by 10 % or more from the price estimated by the contracting authority or from other tenders, tenderers must prove that their tender has been credibly and convincingly calculated.</seg>
<seg id="641">If they are unable to do so, the contracting authority should exclude them.</seg>
<seg id="642">In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure may be cancelled after a price review if only bids with disproportionately low prices have been received and the bidders have not justified these prices.</seg>
<seg id="643">If the price of the bid is significantly higher than the contracting authority's estimate, this does not constitute a reason for refusing to award the contract to the bidder concerned (unlike German procurement law).</seg>
<seg id="644">In Germany, if there is a suspicion of behaviour intended to restrict competition, the contracting authority is obliged to report this immediately to the competent superior authority.</seg>
<seg id="645">The latter must decide on the way forward and whether it is appropriate to inform the antitrust authority or the law enforcement authorities.</seg>
<seg id="646">Furthermore, it must approve (e.g. if the contract exceeds €50,000 and the contract has not been awarded to the lowest bidder) whether the contract will be awarded in the negotiation of the contract or whether the procurement procedure will be cancelled.</seg>
<seg id="647">Czech rules do not regulate this area.</seg>
<seg id="648">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="649">BRH</seg>
<seg id="650">Examination of suitability and award criteria</seg>
<seg id="651">Most of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the relevant requirements.</seg>
<seg id="652">In the case of some recommendations made by potential contractors, made by self-employed persons, the contracting authorities did not themselves check the suitability of the bidders.</seg>
<seg id="653">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="654">In some procurement procedures, insufficient documentation was provided as to whether, in making the choice, the contracting authority took into account all published evaluation criteria or whether the selection decision was based solely on the price criterion.</seg>
<seg id="655">Selection of interested persons and confidentiality of tenders</seg>
<seg id="656">Some contracting authorities used the services of unauthorised persons, such as self-employed persons or employees of building authorities.</seg>
<seg id="657">They were integrated into the planning or implementation process of construction projects, performing functions that were to be performed exclusively by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="658">The contracting authorities tried to justify this by their insufficient human resources in the sector.</seg>
<seg id="659">In some cases, they used self-employed professionals to examine the tenders for the services of persons who were not formally bound to preserve the confidentiality of the tenders and to perform with due diligence their obligations under the contract.</seg>
<seg id="660">As for contracting entities, there was generally no conclusive record of whether tenders in the safekeeping of self-employed professionals were only available to designated persons.</seg>
<seg id="661">Examination and mathematical control of tenders</seg>
<seg id="662">Some contracting entities passed open envelopes for further examination to self-employed professionals without first carrying out the prescribed examination of tenders and mathematical examination and without documenting the results of these examinations.</seg>
<seg id="663">In the event of any intention of manipulation, third parties could make changes to tenders that could not be identified by the contracting entity.</seg>
<seg id="664">Examination of documents revealed a number of cases where unusual elements in tenders were not adequately identified or where data on prices and products were missing.</seg>
<seg id="665">Performance audits</seg>
<seg id="666">A sample check by one contracting authority revealed that in 75% of procurement procedures the most advantageous tenders deviated by more than 10% from the pre-estimated costs.</seg>
<seg id="667">One in twenty procurement procedures was cancelled due to inadequate tender prices.</seg>
<seg id="668">In many cases there was a lack of evidence or sufficient documentation on the examination of tenders or on negotiations with tenderers for further clarification.</seg>
<seg id="669">In many cases there was also a lack of detailed information on, for example, unit prices of the most important invoiced items.</seg>
<seg id="670">Changes in market prices or increases in material costs were often cited as reasons for deviations.</seg>
<seg id="671">Contracting authorities argued that identifying and demonstrating balancing prices was difficult.</seg>
<seg id="672">In the case of one call for tenders, made by an entity outside the ordinary contracting authorities, a price 66% lower than the original cost estimate was offered.</seg>
<seg id="673">No details were recorded on the closer examination of cost or on the reasons for deviations.</seg>
<seg id="674">In clarifying this issue, the contracting authority found no indication of price dumping in the bidder to whom the contract might have been awarded.</seg>
<seg id="675">It was therefore not clarified whether the original cost estimate was excessive or whether the price offered was too low.</seg>
<seg id="676">Later, the contracting authority rated this bidder as a "low-cost company" which was unable to meet either the quality requirements or the deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="677">In another procurement procedure, the contracting authority awarded the contract to a bidder whose price was 35% higher than the original cost estimate.</seg>
<seg id="678">The contracting authority did not cancel the procurement procedure and argued that the said bidder could be assumed not to have based its pricing on unreasonably high costs.</seg>
<seg id="679">Suspected irregularities</seg>
<seg id="680">Two cases of irregularities were found in one contracting authority and these were reported to the firm responsible for technical supervision.</seg>
<seg id="681">In one procurement procedure, two bidders submitted bids containing identical price calculations, which prompted the contracting authority to exclude both bids.</seg>
<seg id="682">The audits did not show any significant deficiencies in the application of other provisions.</seg>
<seg id="683">SAO</seg>
<seg id="684">Assessment of suitability</seg>
<seg id="685">In many construction projects, such as university buildings, roads and railways, the contracting authorities did not exclude bidders from participation in the procurement procedure, even though they did not meet the requirements of the contracting authority specified in the tender specifications, or did not substantiate the qualification to the required extent, or, on the contrary, one contracting authority failed to substantiate or explain the reason for the exclusion of the bidder who met the requirements.</seg>
<seg id="686">Evaluation</seg>
<seg id="687">In the case of the construction of a wastewater treatment plant, individual evaluation criteria of the procurement procedure for the construction contractor were established, but the contracting authority did not respect them during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="688">In the case of the railway infrastructure development project, the weightings of the evaluation criteria were not determined at the time of the contract award, but only at the beginning of the evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="689">In the case of the infrastructure repair project, the evaluation of the criterion “shortening the construction time” was not carried out correctly.</seg>
<seg id="690">For the bidders in second and third place, the evaluation incorrectly indicated a greater shortening of construction time than indicated in their bids.</seg>
<seg id="691">Documentation of the reasons for the selection of the bidder</seg>
<seg id="692">For the three housing promotion actions, the contracting authority did not substantiate the criteria on which it had assessed the bids received and how it had selected the most suitable one.</seg>
<seg id="693">The correctness of the selection of small-scale contractors associated with the construction of a road ring with an estimated price of up to CZK 500,000.</seg>
<seg id="694">It was not possible to verify the correctness of the selection of the contractors, as the contractors were selected only on the basis of telephone consultations on price and timing of performance, but evidence of these negotiations was not produced.</seg>
<seg id="695">Summary</seg>
<seg id="696">In both countries, the rules for the verification and evaluation of bids correspond to EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, they differ with regard to the specific steps of the procedure and the selection of individuals involved in the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="698">Unlike in the Czech Republic, in Germany, these steps of the procurement process are governed by stricter and more detailed requirements, in particular as regards the application of the cross-principle and the protection of bids.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the rules for the verification of the appropriateness of the prices offered.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, in some cases checks found that the substantive steps of the process in the verification and evaluation of tenders were not documented at all and, if so, only partially.</seg>
<seg id="701">The absence of control tools and transparency in the decision-making during the examination and evaluation of tenders allows for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="702">Checks showed serious deficiencies, such as the transmission of tenders to third parties without prior due diligence and the documentation of tenders by the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="703">If contracting authorities entrust a third party with the performance of functions related to the examination and evaluation of tenders, appropriate measures and increased control of measures against the increased possibility of manipulation are necessary.</seg>
<seg id="704">When checking the validity of prices, the German contracting authorities audited did not in all cases use the full set of tools available and did not deal with their own price structure.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, deficiencies were found in the evaluation of the appropriateness of tenders and the application of evaluation criteria.</seg>
<seg id="706">Completion of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="707">After the examination and evaluation of the tenders, the procurement process is concluded by the award of the contract or the cancellation of the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="708">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="709">In the case of the European procedure, all tenderers must be informed in advance of the decision to award the contract.</seg>
<seg id="710">Contractors have the opportunity to review the decision taken within a limited period of 10 or 15 days and to request its review if appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="711">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="712">The period of 10 days applies to electronic submissions and 15 days to other submissions.</seg>
<seg id="713">The contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this period or before the decision of the review procedure.</seg>
<seg id="714">If the review body rejects the complaint and confirms the decision, candidates and tenderers must be given the opportunity to have the correctness of the application of the procurement law reviewed by an independent court.</seg>
<seg id="715">This measure ensures that no contracting authority will be able to circumvent the legal protection of suppliers by swiftly implementing the decision of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="716">The contracting authority must document the progress of the procedure appropriately.</seg>
<seg id="717">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="718">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="719">Both countries have implemented the procedure on information obligations.</seg>
<seg id="720">In both countries, the final decision on the outcome of the procurement procedure rests with the contracting authority.</seg>
<seg id="721">However, the latter cannot arbitrarily deviate from the results of a properly performed screening and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="722">The contracting authority is to conclude the contract within a specified period.</seg>
<seg id="723">This is because the tenderer is not bound by its bid after this period has expired.</seg>
<seg id="724">The content of the contract must not deviate from the winning bid.</seg>
<seg id="725">Unsuccessful tenderers are to be informed of the result in a timely manner, stating the reason why their bid was not accepted.</seg>
<seg id="726">Cancellation of the procurement procedure is permissible only if certain conditions are met, e.g. if the prices in the tenders do not correspond to the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the mandatory waiting period prior to the conclusion of the contract of 10 or 15 days applies to both European and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, the equivalent provision applies only to European procedures.</seg>
<seg id="730">In all other procedures in Germany, tenderers cannot be informed of the award of the contract before the decision on its EU provision and the review award is taken.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be cancelled if a single tender has been received or if only one tender meets the requirements for its consideration and evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, a contract must be awarded even if a single tender has been received, provided that the tender fulfils the conditions set out in the tender documentation and is cost-effective.</seg>
<seg id="733">Main audit findings</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">The audits found few irregularities in the completion of the audited procurement processes.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases of European procedures, companies receiving letters of authority before the expiry of the notification period, which may invalidate the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">Also in several cases of open procedures, letters of authority contained modifications incompatible with the content of the tender, e.g. new deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="738">In some cases, contracting authorities did not meet the deadlines for awarding the contract.</seg>
<seg id="739">In one open procedure, the contracting authority selected the second most advantageous offer because a bidder offering a price more than 50% lower no longer wished to fulfill the contract at the price originally offered.</seg>
<seg id="740">SAO</seg>
<seg id="741">In one case, during the reconstruction and construction of a university, the contracting authority did not conclude a contract with the contractor in accordance with the contract proposal contained in the selected bidder's bid.</seg>
<seg id="742">In some projects for repairs and maintenance of roads, construction of a motorway and a road ring, contracts were concluded later than stipulated by law.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the case of construction modifications in former military districts, the contracting authority sent a notice of selection of the most suitable offer to all bidders after the legal deadline had expired.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries implemented EU regulations on the termination of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="746">Legal protection of unsuccessful candidates contributes to reducing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The Czech Public Procurement Act includes the institute of legal protection even in cases of contracts below the EU limits.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, it was found that the limited time limit for concluding the contract was exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can cause adverse economic consequences and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, contracting entities should eliminate such shortcomings when concluding procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, notifications, information obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The procurement process, with all its individual stages, relevant findings and decisions, including relevant justifications, must be documented in a transparent manner.</seg>
<seg id="753">The completion of procurement procedures at European level must be published.</seg>
<seg id="754">The data on procurement procedures are summarised in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of European law and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="756">The obligation to document procurement procedures complies with the fundamental requirement of the principle of transparency, applied at EU-wide level.</seg>
<seg id="757">Only proper and time-relevant documentation on decision-making and justification gives a guarantee of transparency in the procurement process and, above all, guarantees effective legal protection of the interests of each bidder in cases where the value of the contract exceeds European thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Adequate documentation is also an essential part of anti-corruption measures, as the obligation to provide detailed reasons for individual decisions and their merits significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">In European procurement procedures, the contracting authority must notify the completion of the procedures to the EU's Office of Official Publications within 48 days from the date of the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notification in the Official Journal of the EU and this also fulfils the requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authority must summarise the essential data on its procurement procedures and communicate them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the European Commission issues annual statistics which provide an overview of the development of the single market in the field of construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Provisions of German and Czech procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar provisions</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed into their national legislation the provisions of the European law on documentation and notification obligations.</seg>
<seg id="766">The provisions on documentation and notification for the purposes of European statistics are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different provisions</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to notify the award of a contract applies not only to European procedures, but also to national procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The deadline for notification is only 15 days from the conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, the obligation to notify procurement procedures, in addition to those which are mandatory under European law, applies only to restricted procedures exceeding the limit of €25,000 ($625,000) and direct procedures exceeding the limit of €15,000 ($375,000) including VAT.</seg>
<seg id="771">Below this limit, only the participants in the procedure are informed.</seg>
<seg id="772">Main control findings</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of awards were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The notice did not contain all the necessary information, e.g. reasons for the supply specifications and national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of one procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it concluded a contract with a tenderer whose tender did not contain the mandatory elements.</seg>
<seg id="778">In several cases, some required records were also missing.</seg>
<seg id="779">Publication of the award</seg>
<seg id="780">In some European procedures, the contracting authority made errors in the publication of the notice.</seg>
<seg id="781">In several awards, evidence of the publication of the notice was missing.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting obligation</seg>
<seg id="783">Statistically verified files included the required minimum of information and were created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Preliminary transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the contracting authority published information on the outcome of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of one contracting authority, information on the contract was not published due to a communication error.</seg>
<seg id="787">It took the contracting authority half a year to notice the error.</seg>
<seg id="788">As a result, the outcome of the procedure was not published during this time.</seg>
<seg id="789">SAO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">In events related to the organisation of a major sporting event, significant shortcomings in the documentation of the procurement procedure were found, such as incorrect data on bid prices in the reports of the evaluation committee.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some documents on the opening of envelopes were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Publication of the award</seg>
<seg id="794">In the preparation of repairs and maintenance of roads, construction of a motorway and a road ring, the notices of the award were sent after the deadline, or were not published.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary</seg>
<seg id="796">The provisions on documentation and notification and notification obligations include European requirements and are almost identical in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally ensures transparency of procurement procedures and final selection.</seg>
<seg id="798">Czech notification obligations are somewhat stricter compared to German ones.</seg>
<seg id="799">The audits revealed shortcomings significantly reducing the value of documentation as a means of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Contracting entities should continue to strengthen the transparency of their procurement procedures and fully comply with notification and notification requirements.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits of the SAO and BRH focused on two areas that are essential for the public procurement process in both the Czech Republic and Germany, namely the application of EU procurement law and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU legislation provides an opportunity for international competition within the EU with the aim of creating a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Measures aimed at preventing corruption are aimed not only at avoiding it or at reducing it, but also at preventing financial damage and potential loss of confidence in the integrity of the government.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two audit institutions – the SAO and BRH – with regard to the application of both countries' procurement law and a comparison of its respective provisions give an internal view on common and different elements that can help both countries in further development and application of this law.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed EU procurement law into their national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="809">In both countries there is an important common base for public procurement and fulfilment of the basic requirements in the areas of: competition; equal treatment of candidates; transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">Contracting authorities strengthen these requirements partly with very extensive measures.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has extended public procurement provisions requiring a European procedure to procedures below the EU limits and is therefore governed by national legislation.</seg>
<seg id="812">Nevertheless, the audits showed that contracting authorities are not always fully compliant with all the relevant provisions of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="813">German contracting authorities should continue to improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to eliminate the aforementioned irregularities, taking into account the implementation of EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">In the Czech Republic, the audits identified risks affecting economy and value for money.</seg>
<seg id="815">These include, in particular, incomplete definition of the subject matter of the public contract, which resulted in additional works that were often awarded in violation of the law, insufficient definition of the anticipated price, and the required qualification conditions reducing the potential pool of bidders and thus reducing competition, especially in the area of transport construction.</seg>
<seg id="816">Preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The joint audits were not aimed at detecting cases of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="818">The reason was that both BRH and the SAO did not have sufficient tools to do so.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, they can check whether the competent authorities of both countries take measures to reduce corruption and manipulation in public procurement and how these measures are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">As regards the prevention of corruption, the two countries focused on different aspects.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German provisions give room for wide and unlimited competition, transparency and controls as a central element of the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations aim mainly at enhancing the transparency of public procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, there are general principles for the prevention of corruption, which apply to the whole federal administration.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles were also included among the requirements for public procurement and were adopted in order to meet the specific needs of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="826">The relevant provisions specify, sometimes with great precision, the methods of compliance with the requirements for the prevention of corruption during the procurement procedure and for the selection of persons included in it.</seg>
<seg id="827">In BRH's view, the principle of preference for open procurement procedures and calls for participation is a particularly suitable tool for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in public procurement, while restricting competition increases the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analysis and adequate controls (in particular the principle of cross-checking), transparency requirements, tender documentation and various organisational measures are also effective mechanisms for preventing corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">BRH therefore does not feel the need for substantial changes to the current provisions that public institutions have to comply with when awarding public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="830">Anti-corruption measures are widely applied in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">Irregularities found in some areas have highlighted weaknesses in compliance with certain requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Therefore, contracting authorities should provide their employees with further training to familiarise them with anti-corruption requirements and further raise their awareness in this area.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the revealed weaknesses relate to activities delegated by the building administration to private entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, the absence of adequate controls when delegating powers increases the risk of misuse.</seg>
<seg id="835">Activities susceptible to manipulation and corruption should therefore be transferred to third parties only if the administration can guarantee a sufficient degree of protection against unauthorized interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">SAO</seg>
<seg id="837">Anti-corruption strategies were adopted at government level in the Czech Republic, which also significantly affect the area of public procurement.</seg>
<seg id="838">Audit actions of the SAO took place during the period when one of the most important parts of the strategy was implemented, namely a significant change of the Public Procurement Act and the adoption of subsequent implementing regulations.</seg>
<seg id="839">The adopted strategy and new legal regulations can be effective steps to improve the situation.</seg>
<seg id="840">Under the new regulations, the contracting authority must justify the effectiveness of the public contract, the determination of the expected value of the public contract, the adequacy of the requirements for qualification, the determination of basic evaluation criteria and the method of evaluation of tenders, and document and publish everything properly.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">Overall, the SAO and BRH have a favourable opinion on the ways of implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">Their wide application in practice confirmed that the EU requirements on competition, equal treatment and transparency form an appropriate basis for public procurement within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model, established in the EU, can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and supporting international competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">Taking into account the great potential of material and intangible damages arising from manipulation and corruption in connection with public procurement, both BRH and SAO insist that it is the obligation of contracting authorities to continue and improve measures against corruption and manipulation where possible.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, organisational structures and processes of procurement procedures should be continuously monitored for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for corrective actions and to react appropriately.</seg>
<seg id="847">Compared to the practice in Germany, it has emerged that the Czech Republic should increase the share of open procurement procedures, which give space to competition and substantially reduce the possibility of corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="848">Procurement in parts, where permissible and suitable for contracting authorities, can also have a positive impact on the achieved price. A higher number of bidders puts pressure on the achieved price.</seg>
<seg id="849">The organisation of the procurement procedure also has an influence on the course of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, it is organised by special state organisations, while in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport constructions, it is organised by the central authorities themselves or through contracting organisations.</seg>
<seg id="851">Both the SAO and the BRH wish to further develop knowledge in their work, where appropriate, and to address it with their parliament and government beyond their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Moreover, they are convinced that the principles of procurement law and their implementation, as described in this report, will also be of interest at the level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), as the principles and findings mentioned are of general importance for the effective fight against corruption and for ensuring that public contracts are awarded in a regime of well-functioning and honest competition and that value for money is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="853">Annexes</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_15_33" genre="news" origlang="cs" sysid="CUNI-DocTransformer2020">
<p>
<seg id="1">JOINT FINAL REPORT on the results of parallel audits of the administration of excise duties in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint Final Report</seg>
<seg id="3">May 2017</seg>
<seg id="4">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="5">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="6">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="7">The submitted joint report informs on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic, focusing on the administration of excise duties in 2012-2015.</seg>
<seg id="8">The cooperation between supreme audit institutions of both countries was realized on the basis of a cooperation agreement between the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic in the performance of parallel audits focused on the administration of excise duties, which was concluded in August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="9">The topic of parallel audits was selected on the basis of the fact that both EU Member States are based on common European legislation in order to find out how it is applied at the national level, how the system of administration of excise duties is set up and in what way the systems in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic are different.</seg>
<seg id="10">The greatest benefits of the control actions carried out were the exchange of experience, the identification of differences and the identification of good practice.</seg>
<seg id="11">Last but not least, it was beneficial to find that the international comparability of data on the performance and efficiency of excise duty administration is very limited without the implementation of parallel controls.</seg>
<seg id="12">Miloslav Kala,</seg>
<seg id="13">Karol Mitrik,</seg>
<seg id="14">President</seg>
<seg id="15">President</seg>
<seg id="16">Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="17">Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="18">on the results of parallel controls of the administration of the SPD in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="19">Summary and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="20">The legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and their administration complies with EU legislation and significantly exceeds EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="21">Differences have been found between the excise duty adjustment in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic; in the Czech Republic, it contributes to the effective administration of excise duties by verifying the economic stability of applicants for a permit and mandatory marking and dyeing of selected mineral oils and certain other oils; In Slovakia, the distribution of control stamps is simpler than in the Czech Republic and less burdensome for tax administrators.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the fight against evasion of excise taxes, monitoring of movements of raw tobacco or tobacco raw material, implementation of the fuel distributor institute and registration of sellers of consumer packaging of alcohol have proved good practice in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="23">Revenues from excise taxes in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic have been growing more slowly than other tax revenues.</seg>
<seg id="24">The EU objectives of reducing labour taxation, introducing eco-saving measures and reducing dependence on tobacco and alcohol have not been met in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic so far, among other reasons, because the indexation of excise tax rates is not implemented in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="25">This has the effect of reducing the importance of excise taxes on total tax revenues and, as a result of increasing purchasing power, a real reduction in the tax burden by excise taxes.</seg>
<seg id="26">The introduction of eco-measures has been financially supported by the state for a long time, but these measures have a negative impact on excise tax revenues, which will have to be replaced by other revenues or by a reduction in state expenditures in the future.</seg>
<seg id="27">Administrative expenditures spent on the administration of excise taxes in the Czech Republic and Slovakia have been growing for a long time, mainly due to wage increases, and their efficiency has been decreasing.</seg>
<seg id="28">In the Slovak Republic, this efficiency has also been negatively affected by expenditures on the computerisation of excise tax administration (IT expenditures) and by expenditures on wages of employees performing permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses on alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="29">The computerisation of excise tax administration in the Slovak Republic has not significantly affected the reduction of the number of tax administrators.</seg>
<seg id="30">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend that the Ministry of the Slovak Republic reconsider the validity of the performance of permanent tax supervision in tax warehouses on alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="31">In the Czech Republic, the efficiency of administrative expenditures was influenced by the fact that the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic did not apply procedures during the audited period that would lead to a reduction in the personnel intensity of excise tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="32">The number of comparable administrative acts of tax administrators was similar in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic in the individual years of the audited period, while the number of comparable tax subjects is approximately one third lower in the Slovak Republic than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="33">Tax administrators in the Slovak Republic perform administrative tasks mainly in the form of physical performance of tax supervision, while tax administrators in the Czech Republic emphasize remote supervision and risk analysis.</seg>
<seg id="34">Administration of excise taxes in the Slovak Republic is administratively more demanding than in the Czech Republic and due to the ratio of the number of tax operations to the number of subjects it is also more costly.</seg>
<seg id="35">The electronization of excise tax administration in the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic took place in different areas.</seg>
<seg id="36">Administration of excise tax returns is fully electronized in the Slovak Republic, documents proving taxation of selected products in free tax circulation are electronically transmitted in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="37">Both methods of electronization support effective administration of excise taxes, and therefore the SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic recommend applying them not only in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="38">The total expenditures for implementation of the EMCS system could not be compared, as the Slovak Ministry of Finance provided data on expenditures only for the upgrade of the system in the period 2011–2015, but expenditures were incurred even before this period.</seg>
<seg id="39">Expenditures incurred in the period only for the upgrade of EMCS were in the Slovak Republic about 20% higher than expenses incurred in the Czech Republic both for the implementation of EMCS and for the upgrade of the system in more than ten years.</seg>
<seg id="40">The administrators of excise taxes in the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic did not reach comparable values of qualitative indicators when spending comparable expenses.</seg>
<seg id="41">The level of supervision is comparable in both countries, but in the Slovak Republic the administration of excise taxes is significantly more resource intensive.</seg>
<seg id="42">The introduction of the electronic system for monitoring the movement of products subject to excise tax (EMCS) made the administration of excise taxes more efficient, but in the Slovak Republic to a lesser extent as significantly higher expenses were spent on the implementation of the system and its modernisation than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="43">Basic information</seg>
<seg id="44">The cooperation of the two audit institutions took place on the basis of the Agreement on Cooperation in the execution of parallel audits focused on the administration of excise taxes dated 18 August 2015.</seg>
<seg id="45">The SAO of the Czech Republic and the SAO of the Slovak Republic agreed to perform parallel audits, which will primarily focus on the issue of excise tax administration and whose results will allow analysis, mutual comparison and evaluation of the findings.</seg>
<seg id="46">Joint audit questions were agreed on which the parallel audits were based.</seg>
<seg id="47">Characteristics of the subject and objectives of the parallel audits:</seg>
<seg id="48">The aim of the parallel audits was to compare the performance of excise tax administrators taking into account qualitative and quantitative indicators and to identify weaknesses in the excise tax administration process.</seg>
<seg id="49">The following main audit questions were to be answered in particular:</seg>
<seg id="50">Did the excise tax administrators in the Czech Republic and Slovakia achieve comparable values of qualitative indicators when incurring comparable expenses?</seg>
<seg id="51">Did the introduction of the Excise Movement and Control System (EMCS) make the excise tax administration more effective and was the expenditure spent on its implementation effective?</seg>
<seg id="52">Parallel audits were carried out to identify the causes of significant differences affecting the efficiency and effectiveness of the tax administration in the Czech Republic and Slovakia, especially in the area of legal regulation and in the setting of the organizational structure.</seg>
