<seg id="68">Legislation on excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="69">Legislation on excise duties administration is divided into the level of EU legislation (see Annex 1) and the level of national legislation (see Annex 2).</seg>
<seg id="70">Council Directive 2008/118/EC, concerning the general regulation of excise duties and repealing Directive 92/12/EEC, defines excise duty and lays down the basic rules for the administration of taxes and the treatment of energy products and electricity, tobacco products, alcohol and alcoholic beverages.</seg>
<seg id="71">This directive allows for the imposition of consumption taxes on other products.</seg>
<seg id="72">EU legislation regulates in particular the minimum conditions for: the level of tax rates for each type of selected products, the production, storage, processing and holding of products subject to tax, the incurrence of tax liability, exemption from tax and refund of tax, supervision of transport of selected products between EU Member States, international cooperation and keeping of registers on economic operators and tax warehouses.</seg>
<seg id="73">EU legislation allows for the establishment of control procedures and institutes at national level, provided that they do not distort competition.</seg>
<seg id="74">Excise tax legislation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="75">Definition of legislation in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="76">In the Czech Republic, the legislation on excise taxes is concentrated in the Excise Tax Act (Act No 353/2003 Coll.), which regulates the administration of the mineral oil tax, the alcohol tax, the tobacco products tax, the beer tax, the wine and intermediate products tax and the raw tobacco tax.</seg>
<seg id="77">This Act defines the forms of disposal of products subject to excise taxes, the taxpayer, the authorisation procedure, the conditions for transport of products, the tax declaration and penalties for infringements of legislation.</seg>
<seg id="78">The Act and subsequent decrees further regulate certain other conditions for handling mineral oils (marking of mineral oils), restrictions on the sale of spirits and tobacco products, the monitoring of the handling of special mineral oils and the storage of raw tobacco for a purpose other than the production of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="79">Taxes on other energy products (i.e. natural gas and certain other gases, solid fuels and electricity) are regulated in parts 45 to 47 of Act No 261/2007 Coll., on the Stabilisation of Public Budgets.</seg>
<seg id="80">In the Czech Republic, a number of provisions related to the administration of excise duties are also contained in special legislation. Act No 311/2006 Coll. on Fuel and an implementing regulation regulate the conditions for the sale, supply, distribution of fuel and keeping of records of fuel put into free tax circulation.</seg>
<seg id="81">Act No 61/1997 Coll., on Alcohol, and its implementing regulations define the conditions for the production, storage, registration and control of the production and circulation of alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="82">Act No 307/2013 Coll., on obligatory marking of alcohol, and the relevant implementing regulations stipulate the obligatory marking of alcohol in consumer packaging, the conditions for the handling of control tapes and the conditions for the handling of alcohol (i.e. for the production, processing, sale or other transfer, transport, transport, storage, taking over, use, possession, import or export of alcohol).</seg>
<seg id="83">Tax procedures not specified in the special regulations are governed by Act No 280/2009 Coll., the Tax Code.</seg>
<seg id="84">Penalties are imposed by procedures pursuant to Act No 500/2004 Coll., the Administrative Code.</seg>
<seg id="85">The conditions for issuing a trade licence (concession) for the operation of the trade "production and processing of fuels and lubricants and distribution of fuel" and "production, treatment and sale of fermentation alcohol, potable alcohol and spirits" are governed by Act No 455/1991 Coll., on the trade business (Trade Licensing Act).</seg>
<seg id="86">The Czech Republic has used the authorisation to introduce control procedures and institutes to control the transport of selected products in free tax circulation and to supervise compliance with legal regulations when handling selected products for which excise duty has not been paid, as well as when handling selected products for which tax has already been paid.</seg>
<seg id="87">These include monitoring the handling of special mineral oils and raw tobacco, marking of certain other mineral oils, marking of tobacco products and alcohol in consumer packaging.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Czech Republic has used the authorisation to apply excise duty to other products as well and has introduced excise duty on raw tobacco as one of the measures against tax fraud.</seg>
<seg id="89">Structure of changes in legislation for individual types of excise taxes in relation to the subject of control in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="90">Based on the Government of the Czech Republic's resolution of 3 October 2012 no. 735, the implementation of the "zero tolerance plan for the black market in spirits" resulted in major legislative changes in the Czech Republic in 2012-2015, which introduced a number of measures against tax fraud on excise duty on alcohol.</seg>
<seg id="91">During the same period, there were also major changes in the legislation on mineral oil tax, tax on tobacco products and the criminality of preparation of tax reduction.</seg>
<seg id="92">Criminal law protection of tax revenues</seg>
<seg id="93">With effect from 1 July 2016, the preparation of the crime of "tax reduction, fee and similar obligatory payment" is criminalised. The implemented regulation should enable police authorities to take more effective and timely measures to reduce tax fraud, e.g. the deployment of operatively searched means.</seg>
<seg id="94">General provisions of excise tax administration</seg>
<seg id="95">With effect from 1 January 2015, the issuance of a permit to dispose of products subject to excise duty under the Excise Tax Act is subject to: reliability; indebtedness; economic stability; authorisation to operate a trade enabling the pursuit of the activity related to the permit; situations where the applicant is not in liquidation or bankruptcy.</seg>
<seg id="96">The aim of the legislation was in particular to address the issue of the creation of tax arrears by reducing entities authorised to dispose of products subject to excise tax.</seg>
<seg id="97">The condition of economic stability newly allows the tax administration to take into account the financial situation of tax entities both in the authorisation procedure and after the authorisation.</seg>
<seg id="98">The purpose of this measure is to prevent entities without sufficient financial income to properly fulfil tax obligations from disposing of selected products.</seg>
<seg id="99">To assess the economic stability of the applicant, indicators (profitability, liquidity, financial stability, activity, labour productivity) have been established on the basis of which the financial analysis is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="100">In addition to these indicators, the tax administrator's administrative discretion with regard to the individual conditions of the given procedure also depends.</seg>
<seg id="101">The law stipulates the periodicity of the verification of compliance with the condition of economic stability due to the timeliness of the data – the verification takes place once a year in connection with the deadline for filing the income tax return.</seg>
<seg id="102">The tax administrator has the possibility to determine other conditions needed for the tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="103">If the permit holder does not fulfil the conditions, the tax administrator is entitled to cancel the permit or cancel it with a delay.</seg>
