<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel control of the value added tax administration carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration of 1977 stresses that supreme audit institutions (SAIs) have the power to audit all public financial operations.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Declaration asks that tax revenues be audited to the greatest extent possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The European Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be one of the most important components of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The VIth EUROSAI Congress held in Bonn in 2005 dealt with the audit of public revenue carried out by the SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="7">An important step on the way to optimise the control activities of the SAIs is the development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This applies in particular to taxes as the most voluminous source of public revenue, which is most susceptible to large losses.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies become increasingly interconnected and dependent, the SAIs may to some extent be unable to carry out control activities without the cooperation of the SAIs of another state.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example is the audit of internationally organised fraud, which causes substantial losses in the revenues of many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">To combat this crime, the responsible authorities need to cooperate with each other.</seg>
<seg id="12">The SAIs carrying out control in this area must be willing to establish closer cooperation with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">It was at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn that the idea of carrying out a control of the administration of value added tax (hereinafter "VAT") and the VIES system was developed within the framework of the cooperation of the Supreme Audit Office and the Federal Court of Auditors, the Bundesrechnungshof.</seg>
<seg id="14">This was followed by careful preparation, where both parties first had to get acquainted with the legal environment and procedures for the administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the analysis of this information, a selection of audit topics was made, which were included in the audit programme.</seg>
