<seg id="18">Report on the results of parallel audits of the administration of value added tax carried out in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Audit number: (CZ) 06/27 (D) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Audit subject:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Value added tax administration after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(D) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">Audit objective:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the audit operation in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the administration of value added tax after the Czech Republic's integration into the single internal market of the European Union (hereinafter referred to as the EU) connected with the free movement of goods and services and to examine the use of the VIES system, in particular when checking the application of the right to exemption from value added tax for intra-Community supplies.</seg>
<seg id="26">(D) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of control of intra-Community value added tax with a special focus on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to the aforementioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">The result should be a report on weaknesses and recommendations for their elimination.</seg>
<seg id="28">System of exchange of information on value added tax The audited operations were carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as the SAO) and the German Bundesrechnungshof (hereinafter referred to as the BRH) in mutual cooperation on the basis of a contract concluded between the two auditing institutions on 8 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused mainly on the examination of selected commercial transactions carried out between payers from the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as “the Czech Republic”) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as “Germany”), the use of information obtained through international cooperation between tax administrations and the comparison of the VAT administration systems of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">The joint final report on the results of the auditing operations was prepared in the sense of European Directive No. 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI auditing standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel auditing operations</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel audit in the field of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of a contract between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="34">Apart from the main point – the exchange of information on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) No. 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No. 1925/2004 – the audit covered other topics, such as the registration of payers, VAT returns and summary reports, which are closely connected with the main point.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the control included the legal situation in the field of international bus passenger transport and a comparison of some statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">Comparison of the VAT administration systems of the two countries revealed differences in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) VAT registration.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered irrespective of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion (among others) for registration is exceeding the limit set in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, payers are assigned only one tax identification number, which they also use in intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, payers are assigned a tax number when registering for VAT, serving only for commercial transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="41">If a German payer intends to carry out intra-community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="42">As different methods of registration cause problems, conditions should be balanced across the EU (see 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="43">2) International bus passenger transport.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the Czech Republic, international bus passenger transport is exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT.</seg>
<seg id="45">In Germany, part of the transport that takes place on German territory is subject to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="46">At EU level, efforts should be made to harmonise the situation in the sense of Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of VAT (see 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="47">3) VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="48">While in the Czech Republic, tax payers file VAT returns only for individual tax periods (month or quarter), in Germany, tax payers are obliged to file so-called preliminary VAT returns (monthly or quarterly) and after the end of the calendar year, they have to file annual VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="49">Unlike in the Czech Republic, tax payers in Germany are obliged to file preliminary tax returns electronically.</seg>
<seg id="50">The introduction of an obligation to file VAT returns electronically in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech tax administration (see 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="51">4) Summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="52">While in the Czech Republic, tax payers file summary reports at the tax offices, in the Czech Republic, tax payers file summary reports at the Customs Office.</seg>
<seg id="53">The tax authorities in the Czech Republic therefore have the data from the summary reports available immediately after they have been submitted.</seg>
<seg id="54">The German tax authorities have the information from the summary reports available only after they have been processed into the CLO.</seg>
<seg id="55">Combating VAT fraud requires that updated information on intra-community transactions is available as soon as possible.</seg>
<seg id="56">Monthly submission of the summary reports would shorten the time lag between the date of the transaction and the updating of the data in the VIES.</seg>
<seg id="57">This would in turn allow for a timely verification of taxation in the acquirer's Member State (see 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="58">This would, however, require all Member States to adopt the same deadline for submission of the summary report.</seg>
<seg id="59">5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="60">The Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month deadline for received requests for information.</seg>
<seg id="61">The German CLO does not monitor the elapsed time.</seg>
<seg id="62">As a result, the German tax administration handled a significantly lower percentage of received requests within the deadline.</seg>
<seg id="63">Due to these problems, the BRH recommended that the German CLO carry out a permanent alert (see 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="64">6) Risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="65">Each of the two Member States develops its own risk management system (RMS), which has both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="66">The SAO and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by just one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="67">Successful criteria, components and approaches of RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State, otherwise fraudsters choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).</seg>
<seg id="68">As part of the cooperation, the two SAIs examined selected cases of intra-community transactions, carried out between tax entities from the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="69">Together, thirty-one cases of commercial transactions where there were doubts about their completion or suspicion of VAT evasion were examined using the legislation for the Customs Office.</seg>
<seg id="70">It was found that:</seg>
<seg id="71">In some cases, the tax authorities used the information obtained through international cooperation to assess the VAT liability of the payers.</seg>
<seg id="72">In these cases, the payers either improperly claimed the VAT exemption of the supply or failed to declare the acquisition of the goods in the VAT return.</seg>
<seg id="73">In some cases, the tax authorities could not use the information obtained because the information was either incomplete or incomprehensible.</seg>
<seg id="74">In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in both Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">In some cases, the tax administration of another Member State refused to respond to a request for information.</seg>
<seg id="76">Cases have been identified where payers have erroneously reported commercial transactions in recapitulative statements.</seg>
<seg id="77">As a result, the data in the VIES were incorrect and the tax administrations had to check these cases (see 6.).</seg>
