<seg id="194">Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="195">The situation is different in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="196">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered irrespective of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the primary criterion (among others) for registration is exceeding the limit set in the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="197">If a tax subject in the Czech Republic does not exceed the limit set, he or she has the possibility to apply for VAT registration on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="198">The registration procedure is standardized in Germany, but differences may occur due to different organizational models in federal states.</seg>
<seg id="199">In the Czech Republic, the tax payer is assigned a VAT number at the moment of his or her first registration for any tax.</seg>
<seg id="200">If the payer registers for VAT, he or she uses the same VAT number for intra-community transactions as well.</seg>
<seg id="201">In Germany, the tax payer is assigned a tax number when registering for VAT, serving only for business transactions in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="202">If a German payer intends to carry out intra-community transactions, he or she must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="203">As the SAO and BRH have found, the German two-tier registration system can cause many misunderstandings in other Member States, such as in the Czech Republic, which assigns a single identification number for national VAT registration and registration for intra-community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="204">On the other hand, the two-tier system allows for retroactive (national) registration in cases where payers refuse to inform the municipality or the relevant tax office about their business.</seg>
<seg id="205">This retroactive registration allows for a correct assessment of VAT for the previous tax period, especially an accurate estimation of VAT liability.</seg>
<seg id="206">As different registration methods cause problems, the conditions should be balanced across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="207">The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number (hereinafter the Tax Identification Number).</seg>
<seg id="208">The Federal Tax Office will assign the Tax Identification Number at the birth of a natural person.</seg>
<seg id="209">This Tax Identification Number will be valid for the whole life of a natural person who is a German resident.</seg>
<seg id="210">If a natural person starts a business, the relevant tax office will apply for an economic Tax Identification Number, which will be used as the VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="211">In the future, there should be no delay between the national registration of the payer and the assignment of the VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="212">Work on the introduction of the IT means to administer the Tax Identification Number has not yet been completed.</seg>
<seg id="213">International Bus Transport of Persons</seg>
