<seg id="811">In reply to this RU, the Czech tax administration stated that the request of the German party could not be complied with, because the Czech payer had no agent.</seg>
<seg id="812">As the materials provided by the SAO by the relevant tax administrator show, on 30 March 2006, a protocol was drawn up with the Czech payer's manager to start the VAT audit for the 4th quarter of 2004 and January to December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="813">The payer was also asked by the tax administrator to submit all accounting and tax documents for the above mentioned periods, but did not submit any documents.</seg>
<seg id="814">According to the Commercial Register, the only manager of the Czech payer ceased to be in office on 16 May 2006, a new manager was not appointed.</seg>
<seg id="815">From April 2006, the Czech payer stopped filing VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="816">As part of the audit, the SAO, in cooperation with BRH, examined, among other things, several cases of intra-community supplies made between the Czech Republic and Germany, which had not been the subject of a previous exchange of information between the tax administrations of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="817">Information on the audited cases was exchanged between the two supreme audit institutions via the Customs Offices of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="818">21. A Czech company (eCR), which is not resident in Germany, informed the relevant tax office (Chemnitz-Süd) that it intended to carry out a taxable transaction in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="819">Because of this information, the company was registered since June 2005, but did not receive a German VAT ID.</seg>
<seg id="820">(ECR) received an order from a Danish entrepreneur (eDK) for the production of several wind power plants and for the delivery of these wind power plants in the name, at the risk and on behalf of a Danish customer to Austria.</seg>
<seg id="821">Due to a lack of own capacity, the Czech company handed over part of the order to a German taxpayer (eD), which is based in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="822">The following diagram shows the contractual relations and the method of transportation of wind power plants:</seg>
<seg id="823">According to the German legal situation, the place of execution of these transactions must be determined according to the following:</seg>
<seg id="824">– A Danish entrepreneur (eDK) sent wind power plants for assembly under his name, at his risk and on his own account to Austria.</seg>
<seg id="825">As the assembly of this supply took place in Austria, the supply of wind power plants is taxable in Austria.</seg>
<seg id="826">– As the carrier was instructed by a Danish entrepreneur (eDK) and the transport took place under his name, at his own risk and on his own account, the supply of the German subcontractor (eD) took place where the transport began – in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="827">Although the wind power plants were sent to another Member State and the recipient is a registered payer from another Member State, the supply of the German subcontractor (eD) could not obtain an exemption as the other Member State of destination is different from the other Member State of the seat of the Czech company.</seg>
<seg id="828">This supply is therefore correctly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (eCZ) deducted the input tax in its tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="829">The place of the supply of the Czech company (eCR) is also determined at the beginning of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="830">The transport of some wind power plants started in the Czech Republic and others in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="831">– The supply of those wind power plants that are produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="832">– The supply of the other wind power plants that are produced in Germany took place in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="833">So the Czech company (eCR) made both intra-community supplies from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-community supplies from Germany to Austria.</seg>
<seg id="834">BRH found that the Czech company (eCR) did not declare any intra-community acquisitions in its tax return for VAT in Germany nor did it file a SH with the German CLO.</seg>
<seg id="835">So it is possible that the Czech company reported all intra-community supplies uniformly as intra-community supplies from the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="836">The SAO found that the (eCR) did not declare any intra-community supplies to Austria, but intra-community supplies to Denmark.</seg>
<seg id="837">Examination of the taxation of intra-community acquisitions in Austria would require the cooperation of at least four tax administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German), even though the case does not show any sign of tax fraud or evasion.</seg>
<seg id="838">The SAO and BRH also examined the transactions to point out the differences between the tax return and the VIES data, which were caused by different VAT legislation in 2004.</seg>
<seg id="839">The audited cases also demonstrate that the changes in the legislation need time for the application of the new legislation by both payers and tax authorities:</seg>
<seg id="840">22. In the SH for the second to fourth quarters of 2004, the Czech payer reported intra-community delivery to the German payer for a total value of CZK 792,977,452 (EUR 25,197,885).</seg>
<seg id="841">For the same period, another Czech payer in the SH reported intra-community delivery to another German payer for a total value of CZK 18,157,265 (EUR 576,970).</seg>
<seg id="842">According to information provided by the SAO from BRH, both cases involved the supply of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="843">Both Czech payers reported the above-mentioned supplies in the SH in accordance with the wording of Act No.235/2004 Coll., valid in 2004.</seg>
<seg id="844">By further examining the above-mentioned transactions, the SAO auditing group found that in 2004 there were differences between the Czech Republic and Germany in the legal regulation of the supply or purchase of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="845">While in the Czech Republic, payers reported the supply of electricity in accordance with the valid wording of Act No. 235/2004 Coll. as an intra-community supply of goods, from the point of view of the German statutory regulation valid in 2004 it was not an intra-community acquisition, but a taxable supply with the place of performance in the territory of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="846">The difference in the statutory regulations was eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Act No. 635/2004 Coll., which amends certain laws in connection with the adoption of the Act on Administrative Fees, effective from 1 January 2005.</seg>
<seg id="847">23. When examining selected intra-community transactions in cooperation with the BRH, it was also found that the Czech payer reported intra-community supplies to the German payer in the SH for the 1st to 4th quarter of 2005 in the total value of CZK 240,411,163 (EUR 8,071,823) and another Czech payer reported intra-community supplies to the German payer in the SH for the same period in the total value of CZK 263,470,776 (EUR 8,846,050).</seg>
<seg id="848">According to the information provided by the SAO from the BRH, both cases involved the supply of electricity.</seg>
<seg id="849">According to the wording of Act No.235/2004 Coll., effective from 1.1.2005, in the case of the supply of electricity, the place of supply is the place where the purchaser has its registered office, place of business or where it has an establishment for which the goods are supplied.</seg>
<seg id="850">Therefore, Czech payers should not have reported the supply of electricity to SH in 2005.</seg>
<seg id="851">By reporting intra-Community supplies of electricity in SH, both above-mentioned payers distorted the VIES data by a total of CZK 503,881,939 (EUR 16,917,873).</seg>
<seg id="852">Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="853">The cooperation fulfilled the objectives of BRH and the SAO.</seg>
<seg id="854">Both SAIs gained a deeper knowledge of the VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="855">The cooperation revealed differences between the two systems and showed that the VAT administration legislation differs.</seg>
<seg id="856">During parallel inspections, suspicious cases of intra-Community transactions were found.</seg>
<seg id="857">Some of them make sense to be subsequently examined.</seg>
<seg id="858">Based on the inspection findings, both SAIs made recommendations concerning the VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="859">The follow-up of these recommendations should also be part of the follow-up inspection.</seg>
<seg id="860">New experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of the two audit institutions are the basis for the successful implementation of the following VAT administration inspections.</seg>
<seg id="861">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="862">The report was prepared in Czech, English and German and signed by the President of the Supreme Audit Office, Czech Republic and the President of the Bundesrechnungshof, Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
</p>
