<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in the audits of the administration of excise duties between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic in 2006</seg>
<seg id="2">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="3">The submitted joint report informs on the progress and outcome of international cooperation in the parallel audits carried out by the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic and the Najvyšší Audit Office of the Slovak Republic, aimed at the administration of excise duties in the period after the accession of both countries to the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="4">The cooperation was carried out on the basis of a contract on cooperation in the audit activity concluded in February 2006.</seg>
<seg id="5">The topic of the parallel audits was chosen in view of the fundamental change in the system of collection of excise duties, which took place in connection with the integration of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic into the internal market of the European Union from 1 May 2004.</seg>
<seg id="6">The functioning of the internal market of the European Union requires the free movement of goods, including goods subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="7">The basic principle is to allow the circulation of goods free of tax until the day of their delivery for final consumption.</seg>
<seg id="8">In accordance with the above principle, the new legislation, adopted in both countries, allows goods to move under tax supervision under a conditional exemption regime.</seg>
<seg id="9">The system places great demands on the tax administration and assumes close cooperation between the competent administrative authorities of the Member States in the fight against tax fraud in this area.</seg>
<seg id="10">Report on the outcome of international cooperation in audits of excise tax administration for the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 1.</seg>
<seg id="11">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="12">Audit number: (CR) 05/34 (SR) 48/11</seg>
<seg id="13">Audit subject: (CR) Excise tax administration (SR) Procedure of the competent authorities in the administration of excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="14">On 8 February 2006, the Supreme Audit Office, the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as “SAO-CR”) and the Supreme Audit Office of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as “SAO SR”) concluded the “Contract on Cooperation in Audit Activities”.</seg>
<seg id="15">The subject of the contract was cooperation in the parallel audits "Administration of Excise Taxes", included in the SAO-CR Audit Plan for 2005 under No. 05/34, and "Control of the procedure of colných orgánov in the administration of excise taxes", included in the SAO-CR Audit Plan for 2006 under No. 48/11.</seg>
<seg id="16">The parallel audits had the character of a coordinated audit.</seg>
<seg id="17">The cooperation consisted in the exchange of information that the contracting parties could not obtain during the audit of the administration of excise taxes on the territory of their country, and in the preparation of a joint final report on the outcome of the audits within the meaning of the European implementing directives for the implementation of the INTOSAI auditing standards - Directive No. 31.</seg>
<seg id="18">On the territory of the Czech Republic, the audit (hereinafter referred to as the "CR") was carried out by groups of auditors from the State Budget Department and from the territorial departments of central Bohemia, southern Bohemia, western Bohemia, northwestern Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, northeastern Bohemia, southern Moravia, central Moravia and northern Moravia in the period from 7 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">The auditing operation involved 27 auditors.</seg>
<seg id="20">The audited bodies were the General Directorate of Customs (hereinafter referred to as "DG") and 11 financial offices.</seg>
<seg id="21">Within the DG, 12 selected customs offices out of a total of 54 were audited.</seg>
<seg id="22">The auditing operation on the territory of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as "the Slovak Republic") was carried out by the Financial and Tax Office of the Slovak Republic in cooperation with the SAO of the Slovak Republic Banská Bystrica and Košice at 5 customs offices out of a total of 9 in the period from 13 February to 2 June 2006.</seg>
<seg id="23">The auditing operation involved 8 auditors.</seg>
<seg id="24">The aim of the parallel audits was to examine the procedure of the customs authorities in the administration of excise duties and compliance with the relevant legislation in force in both countries and in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="25">The international cooperation was focused on the procedure of the tax administrators in the performance of supervision of the transport of goods subject to excise duties, in particular on the registration of started and finished transport under the suspension regime, and on the exchange of information within the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the excise tax administrators of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="26">2. Administration of excise duties</seg>
<seg id="27">The administration of excise taxes in the Czech Republic was carried out by financial authorities until 31 December 2003.</seg>
<seg id="28">Since 1 January 2004, this agenda has been taken over by customs authorities, which have so far only collected excise duty on imports.</seg>
<seg id="29">Excise taxes in the Czech Republic are subject to mineral oils, ethyl alcohol, beer, wine and intermediate products and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="30">The revenue of the state budget from excise taxes in the Czech Republic amounted to a total of 82.8 billion CZK in 2004 and 19.5% of the revenue of the state budget from taxes and fees amounted to 424.7 billion CZK.</seg>
<seg id="31">In 2005, the revenue of the state budget from excise taxes amounted to 103.6 billion CZK and the share of the revenue of the state budget from taxes and fees amounted to 460.4 billion CZK was 22.5%.</seg>
<seg id="32">In 2004, the revenue from excise duties on mineral oils to the state budget amounted to 80% of the total revenue from this tax and in 2005 it amounted to 90.9%.</seg>
<seg id="33">The difference to 100% amounting to 13 billion CZK in 2004 and 6.9 billion CZK in 2005 was the revenue of the State Fund for Transport Infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="34">The administration of all excise taxes in the Slovak Republic has been carried out by the customs authorities since 1 May 2004, with the exception of excise tax on mineral oil, which they have been administering since 1 January 2002.</seg>
<seg id="35">Until then, the administration of excise taxes was carried out by the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="36">Excise tax in the Slovak Republic is subject to mineral oil, ethyl alcohol, beer, wine and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="37">The revenue of the State Budget from excise taxes in the Slovak Republic was a total of SKK 43.4 billion in 2004 and excise taxes accounted for 20.7% of total tax revenue amounting to SKK 209.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="38">In 2005, the revenue of the State Budget from excise taxes was SKK 50 billion and excise taxes accounted for 22.5% of total tax revenue amounting to SKK 222.6 billion.</seg>
<seg id="39">Graph 1 — Comparison of revenue of the State Budget of the Czech Republic from taxes and fees and tax revenue of the State Budget of the Slovak Republic with revenue from excise taxes</seg>
<seg id="40">The legislation in both countries is based on the European Union rules governing this area, in particular: - Council Directive 92/12/EEC on the general arrangements for products subject to excise duty and on the holding, movement and monitoring of such products (hereinafter referred to as "Directive 92/12/EEC"), - Council Regulation (EC) No 2073/2004 on administrative cooperation in the field of excise duties (hereinafter referred to as "Regulation No 2073/2004"), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 2719/92 on the accompanying official document for the movement of products subject to excise duty under suspension of excise duty (hereinafter referred to as "Regulation No 2719/92"), - Commission Regulation (EEC) No 3649/92 on the simplified accompanying document for the movement within the Community of products subject to excise duty which have been released for consumption in the Member State of dispatch (hereinafter referred to as "Regulation No 3649/92").</seg>
<seg id="41">The basic legislation governing the issue of excise duties in the Czech Republic is Act No 353/2003 Coll., on excise duties, as amended (hereinafter referred to as Law No 353/2003 Coll.), which has been in force since 1 January 2004.</seg>
<seg id="42">In administering excise duties in the Slovak Republic, the customs authorities are bound, inter alia, by the following generally binding legislation: - Act No 98/2004 Coll. on the spotrebnej tax on mineral oil, as amended by the non-statutory regulations (hereinafter referred to as Law No 98/2004 Coll.), - Act No 104/2004 Coll. on the spotrebnej tax on wine, as amended by the non-statutory regulations (hereinafter referred to as Law No 104/2004 Coll.), - Act No 105/2004 Coll. on the spotrebnej tax on lieh, as amended by the non-statutory regulations (hereinafter referred to as Law No 105/2004 Coll.), - Act No 106/2004 Coll. on the spotrebnej tax on tobacco products, as amended by the non-statutory regulations (hereinafter referred to as Law No 106/2004 Coll.), - Act No 107/2004 Coll. on the spotrebnej tax on beer, as amended by the non-statutory regulations (hereinafter referred to as Law No 107/2004 Coll.).</seg>
<seg id="43">2.1 Movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty between the Member States of the European Union</seg>
<seg id="44">The conditions for movement of excise goods under suspension of excise duty are governed by Directive 92/12/EEC in Title III — Movement of goods Articles 15 to 20.</seg>
<seg id="45">According to these provisions, the movement of such goods may be carried out only by an authorised warehousekeeper, who means a natural or legal person authorised by the competent authorities of a Member State to produce, process, store, receive and dispatch products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="46">The consignee in another Member State may be an authorised warehousekeeper or an economic operator without the status of authorised warehousekeeper, but who may not store or dispatch such products under suspension of duty.</seg>
<seg id="47">Authorised warehousekeeper in the Czech Republic and Slovakia means a tax warehouse operator, the economic operator is an authorised consignee for repeated or ad hoc receipt of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="48">Transport of products subject to excise duty under suspension of duty is possible under Directive 92/12/EEC only with an accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="49">The accompanying document is issued by the consignor in four copies before the transport begins, unless the competent authorities of the Member State of dispatch require further copies.</seg>
<seg id="50">2.2 Procedure for the start and end of transport of goods under suspension of duty between the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="51">Transport from the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="52">The procedure for the start of transport is governed by the provisions of Section 25(3) of Act No 353/2003 Coll., which states, among other things:</seg>
<seg id="53">‘The tax warehouse operator shall inform the customs office which is locally competent to the tax warehouse from which the transport is to start before the transport of the selected products begins;</seg>
<seg id="54">transport of the selected products may start only with the consent of this customs office.</seg>
<seg id="55">The customs office shall give its consent for the transport of the selected products without delay after the condition of securing the tax has been fulfilled...’</seg>
<seg id="56">The consignor in the Czech Republic may start transport of all types of products subject to excise duty only with the consent of the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="57">The customs office shall only give consent to the start of transport if the securing of the tax amounting to the tax attributable to the transported products is provided.</seg>
<seg id="58">The consignor shall prepare an accompanying document in five copies before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="59">The customs office shall indicate on the accompanying document consent to the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="60">Copy No 1 shall be kept by the consignor, copies No 2, 3, and 4 shall be handed over by the consignor to the carrier and copy No 5 shall be kept by the customs office authorising the transport.</seg>
<seg id="61">According to Slovak legislation, the consignee in the Slovak Republic shall keep copy No 2 of the accompanying document. On copies No 3 and 4 he shall acknowledge receipt of the products and submit both copies to the locally competent customs office.</seg>
<seg id="62">Copy No 3 certified by the customs office shall be sent to the consignor no later than the 15th day of the month following the calendar month in which he received the products.</seg>
<seg id="63">Copy No 4 shall be kept by the customs office of the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="64">The transport is terminated by receipt of the products by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="65">The release of the tax security is decided by the customs office in the Czech Republic, which authorised the start of the transport, within 5 working days after submission of copy No 3 of the accompanying document, which is certified by the consignee and by the Slovak customs office.</seg>
<seg id="66">Graph No 2 — Circulation of the accompanying document for transport started in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="67">Transport from the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="68">The procedure for the transport of alcohol and tobacco products from the Slovak Republic to another Member State of the European Union was amended as follows until 31 December 2005:</seg>
<seg id="69">Pursuant to the provisions of Section 26(4) of Act No 105/2004 Z.</seg>
<seg id="70">‘Pri preprave liehu from a tax warehouse in the tax territory to a tax warehouse or to an authorised consignee, or to a tax agent in inom členskom štáte je odosielatel’ (supplier’) obligatory in deň začatia prepravy to send a copy of the first diel sprievodného document electronically or by fax to Colné úradu Poprad; túto kópiu is obligatory to send aj colného úradu písomne do piatich working days odo dňa začatia prepravy.’</seg>
<seg id="71">Pursuant to Article 22(4) of Law No 106/2004 Z. z.</seg>
<seg id="72">‘When transporting tobacco products from a tax warehouse in the tax territory to a tax warehouse or to an authorised consignee, or to a tax plenipotentiary in the inom Member State, the odosielatel’ (supplier) is obliged, on the day of the start of the transport, to send a copy of the first diel of the sprievodné document electronically or by fax to the Colné úrad Poprad; it is obliged to send that copy to the colný úrad pisomne najor to those working days of the start of the transport. “</seg>
<seg id="73">In respect of the transport of other products subject to excise duty (mineral oil, wine and beer) during the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005 (hereinafter referred to as the ‘audited period’), the taxpayer was not required to notify the Poprad Customs Office or the competent customs office of the start of the transport under the duty suspension arrangement.</seg>
<seg id="74">The tax administrator became aware of the transport of these products only during a local investigation or tax inspection from the accompanying documents and accounting documents of the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="75">The consignor in the Slovak Republic is obliged to prepare an accompanying document in four copies before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="76">Copy No 1 is retained by the consignor (when transporting alcohol and tobacco products, he sends a copy of Copy No 1 electronically or by fax to the Customs Office in Poprad and the relevant customs office).</seg>
<seg id="77">Copy No 2, 3 and 4 accompany the goods being transported.</seg>
<seg id="78">According to the Czech legislation, the consignee in the Czech Republic keeps Copy No 2 of the accompanying document issued by the consignor in the Slovak Republic and confirms receipt of the products on Copy No 3 and Copy No 4.</seg>
<seg id="79">Confirmed Copy No 3 and Copy No 4 is sent to the locally competent customs office in the Czech Republic at the latest on the first working day after the end of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="80">The customs office keeps Copy No 4 and Copy No 3, on which it verifies the accuracy and validity, is returned to the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="81">The consignee sends the confirmed Copy No 3 to the consignor in the Slovak Republic at the latest on the following working day after its receipt.</seg>
<seg id="82">Transport in the Slovak Republic is considered to have ended on the day of receipt of the products by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="83">Termination of transport shall be proved by the consignor submitting copy No 3 of the accompanying document certified by the consignee and the tax administrator in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="84">Graph No 3 — Circulation of the accompanying document for transport (alcohol and tobacco products) started in the Slovak Republic and finished in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="85">In 2006, amendments to all excise tax laws were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under suspension of tax is obliged to send a copy of copy No 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office of the locally competent consignor before the start of transport.</seg>
<seg id="86">The document proving the end of transport of alcohol and tobacco products shall be copy No 3 of the accompanying document certified by the consignee and his competent tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="87">The document proving the end of transport of mineral oils, wine and beer shall be copy No 3 certified by the consignee.</seg>
<seg id="88">The confirmation of the receipt of the goods by the consignee by the tax authorities of another Member State shall be required if the latter are obliged to certify copy No 3 of the accompanying document according to the legislation of the respective Member State.</seg>
<seg id="89">2.3 Registration of started and finished transport operations by customs authorities in the Czech Republic and Slovakia</seg>
<seg id="90">There is no single electronic system for monitoring the transport of goods under suspension of tax between Member States of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="91">Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003 on the introduction of an electronic system for the transport and monitoring of products subject to excise duty requires Member States and the European Commission to introduce an electronic system (Excise Movement and Control System) from 1 July 2009, which would allow excise tax authorities in individual Member States to obtain information on the transport of goods in real time.</seg>
<seg id="92">The system will enable the electronic transmission of accompanying documents, which are currently used only in paper form, and will contribute to the simplification of the movement of goods under the suspension regime and to ensuring more effective control of the movement of untaxed products within all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="93">The system will include national databases of transport operations of individual Member States.</seg>
<seg id="94">The Customs Administration of the Czech Republic records all transport operations commenced and terminated on the territory of the Czech Republic in the module of the Registration of Selected Products (hereinafter referred to as EVV).</seg>
<seg id="95">All customs authorities in the Czech Republic have on-line access to the system.</seg>
<seg id="96">In the case of transport operations carried out only on the territory of the Czech Republic, tax authorities can obtain information on the commencement or termination of the transport operation immediately after registration of the accompanying document by the customs office in EVV.</seg>
<seg id="97">The customs office releases the tax security for the transported products provided by the consignor at the moment of registration of the termination of the transport by the customs office of the locally competent consignee.</seg>
<seg id="98">Customs offices in the Slovak Republic use a database based on the application software SysNed, which provides automation of their activities in the administration of excise taxes and communication with the systems of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="99">By registering the tax warehouse, the operator of the tax warehouse or the authorised consignee in the application software SysNed, this data is automatically transferred to the database "System for Exchange of Excise Data" (hereinafter referred to as "SEED").</seg>
<seg id="100">3. Preparation and course of cooperation</seg>
<seg id="101">The first coordination meeting between representatives of the SAO-CR and representatives of the SAO of the Slovak Republic, at which the concrete process of cooperation in the implementation of parallel inspections in the field of excise taxes was discussed, took place in January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="102">Both parties became acquainted with the legislation in the field of excise taxes and with the organization of the administration of excise taxes in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="103">Special attention was paid to the procedure of the customs authorities of the CR and the Slovak Republic in authorizing, respectively, the beginning and ending of the transport of products subject to excise duty under the suspension regime and the exchange of information between the excise tax authorities of both countries.</seg>
<seg id="104">At the meeting it was agreed that the Czech and Slovak sides: - will process the total data on the quantity of products subject to excise duty transported from the CR to the SR and vice versa, whose transport started during the audited period, - will compare the data on mineral oil transport - Combined Nomenclature code 2710 and 2711 and ethyl alcohol - Combined Nomenclature code 2207 and 2208 under the suspension regime initiated in the CR and terminated in the SR and vice versa in the months of November 2004 and September 2005.</seg>
<seg id="105">During the audits, the audited periods were extended by the months of October and November 2005 and during the audits, the transport of tobacco products under the suspension regime was also subjected to the audits.</seg>
<seg id="106">Tables 1 and 2 show the total quantity of products subject to excise duty which were transported under suspension of tax between Czech and Slovak tax subjects during the audited period.</seg>
<seg id="107">4. Comparison of records of transport of goods under suspension of tax exemptions</seg>
<seg id="108">The SAO-CR provided the Slovak side with a database of transport operations terminated in the Czech Republic, which contained a total of 5,876 items listed on accompanying documents, of which 5,738 items related to mineral oils, 134 items to ethyl alcohol and 4 items to tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="109">The SAO-CR provided the Czech side with a database of transport operations terminated in the Slovak Republic, which contained a total of 3,319 items listed on accompanying documents, of which 696 items related to mineral oil, 2,066 items to ethyl alcohol and 557 items to tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="110">The SAO-CR compared data on transport operations listed in the register of commenced transport operations in the Czech Republic with data on completed transport operations registered in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="111">The results of the comparison are shown in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="112">Data on transport operations in the months of November 2004 and September 2005 were compared by the SAO-CR with the Slovak Customs Administration database, which the SAO handed over to the SAO at the beginning of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="113">The database did not contain data allowing reliable reconciliation of individual transport operations and therefore only 63 % of commenced transport operations were assigned.</seg>
<seg id="114">Individual transport operations were assigned according to more data, e.g. consignor, consignee, date of transport, quantity of transported products.</seg>
<seg id="115">Data on transport operations commenced in the Czech Republic and terminated in the Slovak Republic in the months of October and November 2005 were compared by the SAO-CR with the Slovak Customs Administration database, which contained all data according to accompanying documents, on the basis of which 93 % of commenced transport operations were unambiguously assigned.</seg>
<seg id="116">In the database of the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic, data on the quantity of mineral oils were given in litres or in tonnes depending on the type of mineral oil.</seg>
<seg id="117">The quantity of alcohol was given in litres in most cases, which could be converted into litres of absolute alcohol based on the database of the stated percentage of alcohol content.</seg>
<seg id="118">The quantity of tobacco products was given in pieces, in thousands of pieces and in kilograms according to the type of tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="119">In the case of transport operations initiated in the Czech Republic, the completion of which could not be reliably verified in the Slovak database or where the data on the transported quantity of products did not match, the accompanying documents were checked.</seg>
<seg id="120">The documents accompanying 487 transport operations of alcohol, mineral oils and tobacco products were checked.</seg>
<seg id="121">The documents were checked at the customs offices, where the SAO-CR performed the check.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the case of transport operations authorised by other customs offices, the accompanying documents were requested via the DG.</seg>
<seg id="123">The Czech side asked the Slovak side to verify the realization of 141 shipments for which the customs offices in the CR did not prove the certified copies No.3 of the accompanying document, or the quantity of products indicated on the accompanying document did not correspond with the quantity of products indicated in the database.</seg>
<seg id="124">In addition, the Slovak side was provided with data on the shipments registered in the Slovak database, which, however, did not contain the database of the Czech customs administration's shipments.</seg>
<seg id="125">The SAO SR searched the Slovak customs administration's database for 95 shipments.</seg>
<seg id="126">The verification of the remaining 46 shipments was requested by the locally competent customs offices, which proved their completion with copies of accompanying documents.</seg>
<seg id="127">The Slovak side provided the Czech side with copies of accompanying documents, on the basis of which the shipments were identified also in the Czech database, with the exception of the shipments carried out by two Czech tax entities, which were not found in the Czech database of commenced shipments.</seg>
<seg id="128">The audit of these cases found:</seg>
<seg id="129">- in the Slovak database of transports, 11 transports of alcohol in the total amount of 276.7 litres of alcohol carried out by the Czech tax entity in 2004 and 20 transports of alcohol in the total amount of 404.66 litres of alcohol carried out in 2005 were registered.</seg>
<seg id="130">The SAO-CR found that these were transports of taxed products, for which the consignor does not need the consent of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="131">The consignor informed the tax administrator in writing about the commencement of the transport. The transport was carried out on the basis of accompanying documents, which are used for the transport of products under the suspension of tax;</seg>
<seg id="132">- in the Slovak database of transports, a total of 94 transports of mineral oils, Combined Nomenclature code 2710 11 21, were registered in the total amount of 173 thousand litres carried out by the Czech tax entity in the period from September 2004 to December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="133">The SAO-CR found that in the period from May 2004 to June 2005 the tax entity carried out the transport of 102 thousand litres of untaxed mineral oils without the appropriate authorization.</seg>
<seg id="134">The tax entity held a special authorization for receiving and using products exempt from tax, on the basis of which it could supply untaxed products only to the holder of the same authorization.</seg>
<seg id="135">It did not notify the customs office in the CR of the start of the transport and did not provide a tax security of CZK 1,207,680 for the transported products.</seg>
<seg id="136">In the period July 2005 to December 2005, the tax entity transported 71 thousand litres of taxed mineral oils to the territory of the SR. Even in these cases, it did not fulfil the legal obligation by failing to notify the customs office of the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="137">The consignor in the CR can start the transport of products put into free tax circulation in the tax territory of the CR without the consent of the customs office, but he is obliged to inform the customs office of this fact in writing before the start of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="138">The tax entity receiving products put into free tax circulation in another Member State is obliged to declare the quantity and ensure the tax before their withdrawal.</seg>
<seg id="139">The products can be transported only with a simplified accompanying document, the particulars of which are regulated by Regulation No 3649/92.</seg>
<seg id="140">This regulation also allows the use of an accompanying document for transport under suspension of tax, but it must be clearly indicated that it is a "simplified accompanying document for the purposes of tax control (products subject to excise duty)".</seg>
<seg id="141">The same regulation of transport and acceptance of products placed into free tax circulation in another Member State applies in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="142">In these cases, the tax entities transported the products placed into free tax circulation with an accompanying document for transport under suspension of tax, the 3rd and 4th copies of which were submitted by the consignee to the tax administrator in the Slovak Republic for verification.</seg>
<seg id="143">The customs authorities in the Slovak Republic registered these transportations in the database of transport under suspension of tax, as the accompanying documents did not state that it was a simplified accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="144">The SAO of the Slovak Republic compared the database of transport of the Czech customs administration with the Slovak customs administration's database of transport and found:</seg>
<seg id="145">- in the databases, the quantity of transported products was stated inconsistently, e.g. mineral oil was given in litres, in hectolitres or in kilograms; alcohol was given in litres or litres of alcohol, making it difficult to compare the transported quantity of goods;</seg>
<seg id="146">- the quantity of transported alcohol given in invoices did not match the quantity recorded in the databases;</seg>
<seg id="147">- in the databases, not all related invoices were given;</seg>
<seg id="148">- in the Slovak customs administration's database, two transports of alcohol from the Czech Republic to the Slovak Republic carried out in November 2004 in a total volume of 47 237 litres of alcohol were recorded, which were not found in the Czech customs administration's database.</seg>
<seg id="149">The Slovak side handed over copies of the accompanying documents to the Czech side.</seg>
<seg id="150">5. International exchange of information between the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic</seg>
<seg id="151">Until 30 June 2005, the conditions of cooperation between the administrative authorities of the Member States responsible for the administration of excise duties were regulated by Council Directive 77/799/EEC, concerning mutual assistance between the competent authorities of the Member States in the field of direct taxes, certain excise duties and taxes on insurance premiums.</seg>
<seg id="152">On 1 July 2005, Regulation No 2073/2004 entered into force, laying down rules and procedures allowing the competent authorities of the Member States of the European Union to cooperate and exchange the information necessary for the correct assessment of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="153">Each Member State shall designate a central liaison office, which shall ensure contacts with other Member States in the field of administration of excise duties and shall be responsible for the exchange of information on the movement of excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="154">In the Czech Republic, in order to ensure the exchange of information in the field of excise duties between the Member States of the European Union, an “Excise Liaison Office” (hereinafter referred to as “ELO ČR”) has been established at the DG.</seg>
<seg id="155">With effect from 1 May 2004, the ELO at the Poprad Customs Office was responsible for ensuring the management of the systems for controlling the movement of excise goods (SEED, MVS, EWSE) and the exchange of information in the framework of mutual administrative assistance between the Member States of the European Union and the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="156">With effect from 1 July 2005, the tasks of ELO are carried out by the ELO Unit (based in Poprad) of the Excise Department of the Customs Directorate of the Slovak Republic (hereinafter referred to as ‘ELO SR’).</seg>
<seg id="157">Under Article 3(3) of Regulation No 2073/2004, the central liaison office is responsible in particular for: - the exchange of data held in the electronic register of the SEED, - the Early Warning System Excise (EWSE), - requests for verification of movements of excise goods sent to or received from other Member States by the Movement Verification System (MVS).</seg>
<seg id="158">The content, scope and functions of the SEED, EWSE and ISA systems are governed by Articles 22, 23 and 24 of Regulation No 2073/2004.</seg>
<seg id="159">SEED - System for the exchange of information on tax subjects trading in excise goods.</seg>
<seg id="160">The system is made up of national excise tax registers and allows tax authorities in the territory of the European Union to ascertain whether excise products are traded by a person authorised to do so.</seg>
<seg id="161">Each national register is made available to the competent authorities of other Member States for excise purposes only.</seg>
<seg id="162">The central liaison office of each Member State ensures that persons involved in the movement of excise goods in the territory of the European Union can obtain confirmation of the information held in this database.</seg>
<seg id="163">In accordance with § 41 of Act No 98/2004 Z., with § 39 of Act No 104/2004 Z., with § 46 of Act No 105/2004 Z., with § 40 of Act No 106/2004 Z. and with § 39 of Act No 107/2004 Z. ELO SR maintains an electronic database containing a register of tax warehouse operators, authorised recipients and tax warehouses - the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="164">Customs offices in SR contribute to the SEED database by registering the tax warehouse, tax warehouse operator or authorised recipient in the SysNed application software, which is automatically connected to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="165">For example, if a new tax warehouse operator, authorised recipient or tax warehouse is registered in the SysNed database, the related data are automatically transferred to the SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="166">The SAO SR found that the exchange of SEED databases between the Slovak Customs Administration and the Customs Administration of the Czech Republic took place in the audited period usually once a month, exceptionally several times a month.</seg>
<seg id="167">The Customs Administration of the Slovak Republic received 22 SEED files and sent 25 SEED files.</seg>
<seg id="168">The data are transferred to the SEED database in the Czech Republic from the national register, in which all persons authorised to dispose of products subject to excise duty and issued authorisations to dispose of these products are recorded.</seg>
<seg id="169">Individual customs offices in the Czech Republic do not have access to the international SEED database.</seg>
<seg id="170">Requests from customs offices to provide information from the SEED database of other member countries are obtained only through ELO CR.</seg>
<seg id="171">EWSE - an early warning system focused on controlling the transport of goods subject to excise duty, through which the transport of risky consignments is announced.</seg>
<seg id="172">Transport of certain products subject to excise duty in quantities exceeding the limits set by a regulation of the European Commission is considered to be a risky consignment, and transport that is evaluated as a risk by the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="173">The exchange of information takes two forms:</seg>
<seg id="174">- information - is sent when the established limits are exceeded,</seg>
<seg id="175">- a warning message - is sent when the transport of goods is evaluated as a risk.</seg>
<seg id="176">When assessing the degree of risk of a consignment, ELO SR uses the SEED database for sending the warning message, on the basis of which it checks the data stated in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="177">If the data in the SEED database does not match the data in the accompanying document (for example, the registration number of the consignee of the goods or the registered office of the consignee does not match), ELO SR draws up a warning message, which it sends to the ELO office of the Member State of the consignee of the goods.</seg>
<seg id="178">ELO follows the regulations of the Tax and Customs Commission CED 317 and CED 457 when drawing up the reports, which among other things determine the type and quantity of goods in the respective measurement units for drawing up informative and warning messages.</seg>
<seg id="179">During the audited period, ELO SR sent one warning message to ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, information on initiated transport of products in quantities exceeding the specified limits is generated automatically when entering the data from the accompanying document into the database at the time of transport approval.</seg>
<seg id="181">If the tax administrator in the Czech Republic evaluates a consignment as risky on the basis of its own analysis, it prepares a so-called warning message, which it sends to the respective Member State via ELO ČR.</seg>
<seg id="182">In 2005, ELO ČR sent two warning messages to ELO SR.</seg>
<seg id="183">The MVS - the system for controlling the movement of goods - allows through MVS requests to control individual transports of products subject to excise duty as well as the control of the specified transport route between the entities mentioned in the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="184">The exchange of information takes place on the basis of a request in which ELO of the sending country specifies its requirements.</seg>
<seg id="185">The system is used especially in cases where the consignor takes over the certified copy No.3 of the accompanying document and requests e.g. reimbursement of excise duty, and in cases where the data stated in the accompanying document cannot be verified in the international database SEED.</seg>
<seg id="186">In the audited period ELO SR sent 33 requests to MVS.</seg>
<seg id="187">ELO ČR sent 25 requests to MVS.</seg>
<seg id="188">Customs offices in the Czech Republic most often examined the data stated in the accompanying documents, especially the quantity of received or dispatched products or whether the consignor of products mentioned in the accompanying document is entitled to dispose of products subject to excise duty, if this fact could not be verified in the international database SEED.</seg>
<seg id="189">Received requests from MVS were in both countries forwarded to customs offices locally competent for the consignee or consignor of products subject to excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="190">Customs offices verified the required data and notified the result of the investigation through ELO to the other member country.</seg>
<seg id="191">6. Summary</seg>
<seg id="192">Cooperation between the SAO and the SAO SR enabled to compare the basic legislation governing the area of excise duties in both countries, the procedure of the customs authorities of the Czech Republic and Slovakia when starting and ending the transport of products under the suspension regime between the two countries, the registration of these transports and to compare the exchange of information between customs authorities within the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="193">6.1 Comparison of legislation governing the area of excise duties in the Czech Republic and Slovakia revealed differences:</seg>
<seg id="194">a) in the procedure of tax entities and tax administrators when starting the transport of products under the suspension regime.</seg>
<seg id="195">The transport of products under suspension of tax exemption can be started by a tax subject in the Czech Republic only with the consent of the tax administrator, who will allow the transport to start on condition that the transported products have been provided with a guarantee of tax amounting to the amount of tax attributable to them.</seg>
<seg id="196">The start of the transport of products under suspension of tax exemption in the Slovak Republic is not subject to the permission of the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="197">During the audited period, the tax subject was obliged to notify the tax administrator of the start of the transport of alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="198">The transport of mineral oils, beer and wine could start without informing the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="199">In 2006, amendments to all excise tax laws were gradually adopted in the Slovak Republic, according to which the consignor of goods under suspension of tax is obliged to send a copy No. 1 of the accompanying document electronically or by fax to the customs office, which is competent locally, before the transport starts;</seg>
<seg id="200">b) within the deadlines for sending copy No. 3 of the accompanying document.</seg>
<seg id="201">The consignee in the Czech Republic is obliged to send copy No.3 and copy No.4 of the accompanying document to the tax administrator for verification no later than the following working day after the completion of the transport.</seg>
<seg id="202">The certified copy No.3 is obliged to send to the consignor no later than the following working day after its receipt from the tax administrator.</seg>
<seg id="203">The consignee in the Slovak Republic is obliged to send to the consignor of products copy No.3 confirmed by the tax administrator and the consignee of the products no later than the 15th day of the month following the month in which he received the goods.</seg>
<seg id="204">6.2. Customs authorities in both the Slovak Republic and the Czech Republic keep electronic records of transport of products under suspension of excise duty.</seg>
<seg id="205">The content and manner of keeping such records is not regulated by legislation in the Czech Republic or the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="206">Customs authorities in both countries enter into the records all data from accompanying documents on the basis of which the transport is carried out.</seg>
<seg id="207">For the monitoring of the transport of goods under suspension of tax between Member States of the European Union, there is currently no single electronic system that allows excise tax authorities in each Member State to obtain information on the transport of goods in real time.</seg>
<seg id="208">According to Decision 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 16 June 2003, the introduction of an electronic system for the monitoring of the transport of products subject to excise tax is foreseen from 1 July 2009.</seg>
<seg id="209">On the basis of a contract on cooperation in control activities, the Czech side transmitted to the Slovak side a database of transports of products under suspension of tax started in the Slovak Republic and finished in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="210">The database contained 5 876 items relating to transported mineral oils, alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="211">The Slovak side transmitted to the Czech side a database of transports of products under suspension of tax started in the Czech Republic and finished in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="212">The database contained 3 319 items relating to transported mineral oils, ethyl alcohol and tobacco products.</seg>
<seg id="213">The Czech side compared the data on transport operations listed in the register of commenced transport operations in the Czech Republic with the register of transport operations terminated in the Slovak Republic.</seg>
<seg id="214">The Slovak side compared the data on transport operations of goods under suspension of tax commenced in the Slovak Republic and terminated in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="215">The comparison of the data was made more difficult by the fact that the quantity of transported goods was not reported uniformly in the databases.</seg>
<seg id="216">In cases where it was not possible to unambiguously assign the data on individual transport operations in the two registers, a check of the accompanying documents was carried out and no violations of the suspension of tax or cases of tax evasion were detected.</seg>
<seg id="217">Based on the findings from the parallel checks, it can be concluded that Member States can obtain valuable information from the transport registers to improve the administration of excise duties.</seg>
<seg id="218">The establishment of an electronic system for the transport and control of excise goods within the meaning of Decision No 1152/2003/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council will allow the electronic transmission of the accompanying document and more efficient control of movements under the suspension arrangement in the territory of the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="219">Communiqué</seg>
<seg id="220">This report was prepared in Czech, English and Slovak languages.</seg>
<seg id="221">The report was signed by the President of the Najvyššie Audit Office of the Slovak Republic and the President of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
<doc docid="testsuite-segment_65-KA_09_11_OCR" genre="news" origlang="en" sysid="CUNI-DocTransformer2020">
<p>
<seg id="1">Value Added Tax Administration in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the results of the ex-post audit</seg>
<seg id="3">Introductory word</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes generally constitute a key source of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="5">It goes without saying that Supreme Audit Institutions (SAIs) should focus their attention on this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">An example of this is value added tax (VAT) fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">In their case, a loss of EUR 100 billion is estimated every year in the European Union (EU).</seg>
<seg id="8">Already in 2005, participants of the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn agreed on the need for very close cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">As part of this cooperation, SAIs can exchange control procedures, find the best solutions, etc.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is a very suitable area for audit cooperation, as it is the only tax harmonised within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="11">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (SAO) and the Federal Court of Auditors (Bundesrechnungshof, BRH) carried out the first parallel audit in the field of VAT in 2006.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is not limited to a single country, but is spread throughout the EU, close cooperation between SAIs is necessary to ensure a comprehensive evaluation of the steps taken to solve this problem.</seg>
<seg id="14">Both SAIs therefore decided to further develop cooperation in this area and carried out the subsequent parallel auditing.</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Audit number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Audit subject: (CZ) Value Added Tax Administration (D) Bilateral audit with the SAO (follow-up audit)</seg>
<seg id="18">Audit objective:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The aim of the auditing operation was to examine the procedure of the financial authorities in the administration of VAT, in particular to verify the procedure for resolving selected cases of commercial transactions between the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as Germany), and to examine the procedures of the tax administrations of both countries within the framework of international cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The auditing operation was designed to evaluate the measures taken by the tax administration to implement the recommendations issued by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="21">It was also intended to cover other areas related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="22">The resulting audit findings were intended for comparison with the established best practice (if any).</seg>
<seg id="23">The audited period covered the years 2006 to 2008, in case of factual connections also the periods before and after, until the end of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of parallel audit actions</seg>
<seg id="25">The follow-up audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two SAIs.</seg>
<seg id="26">During the previous parallel audits, suspicious cases of intra-community transactions were detected.</seg>
<seg id="27">Some of them required further examination.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on the audit findings, both SAIs formulated recommendations concerning the VAT administration.</seg>
<seg id="29">The follow-up audit action performed was used to evaluate the measures taken in response to these recommendations and to examine selected suspicious cases.</seg>
<seg id="30">Furthermore, the audit focused on, for example, selected cases of high-risk intra-community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of claims and the implementation of VAT controls on large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the audit of the VAT administration in selected areas in both countries, the auditors arrived at the following audit findings:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations from the previous audit</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Conditions of registration of payers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In previous parallel controls, a comparison of the VAT registration systems in both countries revealed differences.</seg>
<seg id="35">As the different registration methods cause problems, both SAIs recommended harmonising the conditions of registration of payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This recommendation was presented at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The proposal to amend Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 on administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax and repealing Regulation (EEC) No 218/92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003") called for the extension of existing databases within the EU, including the VAT payers' tax identification numbers database.</seg>
<seg id="38">It also modified common standards for the registration and deregistration of tax payers.</seg>
<seg id="39">The SAIs expected EU Member States to agree on appropriate standards to support their decision to exclude unreliable traders from the VAT system as quickly as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">However, the latest version of this document, agreed by EU Member States in the framework of ECOFIN, no longer contains the mentioned issue.</seg>
<seg id="41">Both SAIs regret that the idea of common minimum standards has been abandoned.</seg>
<seg id="42">However, they continue to consider this intention as a relevant tool for prevention in the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="44">In the framework of international cooperation, a previous control action recommended that all EU States introduce a monthly deadline for the submission of recapitulative statements to allow for a more timely verification of the values of intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion linked to intra-Community transactions reduces the period for the submission of recapitulative statements on intra-EU transactions to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this measure was implemented through the Value Added Tax Act with effect from 1 January 2010, in Germany it was implemented from 1 July 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the obligation to submit recapitulative statements monthly was not introduced by the deadline in accordance with the applicable EU rules, while in the Czech Republic it was.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Comparison of data in VAT returns and recapitulative statements in Germany to achieve greater reliability of data in the VIES system and consideration of linking the two systems for VAT returns and recapitulative statements</seg>
<seg id="49">The German tax administration accepted the BRH's recommendations and set up a working group to explore possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="50">Work is still ongoing and the BRH will closely monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Sharing of successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system at EU level Based on the results of the previous audit, both SAIs agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by only one Member State.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria, components and approaches of the risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in individual EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not the case, the perpetrators of fraudulent activities will choose the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The audit found that our two Member States use different risk management systems, which have their advantages and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">In this area, the SAO carried out an audit of the EUROCANET system, which allows exchange of information within the EU, while the BRH focused on the German participation in the so-called risk management platform.</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Follow-up of selected cases of intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the previous audit operation, business transactions where there were doubts about their completion or irregularities in the reporting of business transactions in tax returns or summary reports by tax payers from both countries were examined together.</seg>
<seg id="58">The two SAIs selected nine cases for the follow-up, which included intra-Community movement of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits carried out by the tax authorities of the respective countries were not closed on the date of completion of our previous joint audit operation.</seg>
<seg id="60">The follow-up operation verified that most of the tax procedures related to the selected cases of commercial transactions between tax payers from the Czech Republic and Germany were closed and that adequate measures were taken by the tax administration of the Czech Republic or Germany (e.g. additional VAT assessments or avoidance of input tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Audit of selected cases of risky intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">High-risk cases of intra-community transactions carried out by EU payers, which were included in the EUROCANET system, were selected for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="63">The EUROCANET system is a tool for detecting risky tax payers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="64">Participation of the Member States in the system is voluntary.</seg>
<seg id="65">The Czech Republic is an active participant in the EUROCANET system, while Germany has a passive status.</seg>
<seg id="66">It is unsatisfactory for an active participant in the system if some Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">Due to the fact that the German tax administration did not participate in the exchange of data in the EUROCANET system, it was not possible to obtain any information about which suppliers with the German VAT ID were assessed as risky.</seg>
<seg id="68">The SAO found cases of common commercial transactions as well as cases of suspected involvement in carousel transactions or fraudulent behaviour related to VAT.</seg>
<seg id="69">Tax administrators have limited possibilities of controlling risky transactions, especially when it comes to missing traders, and mere physical verification of documents can hardly prove any fraudulent behaviour to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">A similar situation arises for tax administrators when imports and exports to third countries are linked to intra-Community carousel trades.</seg>
<seg id="71">In such cases, it would be advisable to ensure greater cooperation between customs and financial authorities in order to identify goods and irregularities in transport documentation as well as to monitor their physical movement within the EU towards the final consumer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany, like some other countries, is hesitant to actively participate in EUROCANET due to the lack of a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">In Germany, other tools for detecting risky tax payers are being used, which until now have proved successful for the German tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="74">In this area, there is a need to communicate and exchange experiences between EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU reached a political agreement on a draft regulation amending Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.</seg>
<seg id="76">Its main innovation is the creation of the EUROFISC network.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far in using EUROCANET should be the basis for the creation of this new network for combating VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance for the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">In the area of international assistance for the recovery of claims, all EU Member States are governed by the same European legislation.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, the way of handling requests for international assistance for the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic and Germany is the same.</seg>
<seg id="81">The SAO and BRH compared the statistics submitted by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006-2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">The data contained in these statistics were not the same.</seg>
<seg id="83">Both SAIs consider it useful to renegotiate the statistics at EU level in order to find a way to avoid persistent discrepancies.</seg>
<seg id="84">Without this, the statistics will not be reliable and comparable.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the SAIs agree that reliable statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">It would probably be useful for the Commission to prepare an analysis based on more detailed statistics to help the Member States strengthen the effectiveness of the fight against VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">In the opinion of both SAIs, this means helping Member States with a low recovery rate so that they can increase the recovery rate to at least the EU average.</seg>
