<seg id="499">4.5.1 Control of large tax entities in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="500">General information</seg>
<seg id="501">The VAT audit of large tax entities is governed by the same rules as that of other tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="502">The procedural procedure for the control of VDS is based on Act No. 337/1992 Coll., on the Administration of Taxes and Fees.</seg>
<seg id="503">The Czech Ministry of Finance defined VDS as natural or legal persons that were established or established for the purpose of business and whose net turnover for the tax period stated in the personal/corporate income tax return amounted to CZK 2 billion or more.</seg>
<seg id="504">The classification of a tax entity as a VDS took place after the submission of the income tax return for the relevant tax period, for the first time for 2003.</seg>
<seg id="505">A tax entity ceased to be referred to as a VDS if, in three consecutive tax periods from the end of the period on which it submitted the tax return on the basis of which it was classified as a VDS, its net turnover for the tax period fell below the stated limit.</seg>
<seg id="506">A tax entity was not allowed to be removed from the VDS register without carrying out a tax audit of at least one tax for one tax period.</seg>
<seg id="507">All VDS were audited at least every five years until the end of 2009.</seg>
<seg id="508">Since 2010, a written evaluation of the tax entity must be carried out at least every two years and the chosen subsequent procedure must eliminate the tax risks and their negative impact on the correct determination and collection of the tax.</seg>
<seg id="509">The audit of the FÚ is focused on at least one type of tax; the tax administrator usually chooses several tax periods at once.</seg>
<seg id="510">The VDS were audited by specialised audit departments, which are set up at 13 FUs in total, or by the staff of the audit departments of the locally competent FUs.</seg>
<seg id="511">The specialised audit departments carry out tax audits within the remit set by the Director of the Financial Directorate.</seg>
<seg id="512">In addition to large tax entity audits, it also examines</seg>
<seg id="513">• tax entities operating in unusual and specific fields of business;</seg>
<seg id="514">• entities where carrying out a tax audit is technically and extremely time-consuming;</seg>
<seg id="515">• entities with a branched territorial and organisational structure;</seg>
<seg id="516">• entities suspected of large-scale tax evasion;</seg>
<seg id="517">• entities connected in chains and networks where there is a suspicion of large-scale tax evasion and unjustified enticement of excessive deductions.</seg>
<seg id="518">The number of tax audits carried out by specialised audit departments of the FUs and the results of these audits are shown in Table 3.</seg>
<seg id="519">The Czech Ministry of Finance has proposed an amendment to Act No 531/1990 Coll., on territorial financial authorities, which consists in the establishment of a specialised Tax Office with nationwide coverage for selected tax entities (i.a. for legal entities set up for the purpose of business which have a turnover of more than CZK 2 billion).</seg>
<seg id="520">4.5.2 Inspection of large tax entities in Germany</seg>
<seg id="521">General information</seg>
<seg id="522">VAT inspections of large companies are governed by the same rules as tax inspections in general, i.e. the relevant provisions are enshrined in the following regulations: • the German Fiscal Code (AO), • the Fiscal Administration Act (FVG), • the regulations on tax inspections (BpO).</seg>
<seg id="523">Other methodological documents are also in force.</seg>
<seg id="524">The German Fiscal Code</seg>
<seg id="525">The statutory control provisions are enshrined in sections 193-203 of the German Fiscal Code in Section IV - Tax Control on Site. These articles enshrine in particular the rules on the admissibility of tax control on site (i.e. on the premises of an undertaking), their scope in terms of subject matter, the rules on the allocation of responsibilities, the form and content of the control notice, the control principles, the obligations of the taxpayer to cooperate and the prerequisites for carrying out the final examination and communication of the control report.</seg>
<seg id="526">Tax control on site is carried out by the responsible tax authorities (section 195 of the Code).</seg>
<seg id="527">Fiscal Governance Act According to section 5.1, point 1, in conjunction with section 19 of the Act, participation in tax controls on site by the tax authorities is compulsory for the Federal Central Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="528">The authorities involved agree with each other on the spot the nature and extent of the Federal Central Tax Office's participation in tax controls.</seg>
<seg id="529">In addition, the Federal Central Tax Office has the right to require that the specific undertakings it chooses be subject to an inspection at a time it determines.</seg>
<seg id="530">In such a case, it may declare the rules for the conduct and content of the inspection at the premises of those companies.</seg>
<seg id="531">Tax inspection regulations Under Article 108.7 of the German Constitution, the regulations on tax inspections (German abbreviation BpO 2000) have been approved by the Federal Council (Bundesrat, the upper house of the German Parliament in which the governments of the Länder are represented).</seg>
<seg id="532">These administrative regulations apply to the on-the-spot check carried out by the tax authorities of the Länder and by the Federal Central Tax Office.</seg>
<seg id="533">The undertakings are classified by size at regular intervals, in accordance with Article 3 of the BpO 2000.</seg>
<seg id="534">Large undertakings are subject to subsequent inspection (Article 4.2 of the BpO).</seg>
<seg id="535">Under Article 33.1 of the BpO 2000, each informed tax office must keep a register of groups of companies as defined in the BpO 2000.</seg>
<seg id="536">Methodological guidelines</seg>
<seg id="537">In addition to the above, the following guidelines set out an additional methodology for the tax administration:</seg>
<seg id="538">• Uniform manual for special VAT controls in Germany ;</seg>
<seg id="539">• USLO manual, which sets out the methodology for using data on intra-Community business relations kept in the VIES system;</seg>
<seg id="540">• ZAUBER manual, which sets out the methodology for using the ZAUBER database;</seg>
<seg id="541">• Work aids for various and special objects.</seg>
<seg id="542">The classification of tax entities is based on criteria such as turnover and net profit, with different thresholds depending on the type of business.</seg>
<seg id="543">The data is published by the Federal Ministry of Finance.</seg>
<seg id="544">They are evaluated every three years and fixed for the following three years.</seg>
<seg id="545">The number of companies to be inspected - not just large enterprises - must be determined at regular inspection intervals.</seg>
<seg id="546">As a general rule, inspections of large enterprises are carried out on an ongoing basis.</seg>
<seg id="547">Inspections are usually announced, including VAT inspections.</seg>
<seg id="548">This means that during the inspection, inspections are carried out definitively mainly on income tax, excise tax and VAT - i.e. inspections of all types of relevant taxes.</seg>
<seg id="549">VAT inspections can be carried out either by tax inspectors or by VAT inspectors.</seg>
<seg id="550">Implementation varies and depends on the organisational arrangements of the Länder.</seg>
<seg id="551">The number of tax periods covered by inspections usually varies between three and five years.</seg>
<seg id="552">The BpO 2000 foresees a control period of three years.</seg>
<seg id="553">All taxes of the company are subject to inspection.</seg>
<seg id="554">4.5.3 Management of control of large tax entities</seg>
<seg id="555">Both SAIs decided not to examine individual cases of VDS inspections carried out, but focused on management issues in order to obtain an overview of how the tax administrations manage the issue of VAT inspections at VDS.</seg>
<seg id="556">In the form of a questionnaire, they gathered information from the tax administrations on the areas they consider essential for managing this issue.</seg>
<seg id="557">• What statistical records and analyses are available to the management of the tax administrations regarding the VAT inspection at VDS?</seg>
<seg id="558">In particular:</seg>
<seg id="559">• Are there any statistics or records of the extent to which a distinction is made between the fight against VAT fraud and VAT control in general?</seg>
<seg id="560">Czech Republic: No, the ADIS system does not allow such a distinction with the current data version.</seg>
<seg id="561">Germany: The tax administration does not distinguish between control designed to fight VAT fraud and general VAT control.</seg>
<seg id="562">• Are there any statistics or records of the timeliness of VAT controls (in relation to the time period of the audited transactions)?</seg>
<seg id="563">Czech Republic: The records of the timeliness of the questioning with relevance for intra-community acquisitions of goods for selected VAT payers are reported in the ADIS system.</seg>
<seg id="564">In addition, the information recorded in the ADIS system also includes data of the type of time the questioning took.</seg>
<seg id="565">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors only contain information on the average time of the last inspection (information on the year).</seg>
<seg id="566">This data does not provide an overview of the selected inspection periods with regard to individual entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="567">VAT inspectors focus on the most recent tax assessment period; they also have the right to carry out VDS checks.</seg>
<seg id="568">However, the statistics produced at federal level for special VAT inspection units do not provide information on the classification of tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="569">• There are any statistics or records on the nature of the tax revenues additionally generated, broken down e.g. according to the following criteria:</seg>
<seg id="570">i. net increase in tax liability (e.g. in cases where a tax entity has unduly applied a reduced VAT rate instead of the standard tax rate);</seg>
<seg id="571">ii. only nominal increase in tax liability (e.g. transfer of a fully qualified VAT case to another tax period);</seg>
<seg id="572">iii. additional collection of tax revenue (payment of outstanding additional tax due).</seg>
<seg id="573">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech tax administration monitors the number of tax verifications carried out, the amounts of additional tax assessed broken down by type of tax, by the number of tax entities audited and by the number of tax periods audited.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (local investigations, complaints procedures) are monitored in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">Time data and amounts of additional taxes paid are recorded as a separate task.</seg>
<seg id="577">Statistics on general debts are also kept broken down by type of tax, but not by the declared tax or the tax determined by the tax administration.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not distinguish between the above criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">Moreover, the majority of tax administrations visited do not distinguish between these differences either.</seg>
<seg id="580">• Are inspection areas registered which generate high additional revenues?</seg>
<seg id="581">Czech Republic: Yes, the tax administration has the right to select tax payers for verification on the basis of criteria which can be linked to the selected indicators in the special sections of the ADIS.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">It follows that the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, there is one coordinated approach by the finance ministers of the Länder and the federal government.</seg>
<seg id="585">In the ZAUBER database, tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder must record their increased tax (VAT) liability if it exceeds a certain amount.</seg>
<seg id="586">In such a case, they must specify, for example, the nature of the increased tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="587">• What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">Czech Republic:</seg>
<seg id="589">- The VDS claim an unjustified right to deduct input tax on supplies and services:</seg>
<seg id="590">• which have not been used to carry out any economic activity pursuant to Section 72(1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="591">• which have been used for representation pursuant to Section 75(3) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="592">• on the basis of tax documents which did not meet the requirements laid down in Section 73(1) of the VAT Act;</seg>
<seg id="593">- The VDS did not declare output VAT pursuant to Section 21(1) of the VAT Act.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: It has been established that there are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">It follows that the uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not provide such data.</seg>
<seg id="596">Findings relating to VAT are not separately registered by the Länder insofar as they result from the tax inspections of the VDS.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, in the ZAUBER database, where tax inspectors or tax investigators from the Länder have to enter their increased tax (VAT) liability if it exceeds a certain amount, the Federal Central Tax Office is able to analyse this information.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the tax administration carry out analyses of the control areas from which a high "return" results and draw the consequences for the management?</seg>
<seg id="599">Czech Republic: Yes, for example, they launch nationwide audits focusing on risky commodities or the subject of economic activity.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">The uniform statistics at federal level for tax inspectors and special VAT inspection units do not provide data on the audit areas from which a high "return" results.</seg>
<seg id="602">There are different views on the process of analysis as well as on case management in terms of materiality.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some regional tax offices provide special information, but its use is at the discretion of the tax authorities.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">The differences in the replies of the two Member States show that the Czech Republic provides a system that collects a lot of data from the tax inspections carried out as well as data from the financial statements - balance sheet and profit and loss statements.</seg>
<seg id="606">Based on a wide range of data, the Czech Republic is able to guide the selection of risk-prone cases.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same is true of VAT control analysis and management in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In 2012, the establishment of a specialised tax office for the administration of VDS is planned in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect this information.</seg>
<seg id="610">This makes it more difficult to carry out these tasks in a similar way.</seg>
<seg id="611">However, the philosophy of Germany places more emphasis on the selection of individual cases based on data from submitted tax returns.</seg>
<seg id="612">Therefore, the risk management components will be strengthened and improved.</seg>
<seg id="613">Based on adequate reference notes, expert auditors must be able to assess the exact amount of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="614">Both SAIs agree that the Member States should be able to ensure adequate financial management as well as an adequate risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="615">This will help to reduce the shortfall in VAT revenues.</seg>
<seg id="616">As a result, the revenue from VAT collection will increase and the level of risk detection for unreliable entrepreneurs will also improve.</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusion</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of both SAIs on parallel controls of VAT administration met the objectives set by the SAO and the BRH.</seg>
<seg id="619">Both SAIs got to know each other better the systems in place in the following areas: • intra-community transactions; • VAT risk management, especially with regard to the selection of transactions with a propensity to risk; • assistance in the recovery of VAT claims; and • VAT control of large tax entities.</seg>
<seg id="620">Thanks to the mutual cooperation, differences in the strategies for detecting cases of VAT fraud as well as differences in the above mentioned areas of VAT administration were revealed in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="621">Control findings have been compared and best practices have been identified on the basis of them.</seg>
<seg id="622">In addition, both SAIs hope that the results achieved will provide an impetus for stakeholders to start a discussion on approaches and strategies within the Member States, among them at the level of the European Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The extremely valuable experience and knowledge gained from the cooperation of both SAIs can serve as an encouragement for the implementation of future control actions in the field of VAT administration.</seg>
